<HEAD>Names In The News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY14</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RAPID CITY, S.D. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actor Kevin Costner says he's making his
debut as a director because he wants to make sure a frontier film
being shot in South Dakota this summer is done correctly.
   ``I take it very personally what this movie should be,'' Coster
said Wednesday, while touring the state for filming locations.
   Costner also will play the leading role in ``Dancing With
Wolves,'' which tells the story of Lt. John Dunbar, who is assigned
to a frontier post in the 1860s. Dunbar and an Indian man both go
through changes while learning to understand people of an
unfamiliar culture, an official of the film production company has
said.
   Hollywood studio officials and others in the film industry have
suggested many changes in the movie, Costner said. But he said as
director he wants to tell the story the way it should be told,
without making changes just to ensure the film is a financial
success.
   ``This is not so much a movie of how the West was won. It's more
about how it was lost,'' Costner said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When Tom Smothers reflects on his battles with
the CBS censors and the network's cancellation of his comedy show,
he can't help but smile.
   ``It hurt us a lot at the time, but I'd say CBS' firing us and
all the publicity we got from that probably added 20 or 30 years to
the life of the Smothers Brothers,'' said the elder Smothers in
May's McCall's.
   In the same article, brother Dick credited the team's longevity
to their continued close association despite ups and downs in their
other relationships.
   ``What I have with Tommy is a prior commitment. This is my
brother from the day I was born,'' he said. ``Tommy has been part
of my life with every person. He knows everything about me.''
   Agreed Tom: ``We are brothers first. If there's any anxiety
about me from the women in Dick's life, they put that on
themselves, because I'm No. 1 in his life.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actor Reginald Vel Johnson, who played the
police sergeant in the blockbuster movie ``Die Hard,'' has been
arrested for investigation of cocaine possession, authorities said.
   Johnson was arrested Tuesday night during a stakeout of an
alleged drug dealer's home, said Los Angeles County Sheriff's Sgt.
Terry Judge.
   He said deputies watched customers drive up, make a purchase and
drive away. Deputies followed the buyers until they were out of
sight, then stopped them and searched them for illegal drugs, he
said.
   Johnson was stopped and booked for investigation of possession
of cocaine and held in jail overnight. He was released Wednesday on
$2,500 bail, authorities said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Princess Anne and her husband, Mark Phillips, are
1,000 miles apart and are still silent on rumors of a rift in their
15-year marriage.
   The 38-year-old princess carried out a typically busy day of
public engagements Wednesday, starting with the opening of a body
scanning unit at Wycombe General Hospital and ending at a gala
premiere of the American movie ``Three Fugitives'' to benefit the
Save The Children Fund.
   Her 40-year-old husband left for Spain on Tuesday, and visited
the April fair in Seville on Wednesday.
   Royal Navy Commander Timothy Laurence, 34, whose letters to Anne
touched off the wave of speculation, remained out of sight
Wednesday at Windsor Castle where he was on duty as an aide to
Queen Elizabeth II.
   Rumors of trouble in the princess' marriage have circulated
since 1981. The latest round began Thursday when The Sun tabloid,
Britain's top-selling paper with a circulation of 4.2 million,
reported it had received four letters sent to Anne and stolen from
her briefcase.
   Buckingham Palace late Saturday identified the letter-writer as
Laurence after a Sunday paper said it would do so. On Tuesday, The
Sun quoted unidentified friends of Laurence's as saying he ``is
besotted with Princess Anne and believes she loves him, too.''
</TEXT>
