<FILEID>AP-NR-04-13-89 0219EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-PetDentistry     04-13 0593</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Pet Dentistry,0611</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dealing With Bad Breath In Dogs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LORI DODGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Is Fido's breath worse than his bite?
   If so, maybe it's time you learned about doggie dental hygiene,
says the new president of the American Veterinary Dental Society.
   ``It's a myth that dogs just get doggie breath,'' said Dr. Gary
Goldstein, whose organization has grown from 10 members in 1977 to
850 today.
   ``But if we get their teeth cleaned once a year and brushed
everyday they won't have doggie breath.''
   Goldstein, a veterinarian in Houston, was elected president of
the society at the start of this week's convention of the American
Animal Hospital Association.
   About 1,300 veterinarians are attending the conference to hear
lectures on topics such as anorexia in Angoras and pacemakers in
pugs. But pet dentistry, according to Goldstein, is the
fastest-growing veterinary care specialty.
   ``Dental problems in animals have been around for years,''
Goldstein said. ``We're now just recognizing that they're problems
that can be taken care of. Just about exactly the same thing that
can be done in human dentistry we can do in animal dentistry.''
   Preventive care includes a daily brushing of a pet's teeth with
a special brush and toothpaste and a professional cleaning and
checkup each year by a veterinarian. More extensive treatment can
even include braces.
   Many pet owners are not aware that Rover's bad breath may be
sign of a more serious problem, that he needs a root canal or has
an overbite that makes it difficult to chew properly.
   ``Ninety percent of all pets in the United States have some type
of dental disease,'' Goldstein said. ``When I work in the clinics,
it seems like every animal that comes in has some kind of dental
problem.''
   Nevertheless, Goldstein has had a problem getting people to take
pet dentistry seriously. Even his colleagues have been known to
chuckle.
   ``If the vets laugh and joke about it, then their clients will
laugh and joke about it and we're not getting anywhere,'' Goldstein
said. ``That's why we need to have meetings like this. If we can't
spread the word to vets, then certainly their clients aren't going
to be aware there's a problem.''
   Goldstein said the cost of dental treatments such as root
canals, crowns and orthodontics did not seem to deter pet owners
from getting the work done.
   ``One of the reasons it has blossomed is that animals now are
more companions than they are just pets,'' he said. ``We need to do
all we can do to accommodate these people who want the best for
their animals.''
   Goldstein's start in veterinarian dentistry began when he was
preparing to graduate from the University of Minnesota in 1984.
There had been no lectures on animal dentistry, and he noticed that
the veterinarians he worked with virtually ignored broken teeth and
other dental problems. So, noting that the trend in veterinary
medicine was toward specialization, he decided he had found his
niche.
   Goldstein does only pet dental work and says he's ``swamped.''
   About 90 percent of his work is on the mouths of dogs and cats,
but he has also been called out to the zoo to fill five cavities in
the mouth of a grizzly bear and to the University of Houston to do
three root canals on the school's mascot cougar.
   But promoting preventative dental care for pets is his primary
concern.
   ``If we can get them on a preventative dental program, we can
extend their lives by two or three years,'' Goldstein said.
</TEXT>
