<SECOND>AM-Deaths, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0844,0915</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES with Hoffman; Separate moved for AMs as a0749 on Robinson
and as a0411 on Hoffman.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Abbie Hoffman</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW HOPE, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Abbie Hoffman, a Chicago Seven radical who
founded the Yippie movement of the 1960s and wrote ``Revolution for
the Hell of It'' and ``Steal This Book,'' died Wednesday. He was 52.
   Hoffman rose to prominence with the Chicago Seven, a group of
radicals who stood trial on charges of conspiring to disrupt the
bloody 1968 Democratic National Convention in Chicago.
   The others of the Seven were Thomas Hayden, Jerry Rubin, David
Dellinger, Reynard C. Davis, Lee Weiner and John Froines.
   The 4{-month-long trial's theatrics featured wild-haired
defendants and a 74-year-old judge Julius Hoffman who ordered Bobby
Seale, a former Black Panther leader, bound and gagged in the
courtroom.
   Hoffman started the loosely organized Yippie movement, or Youth
International Party, in 1968 to bring together radicals to protest
the government and the Vietnam War.
   In addition to his earlier writings, he wrote ``Square Dancing
in the Ice Age: Underground Writings'' in 1982. His memoirs, ``Soon
to Be a Major Motion Picture,'' were published in 1980.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Ray Robinson</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CULVER CITY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sugar Ray Robinson, the
fast-punching, high-living boxing champion considered by many to be
the finest fighter in history, died Wednesday. He was 67.
   Robinson made his professional debut came in 1940 at Madison
Square Garden. In a career of more than 25 years, Robinson won the
welterweight championship once and the middleweight title five
times. He retired from boxing in 1965 with a record of 174-19-6 and
110 knockouts.
   Robinson won the vacant world welterweight title on Dec. 20,
1946 with a 15-round decision over Tommy Bell and never lost a
fight to a welterweight the rest of his career.
   Robinson won his first middleweight title, stopping Jake LaMotta
in the 13th round on Feb. 14, 1951 in Chicago. When he met LaMotta,
his record already was 119-1-2, and he was well on his way to
establishing a reputation so great that his nickname would be taken
by others hoping to be as good.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Matilda Clough</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTA MONICA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Matilda Clough, who humored the
stars of Ziegfeld's Follies and arranged the elephant collection of
her boss, Florenz Ziegfeld, died April 3 at age of 87.
   Ziegfeld hired Ms. Clough as his personal secretary. For $35 a
week, she kept such stars as Fanny Brice, Marion Davies, W.C.
Fields, Will Rogers, and Fred Astaire amused as they waited for
Ziegfeld to appear in his New York office.
   After Ziegfeld's death, Ms. Clough became a theater manager in
New York's Times Square. She later moved to Los Angeles with her
second husband. She became an assistant to the president of Radio
Recorders, a Hollywood studio.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>John Warner</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   John Christian Warner, president of Carnegie
Institute of Technology for 15 years and a chemist who supervised
research on the Manhattan atomic energy project during World War
II, died Wednesday. He was 91.
   Warner joined Carnegie Institute of Technology, now Carnegie
Mellon University, in 1926 as a chemistry instructor. He was head
of the chemistry department in 1938 and 1949 and dean of graduate
studies from 1945 to 1949.
   Warner became president of Carnegie Institute of Technology in
1950 after a year as vice president and president-elect of the
institution. His administration pioneered the use of computers in
education, establishing a computation center in 1956 that helped
the institution gain national recognition as a center of research
in computer science.
   During the last two years of World War II, Warner worked on the
Manhattan Project, supervising research on the chemistry and
metallurgy of plutonium. He was on the General Advisory Committee
to the U.S. Atomic Energy Commission for 12 years and also served
on the Policy Advisory Board of the Argonne National Laboratory.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Joe Towey</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Joe Towey, an emmy award-winning television
director who spooked and delighted thousands of Northwest viewers
as The Count of KIRO-TV's ``Nightmare Theater,'' died Sunday
following a lengthy illness. He was 55.
   Towey was a producer and director at KIRO for 30 years. He
directed the popular children's show ``J.P. Patches'' for 22 years
until the show left the air in 1981.
   Towey received two Emmys for directing that show and one for set
design for ``Nightmare Theater,'' a late-night show featuring
horror movies that he hosted.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Samuel Slaymaker</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LANCASTER, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Samuel R. Slaymaker, 66, a historian,
author and nationally recognized expert on fly fishing, died
Tuesday of natural causes. Slaymaker retired as executive vice
president of his family's business, Slaymaker Lock Co., in 1975
after 28 years with the firm. While still working, he moonlighted
as an outdoor writer, publishing two books on fly fishing and
writing articles for Sports Afield, Outdoor Life and Field and
Stream.
   After retiring from the lock company, Slaymaker devoted himself
to outdoor and historical writing and opened his home, White
Chimneys, to the public. The house is listed on the National
Register of Historic Places.
   Slaymaker was president general of the General Society of the
War of 1812 and was regarded as an authority on military history.
In addition, he wrote two books about his historic home, which has
been in the family for centuries.
</TEXT>
