<FIRST>r w PM-ConsumerCommission     04-13 0407</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Consumer Commission,410</SECOND>
<HEAD>Legislation Would Strengthen Safety Commission</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bill that would give more teeth to the
Consumer Product Safety Commission and let it do business at less
than full strength is making progress in a House committee but
faces business opposition.
   The bill, sent to the Energy and Commerce Committee on Wednesday
by a subcommittee, would specify a quorum of two when there are
only three members on the commission. It has the support of major
consumer groups.
   Currently, the commission has five authorized members and the
quorum is three. In recent years Congress has appropriated money
for only three salaries, so when there is a vacancy _ as there has
been since January _ the two remaining members can do nothing.
   Some Republicans on the commerce, consumer protection and
competitiveness subcommittee sought to sidetrack the bill,
sponsored by Chairman James Florio, D-N.J., in favor of an
amendment providing straightforward renewal of existing authority.
   ``This bill is opposed by every business group that has
commented on it,'' said Rep. Howard C. Nielson, R-Utah, sponsor of
the amendment, which was defeated 7-4 before the subcommittee's
voice-vote approval of Florio's measure.
   Nielson said Florio's bill was too cumbersome and had little
chance of passage.
   The bill would also:
   _Let consumers petition the commission for safety rules and
would require decisions on them within 120 days.
   _Let state attorneys general and certain other state officials
duplicate federal lawsuits brought by the commission.
   _Require reports, studies or decisions about the flammability of
sleepwear used by the elderly, standards for reclining chairs,
safety of cigarette lighters, indoor air pollution and age
requirements for operators of amusement park rides.
   A similar bill was approved by the subcommittee and the parent
committee last year, but action was too late in the session for
consideration by the House.
   The commission has been operating on year-to-year authority
granted in appropriations bills since 1983.
   Nielson said deaths from products under the commission's
jurisdiction fell from 26,000 in 1975 to 22,000 in 1984, and ``the
per capita decline has been more dramatic'' because the population
has grown. ``I don't think there is any evidence the commission is
not doing its job,'' he said.
   Supporting Florio, Rep. James C. Slattery, D-Kan., said, ``For
those people who don't think we need a vigorous CPSC, they ought to
spend an hour in a Toys 'R Us store with a child.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890413-0014 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-13-89 0241EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-FarmScene     04-13 0926</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Farm Scene,910</SECOND>
<HEAD>Activist Says Harvest too Poor to Support Exports</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A consumer advocate says the outlook for the
1989 harvest is so grim that the government should suspend export
subsidies despite their popularity with wheat farmers.
   Rodney E. Leonard, executive director of the private, non-profit
Community Nutrition Institute, said Wednesday he wrote Agriculture
Secretary Clayton Yeutter on April 3 to repeat a similar request
made last fall, ``when the situation was less precarious'' and
steps ``could have been taken to safeguard supplies.''
   The institute studies nutrition and food policy issues.
   The target of Leonard's complaint is the Export Enhancement
Program, or EEP, which subsidizes the sale of wheat and other
commodities to selected foreign countries. Huge sales of wheat to
China and the Soviet Union have been made under the program since
the arrangement was authorized by Congress in the 1985 farm law.
   Subsidies at one time ranged to more than $40 per metric ton, or
approximately $1.09 per bushel, from less than $20 per ton, or
about 54 cents per bushel. Lately, reflecting generally higher
world prices, the subsidies have been even lower, with shipments to
China recently carrying EEP subsidies of $6.33 per ton, or 17 cents
per bushel.
   A metric ton is about 2,205 pounds and is equal to 36.7 bushels
of wheat.
   Yeutter said this week the program had helped significantly in
getting agricultural trade discussions moving under the current
Uruguay Round of the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade.
   But Yeutter also said in an interview with a group of reporters
on Monday that the subsidy program would be reviewed to see how
effective it has been and whether ``too much or too little'' is
being spent on it.
   Leonard said that the condition of the winter wheat crop is
deteriorating and that experts in the Agriculture Department and in
the major production areas point to a harvest this year of about
1.6 billion bushels. A spring wheat output of 600 million bushels
would make a total U.S. wheat harvest of about 2.2 billion bushels.
   If wheat use in the 1989-90 marketing year, which will begin
June 1, totals in the range of 2.4 billion to 2.5 billion bushels,
this year's harvest would fall short of meeting demand.
   In that case, Leonard said in his letter to Yeutter, at least
200 million bushels of wheat will have to be drawn from existing
stocks, which are estimated by the Agriculture Department to be
drawn down to 549 million bushels by June 1.
   Thus, he said, the U.S. wheat stockpile by June 1, 1990, could
well be down to around 300 million bushels. According to department
records, that would be the the smallest U.S. wheat reserve at the
end of a marketing year since 1952, when it was 256 million bushels.
   ``This is hardly adequate as a domestic reserve, and will leave
the U.S. unable to intervene if famine conditions develop anywhere
in the world,'' Leonard said. ``The (United Nations) Food and
Agriculture Organization ... a month ago said that world grain
stocks will be drawn down again in 1989-90 for the third year in a
row.''
   Leonard added: ``In effect, FAO does not expect food grain
production to increase significantly in any of the major
food-producing areas outside the U.S.''
   The department's first official estimate of 1989 winter wheat
production, which usually accounts for three-fourths of the U.S.
total, will be released May 11.
   Meanwhile, department analysts have used unofficial projections
showing that the 1989 wheat harvest could be as low as 2.3 billion
bushels, or slightly more than Leonard's benchmark.
   The biggest problem is in major areas of the Great Plains,
particularly in Kansas, the No. 1 wheat producer, where soils have
been parched since the crop was planted last fall.
   Yeutter is scheduled to tour some of the Kansas wheat area on
Friday, his office said. There has been congressional pressure on
the department to extend 1988 drought relief to the stricken winter
wheat farmers.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New projections by the Agriculture Department
show the European Economic Community continues to push grain
exports aggressively, with shipments expected to be at a record
level this year.
   An analysis released Wednesday by the department's Foreign
Agricultural Service said EEC exports of wheat and coarse grains
such as barley and corn are expected to total 33.3 million metric
tons in 1988-89, up 39 percent from 23.9 million tons last year.
   The international trade years begin on July 1 for wheat and Oct.
1 for coarse grains. A metric ton is about 2,205 pounds and is
equal to 36.7 bushels of wheat or soybeans, or 39.5 bushels of corn.
   Wheat exports by the EEC are at a record 21 million tons, up
from 15.3 million in 1987-88.
   But the coarse grains, mostly barley, also have also grown,
forecast at 12.3 million tons against only 8.6 million tons last
year.
   ``Over the past seven years, subsidized barley exports by the
EEC have jumped by 150 percent,'' the report said. ``While EEC
barley exports comprised less than 30 percent of world barley trade
as recently as the early 1980s, their share is now almost 60
percent, a growth in exports that has come at least partially at
the expense of U.S. coarse grain market share.''
   The United States, the world's leading grain exporter, was
forecast to have total wheat and coarse grain shipments of 103.4
million tons in the current trade years, up from 96.9 million tons
in 1987-88, a 7 percent increase.
</TEXT>
