<FIRST>r i PM-Peru-Violence     04-13 0270</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Peru-Violence,0277</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rebels Kill 13 Peasants In Apparent Retaliation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HUANCAYO, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Maoist Shining Path guerrillas armed with
guns and machetes killed 12 peasants in an Andean village where
municipal officials had arrested three rebels, authorities said.
   In other violence, rebel assassins shot to death a leader of the
governing party's youth organization as he boarded a bus in this
highland capital, according to police.
   Abilio Fernandez, prefect of Junin state, told The Associated
Press that a band of Shining Path insurgents on Wednesday rounded
up 12 people in the town square of Chongos Alto, a hamlet of 100
peasant families 20 miles southwest of Huancayo, the Junin capital.
   He said the rebels killed the peasants by shooting them or
hacking them with machetes in apparent retaliation for the recent
capture of three Shining Path guerrillas by village officials.
   Police blamed the Shining Path for the assassination Tuesday of
Juan Torres, head of the Huancayo branch of the Peruvian Aprista
Youth.
   They said two gunmen had surprised Torres, 21, shooting him in
the head at a bus stop near his home in Huancayo, which is 140
miles east of Lima.
   The Shining Path has slain dozens of officials from the
center-left Aprista Party in its nine-year insurgency to topple the
elected government and impose Marxist rule.
   Huancayo, one of the nation's most important provincial
commercial centers, has become of major focus of insurgency
violence over the past three years.
   The government blames the Shining Path for more than 15,000
deaths. The guerrilla movement opposes Soviet and Chinese communism
and has no known ties to any other rebel group.
</TEXT>
