<FIRST>r w PM-DeathPenalty     04-13 0328</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Death Penalty,340</SECOND>
<HEAD>Death Penalty no Deterrent to Drug Dealers, Lawyer Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LISA M. HAMM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Attorney General Dick Thornburgh's
suggestion that prosecutors seek the death penalty in some
drug-related murders in the District of Columbia is ``ridiculous,''
the chief of the trial division of the Public Defenders Service
says.
   The death penalty would not deter drug dealers from pursuing
their lucrative but dangerous business, Mark Rochon said Wednesday.
   ``These guys are running around with death contracts on them and
they are still out hustling,'' Rochon said. ``The fact of the
matter is, these are people who have chosen to go into a
violence-prone way of living. And they (federal officials) think
two or three deaths a year is going to deter them? It would be
funny if it weren't so ridiculous.''
   A record 372 persons were killed in the city in 1988, and police
have said 80 percent of the deaths were drug-related. The district
is headed for another record total in 1989.
   Thornburgh on Monday said U.S. Attorney Jay Stephens has the
power to identify cases for federal prosecution under the new death
penalty statute enacted last fall as part of the 1988 Anti-Drug
Abuse Act. The bill allows the death penalty for the murder of a
law enforcement officer during narcotics trafficking and for
homicides committed by ``drug kingpins.''
   Metropolitan Police Department spokesman Walt Ferguson said
Police Chief Maurice Turner Jr., who in the past has expressed
support for the death penalty, is ``in the process of reviewing
statutes and other ins and outs of the legislation.''
   The D.C. Council struck the death penalty law from the city's
criminal code in 1980, joining 13 other states that forbid capital
punishment.
   Stephens said the death penalty would be employed in the
district ``only after very careful scrutiny and review.'' The
Justice Department is developing guidelines to screen cases in
which the death penalty might be sought, he said.
</TEXT>
