<FIRST>u a AM-PeoriaFire 5thLd-Writethru a0837 04-13 0731</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Peoria Fire, 5th Ld-Writethru, a0837,0749</SECOND>
<HEAD>Homeless Man Charged With Murder in Fire That Killed Nine</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after 7th, `Authorities said ..., to UPDATE with
newspaper report.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT LEE ZIMMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PEORIA, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A homeless man was charged Wednesday with
nine counts of murder after telling police he set a fire that swept
through an apartment house, killing seven children and two young
mothers, a prosecutor said.
   Joe Pickens, 34, who has no permanent address, was charged in
the Tuesday fire, the deadliest in the history of this central
Illinois city of about 130,000 people, said Peoria County State's
Attorney Kevin Lyons.
   Pickens was charged with criminal trespass, a misdemeanor, just
hours after fire.
   But Lyons said murder charges were lodged after Pickens
confessed to setting fire to a sleeper-sofa on the first floor,
igniting a fast-moving fire that swept up a stairwell to the second
floor where three families slept.
   ``Initially he claimed the fire was set accidentally,'' said
Police Chief Allen Andrews. ``He subsequently admitted he had
deliberately set the fire.''
   Following Pickens' brief court appearance, Circuit Judge Robert
Barnes set bond at $2 million and scheduled a hearing for May 5.
   Authorities said Pickens had been arrested several times on
misdemeanor vagrancy and criminal damage to property charges in
recent years.
   Pickens should have been in jail at the time the fire was set,
but had ignored a judge's order March 31 to begin serving a 30-day
sentence for resisting arrest _ his 22nd misdemeanor conviction
since 1983, the Peoria Journal-Star reported in Thursday's edition.
   Claudie Garner, who lives across the street from the burned
building, said she knew Pickens ``pretty well.''
   ``He'd get violent when he was under the influence of alcohol,''
she said. ``Otherwise he was a nice fellow.''
   Andrews said after Pickens set the fire, he went to the police
station and asked officers whether there were any outstanding
warrants for his arrest. After being told there were none, Pickens
simply left, Andrews said.
   Fire Chief G. John Parker had said Pickens apparently stayed at
the two-story wood-frame home in the past and ``was put out of the
house (Monday night), but he came back.''
   Parker said he did not know why Pickens had been forced to
leave, but said Pickens is believed to have left at 11 or 11:30
p.m. Monday, returned later and remained in the first-floor
apartment. The fire was reported at 2:20 a.m.
   The apartment had recently been vacated by Joyce Barnes, one of
three survivors of the blaze, and a daughter who died in the fire.
Authorities believe Ms. Barnes had moved in with the families
upstairs.
   ``Mr. Pickens made a statement that he set a fire downstairs and
we believe the evidence shows the facts are consistent with that
... and that he was aware residents were inside,'' Lyons said.
   Fire Department spokesman Greg Joos said a preliminary
investigation revealed the fire began near a space heater on the
first floor. He said electrical service in the downstairs apartment
had been shut off, but gas service was not. Joos also said the
landlord told authorities he had no idea that three families
apparently were living in the building.
   Joos said hard-wired smoke detectors had been installed on both
floors, but that Carl Wells, 29, who survived the blaze by climbing
on the roof with two others, said he did not hear an alarm.
   A memorial service was held for the victims at a community
center.
   And counseling was made available to children at the elementary
school attended by several of the children killed in the fire, and
similar help would be offered to firefighters.
   ``Traditionally, these are pretty macho guys and they may not
seem outwardly affected. But a few were really hurt by hearing
screaming kids and not being able to help,'' he said.
   Coroner Herbert Buzbee said the nine victims died of smoke
inhalation.
   The victims were Terry Davis, 27, and three of her children,
Arnisha Davis, 7, Karlissa Davis, 2, and Tanoa Davis, 10; Davis'
sister, Wanda Hobbs, 20, and her children, Felicia Hobbs, 4, and
Ashley Hobbs, 1; and Eugene Roberts Jr., two months; and Jacolby
Thomas, 2, the daughter of 30-year-old Ms. Barnes, who survived.
   Barnes and 14-year-old Eric Davis, son of Terry Davis, were in
fair condition at Franciscan Medical Center in Rock Island.
</TEXT>
