<FIRST>r i PM-Guyana-Strikes     04-13 0325</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Guyana-Strikes,0334</SECOND>
<HEAD>Protests Convulse Guyana's Capital Over Austerity Measures</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GEORGETOWN, Guyana (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three hundred department store workers
were fired for their one-day walkout in support of a two-week-old
strike by bauxite and sugar workers who are protesting
government-mandated austerity measures.
   The measures imposed on this English-speaking country of 750,000
on the northeast coast of South America included a 230 percent
devaluation of Guyana's dollar and the doubling of interest rates
to 35 percent.
   The measures were adopted by the government of President Desmond
Hoyte to meet conditions set by the International Monetary Fund for
a $1.9 billion aid package to revive the country's economy, which
hasn't grown in 10 years.
   Fourteen protesters, including two Jesuit priests jailed Tuesday
for picketing outside Parliament buildings, were released Wednesday
by police. The arrests brought to 100 the number of people jailed
for demonstrating against the measures since Hoyte announced them
on March 31.
   While there has been no violence in the protests, about 300
department store workers who paralyzed the capital's commercial
sector by staging a one-day walkout Tuesday were fired when they
returned to work Wednesday, authorities said.
   The strike by 5,000 bauxite workers, 20,000 sugar workers and
800 university employees, including professors, entered its second
week. Sugar and bauxite, which is used to make aluminum, are among
the country's main exports.
   Government spokesman Christopher Nascimento said union leaders
calling for strikes were hurting themselves because ``in attempting
to bring the economy to a halt, they will not hurt the government
but the nation as a whole.''
   With the measures, Guyana's dollar officially fell to 33 to the
U.S. dollar, although it fetches up to 50 to a U.S. dollar in the
black market.
   Prices, already high before the measures, have soared. A loaf of
bread costs about $5.
   The government tried to offset the devaluation with a 20 percent
wage increase but union leaders say that will not make a difference
in workers' paychecks.
</TEXT>
