<FIRST>r w PM-SocialSecurity-Hardy     04-13 0648</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Social Security-Hardy,650</SECOND>
<HEAD>Administration Moves to Replace Head of Social Security</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BARKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Government sources say the Bush administration
may replace Social Security Commissioner Dorcas R. Hardy, a Reagan
appointee whose travel and hiring records are being scrutinized by
congressional critics.
   Sources in the Bush administration and on Capitol Hill said
Wednesday that the administration is seriously considering
replacing Hardy with Gwendolyn King, a former legislative aide to
Sen. John Heinz, R-Pa. King has also headed the Washington office
of Attorney General Dick Thornburgh when he was governor of
Pennsylvania.
   None of the sources would be identified by name.
   Reached at the government relations firm of Gogol &amp; Associates,
where she is executive vice president, King said: ``I will be
pleased to serve wherever the president needs me.'' She declined to
discuss the Social Security post.
   Hardy, 42, worked for Ronald Reagan on welfare issues when he
was governor of California, and was a health and human services
assistant secretary during his first presidential term before being
named to run Social Security in 1986.
   Although Bush took office Jan. 20, Hardy has not yet been told
whether she will be retained, according to agency spokesman Phil
Gambino.
   Like all political appointees from the Reagan administration,
she was asked to submit her resignation after Bush became
president, ``but it has not been accepted,'' Gambino said.
   As the administration deliberates on a successor, a House panel
has been looking both into Hardy's travel and her hiring of a
handful of former political appointees as consultants.
   It was not clear whether the investigation was a factor in the
administration's decision to seek a replacement for Hardy.
   In the last three weeks, Health and Human Services Secretary
Louis Sullivan has received two letters from a House Government
Operations subcommittee as part of an inquiry into whether Hardy
combined business trips with vacations or political travel. The
subcommittee declined to release the letters.
   Hardy declined several requests to be interviewed.
   However, Gambino said: ``In the 13 years since I've been here,
three other commissioners have been asked for travel information.
It's not unusual.''
   He said Hardy's job frequently required travel, and not always
in the United States. Last summer, for example, he said Hardy was
asked by the State Department to brief officials in China on
America's Social Security system, and that she stopped in Hawaii
for 24 hours as a ``natural progression.''
   HHS has turned down a few trips proposed by Hardy, according to
Tom Burke, a private consultant who was chief of staff under former
Secretary Otis R. Bowen. However, Burke said: ``Lots of people got
their trips turned down. We just questioned the need for them.
She's not at the top of the list.''
   The subcommittee has also been looking at four or five SSA
employees who were immediately rehired as consultants by Hardy
after the administration asked them to step down because they were
political appointees.
   Rep. Ted Weiss, D-N.Y., the subcommittee chairman, has been a
frequent critic of Hardy. Most recently, he accused the Social
Security agency in December of failing to speedily implement a law
requiring it to help homeless people receive benefit checks.
   Hardy's efforts to trim the agency through computerization and
staff cuts brought periodic protests from Capitol Hill. Lawmakers
have expressed concern about the cuts in view of the increased
caseloads brought on by new tax and immigration laws.
   On Monday, Hardy's program to implement a national telephone
number to field Social Security questions was criticized by two
federal employee groups, which said she created ``sweatshop
conditions'' for workers and was insensitive to callers' needs.
   Hardy said the system was still being smoothed out and that it
would ultimately make the agency more accessible to millions of
Americans. She has said automation may be trying for some
employees, but that it makes the agency more efficient.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
