<DOCNO> AP890413-0024 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-13-89 0239EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Japan-Politics     04-13 0810</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Politics,0834</SECOND>
<HEAD>Takeshita's Leadership Facing Unprecedented Crisis</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Thursday AMs report.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ERIC TALMADGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Politicians battling to regain the public's trust
as scandal rages around them are frequently quoting an old Japanese
saying: The next step ahead is darkness.
   Never in the Liberal Democratic Party's 34-year rule has the
popularity of its leader fallen so low, and never have so many of
its elite been accused of dirty dealing.
   But in the crisis, Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita is displaying
a surprising ability to survive.
   Takeshita, 65, has rejected opposition demands to step down, and
top Liberal Democrats refuse to submit former Prime Minister
Yasuhiro Nakasone to questioning under oath in Parliament.
   Instead, they have focused on bringing about ethical reforms and
resuming deliberations on the fiscal 1989 budget. The opposition
has boycotted the budget talks since March 8.
   That battle will come to a head later this month, when fiscal
deadlines must be met, but party Secretary-General Shintaro Abe
already has suggested the conservatives will use their majority in
both houses to simply force the budget through _ a move bound to
spark criticism in consensus-conscious Japan.
   ``Very few members of the ruling party say Takeshita should be
dumped before the budget is passed,'' said analyst Asao Yamaguchi.
``But afterward, the wind will blow in the other direction.''
   Yamaguchi said that by unilaterally passing the budget,
Takeshita would be left with no other political choice than to
dissolve the lower house and call elections this summer, when
polling for half the seats in the upper house is scheduled. A loss
at the polls then would likely end his administration.
   Behind the conservatives' dilemma is the Recruit Co., a huge
publishing conglomerate. Recruit sold unlisted shares in a
real-estate subsidiary to about 160 political, business and
government officials at low prices in 1986. The buyers received
handsome profits when the shares soared in value shortly after they
were listed on the market.
   In all, 14 people have been arrested on bribery and other
charges and three Takeshita-appointed Cabinet ministers have
resigned in connection with the scandal.
   Along with Takeshita, Abe and Nakasone, former Finance Minister
Kiichi Miyazawa and Michio Watanabe, pegged as a future party
leader, all have been implicated in Recruit share transactions.
   On Tuesday, Takeshita went before a special session of the lower
house Budget Committee to acknowledge that from 1985 to 1987, he
received about $1 million in donations from Recruit and its
subsidiaries.
   The admission was an attempt to clear his name _ he claimed the
donations were all legal _ and was hailed by party leaders.
   But Takeshita, whose support in recent public opinion polls has
fallen below 10 percent, faces other problems.
   His pet project, a controversial new 3 percent sales tax, went
into effect April 1, raising consumer prices in a nation that
already has one of the world's highest costs of living.
Liberalization of agricultural imports has alienated some farmers,
one of the conservatives' main support groups.
   ``There are many voices within the party calling for the top
leader to be replaced,'' said Keiichiro Nakamura, a former aide to
the late Prime Minister Takeo Miki.
   Nakamura told The Associated Press the critics are still a
minority, but ``with elections this summer drawing near, more and
more members of the party are realizing that with Takeshita as
their leader, they will not be able to be re-elected.''
   He said Takeshita's successor must be Recruit-clean, and, with
heads of major factions linked to the scandal, the most likely
candidate is Masayoshi Ito, 75, chairman of the party's Executive
Council.
   Other analysts speculate that former Prime Minister Takeo
Fukuda, 84, whose protege is Abe, may succeed Takeshita. Even
Takeshita mentor Shin Kanemaru, 74, has been mentioned as a
possible heir.
   All are thought of as interim prime ministers who would hold the
reins only until a new, younger leader could be found.
   ``This is the most important political crossroads since the end
of World War II,'' said Takako Doi, head of the largest opposition
party, the Socialists.
   But opposition parties are far apart on policy and they also
have been tarred by the Recruit scandal.
   The former head of the Democratic Socialist Party said he would
not seek re-election after being linked to the affair; a Socialist
legislator has resigned; and a former deputy secretary-general of
the Komeito, or Clean Government Party, has acknowledged his
brother bought shares.
   There is speculation that rebels might leave the Liberal
Democrats and form a new party. One restive group of party hawks,
headed by legislator Shizuka Kamei, has demanded the resignation of
all politicians who received Recruit funds.
   But analyst Yamaguchi said such a breakaway would never happen.
``It takes money to form a new party, and very few people are
willing to contribute in times like these,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
