<FILEID>AP-NR-04-13-89 0234EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-TaxReturns     04-13 0582</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Tax Returns,560</SECOND>
<HEAD>IRS Boosts Phone-Line Staff for Filing Deadline Crunch</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LUTHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Tax Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If you are among the millions of taxpayers
delaying the inevitable, the Internal Revenue Service is offering a
little extra help to get you through the final weekend of the tax
filing season.
   The agency is making many of its employees available extra hours
on Saturday and Monday _ the filing deadline _ to answer calls on
its toll-free telephone lines. The lines will be open five hours on
Saturday and an extra two hours, until 7 p.m., on Monday.
   In addition, IRS offices nationwide that offer assistance to
taxpayers who walk in will not close Monday night until the last
customer has been served.
   The IRS is expecting more than 25 million returns _ out of the
109 million due this year _ to be filed during the 16 days ending
Monday night, and the agency is cautioning procrastinators against
careless errors.
   ``Being careful now can help you avoid common mistakes made in a
last-minute rush which could delay processing your return or hold
up your refund,'' the agency said Wednesday.
   Such careless mistakes have shown up on hundreds of thousands of
returns already this year. The most common: failing to sign the
return; non-itemizers neglecting to claim a standard deduction;
students failing to state whether they can be claimed as a
dependent by a parent; writing down the wrong tax liability from
the tax tables, and basic mathematical mistakes.
   In some cases, such as errors in math, IRS computers catch the
mistakes and correct them. Others, such as failing to sign the
return, require an exchange of letters between IRS and taxpayer
before the return can be processed and a refund mailed.
   The IRS anticipates that about 6 million couples and individuals
will avoid the last-minute rush by taking an automatic four-month
extension of the filing deadline. That option is available by
filing a Form 4868.
   However, that only delays filing, not paying any tax due. The
form must be accompanied by a check for the estimated tax due.
   Through Friday, the IRS had received almost 64.7 million
returns. That is 0.3 percent above the 64.5 million received during
the same period a year ago.
   Almost 53.3 million returns have been processed this year, up
almost 1 percent. The inventory of unprocessed returns is 11.4
million, compared with 11.7 million last year. Many in that
inventory are those that do not qualify for a refund; the IRS
processes refund returns first to avoid paying interest on late
refunds.
   So far this season, the IRS has certified 42.1 million refunds,
up 1.8 percent from almost 41.4 million at this time in 1988. This
year's refunds have totaled $34.7 billion, compared with $34.3
billion last year. The average refund is $824, down from $830 last
year.
   In addition to offering extra hours for telephone assistance
this weekend, the IRS said programs that use volunteers to help the
elderly and others fill out returns will stay open late. Locations
of the Volunteer Income Tax Assistance and Tax Counseling for the
Elderly projects are available by calling the IRS toll-free
telephone number.
   Those numbers are listed in the instructions that accompany
individual tax forms, as are separate numbers for the Tele-Tax
system.
   The Tele-Tax number also is the one to call for information on a
refund, if you filed a return at least eight weeks ago and have not
yet received a refund.
</TEXT>
