<FIRST>r w PM-Guard-Computers     04-13 0508</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Guard-Computers,500</SECOND>
<HEAD>Guard Computers Like `Missiles Without Guidance Systems'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA CASSATA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Computers purchased by the National Guard
under a 1986 contract remain useless because they lack the
necessary software and probably won't be in full working order
until 1991, a House subcommittee was told.
   The Army National Guard Bureau bought 119 Unisys 5000
minicomputers, about 5,000 terminals and hundreds of printers and
other equipment but failed to obtain the programs, data and other
routines, investigators told the House Energy and Commerce
subcommittee on oversight and investigations.
   The bureau opted for the Unisys system, believing that their
Burroughs 1900s system would be obsolete by 1986. But Guard units
in 54 states and territories are still using the Burroughs 1900s.
   Lt. Gen. Herbert R. Temple Jr., chief of the National Guard
Bureau, and Maj. Gen. Donald Burdick, director of the Army National
Guard, estimated Wednesday that the first software package should
be ready by April 1990 and the Unisys system should be operating by
1991.
   ``Validation of software systems is currently under way,''
Temple and Burdick said in a joint statement. ``It is our intention
to fully utilize this equipment.''
   Meanwhile, the computers remain idle with the staff occasionally
opening boxes to see if they still run or using them ``for games
like tick-tack-toe,'' said Richard Chervenak, a subcommittee
investigator who visited eight states that purchased the computers.
   ``In military terms, this would be analogous to buying missiles
without guidance systems, troop carriers that do not protect troops
and attack helicopters without engines,'' said Rep. John Dingell,
D-Mich., chairman of the House subcommittee.
   Staff investigators from the subcommittee, who have been looking
since July 1988 into allegations of irregularities, testified that
some states have threatened to develop their own software for the
Unisys computers. The Bureau's Information Management Agency warned
against that step, expressing concerns about possible
incompatibilty of the locally developed software and the software
being developed for the system.
   ``Computer experts in the Army have told us that it is
unthinkable to purchase computer hardware without knowing that the
software in available,'' Chervenak said. ``They stated that the
federal government purchases computers and software routinely and
could not understand how the bureau could make such a fundamental
mistake.''
   Dingell said the investigation found no irregularities by Unisys
but numerous problems with the bureau's handling of the
procurement, including misuse of an expedited contract and probable
violations of procurement regulations.
   According to estimates, the Guard will spend between $30 million
and $40 million to replace its computer system, Dingell said.
   Dingell said that Guard and state officials told subcommittee
staff that Fred Trent, a civilian employee of the bureau, was
largely to blame for the procurement irregularities. But Trent died
in 1986, more than a year before the Guard purchased the computers.
   ``In addition to being reprehensible, blaming the dead for one's
own mistakes fits an all too familiar Pentagon pattern,'' Dingell
said. ``For example, blaming the pilots shot down in the raid on
Libya for bombing the French Embassy there.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
