<FILEID>AP-NR-04-13-89 0232EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Bush-Disabled     04-13 0671</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush-Disabled,660</SECOND>
<HEAD>Disabled-Rights Groups Say Bush Broke Campaign Promise</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After being courted by President Bush in last
fall's campaign, groups representing disabled Americans are angry
at the administration's appeal of a court ruling requiring
wheelchair lifts on new buses.
   The accusations that Bush broke campaign promises are prompted
by the administration's request this week that an appellate court
review its Feb. 13 ruling that mandated installation of wheelchair
lifts on new buses bought with federal money
   ``Most of us feel as if he has sold us out, that we were used,''
said Marca Bristo, president of the Chicago-based National Council
on Independent Living. ``This was an opportunity for him to take a
clear and decisive leadership role on probably the most passionate
issue that faces the disabled community _ public transportation.''
   Advocacy groups for the disabled say the legal maneuver doesn't
square with Bush's campaign rhetoric and his State of the Union
pronouncement that handicapped people ``belong in the economic
mainstream.''
   ``We need your talents in America's workforce. Disabled
Americans must become full partners in America's opportunity
society,'' Bush said during his address to Congress on Feb. 9.
   Disabled rights lobbyists say Bush won many votes by endorsing
legislation last fall that would do exactly what the court decision
mandates _ require that wheelchair lifts be installed in buses
purchased by local transit companies with federal funds.
   The request for a rehearing of the ruling by the full 3rd U.S.
Circuit Court of Appeals in Philadelphia was filed Monday despite
pleas to Transportation Secretary Samuel Skinner and White House
Counsel Boyden Gray by the disabled-rights groups at meetings last
week.
   Gray was described as sympathetic and Skinner promised on Friday
to review the appeal, which was originally planned to be filed that
day, Bristo said.
   Skinner told the group that he was not concerned about the cost
of installing wheelchair lifts as much as court interference with
his agency's discretion in promulgating regulations.
   The petition for rehearing also was submitted despite
recommendations by three federal agencies _ the National Council on
the Handicapped, the President's Committee on Employment of People
with Disabilities and the U.S. Architectural and Transportation
Barriers Compliance Board.
   In a Feb. 27 letter to Bush, the chairman of the employment
advisory committee, Harold Russell, told the president that the
court ruling ``would be entirely consistent'' with his stated goal
of helping disabled Americans get more job opportunities.
   Tim Cook, an attorney with the National Disability Action
Center, which is representing the plaintiffs in the bus lawsuit,
said that ``for the administration to now renege on that promise
and seek to overturn this case is not being well accepted by the
disability community.''
   The 3rd Circuit set aside regulations that allowed local transit
to demand 24-hour notice from the handicapped that special services
would be needed. It also struck down a provision of the regulation
that said transit authorities would be considered in compliance
with disability rights policy if they spent 3 percent of their
operating expenses on improving access for the handicapped.
   The decision was seen by disabled people as a landmark ruling in
their quest for access to public transportation, Cook said.
   ``The major reason that people with disabilities are unemployed
is the lack of lack of decent public transportation,'' Cook said.
``If you can't get to the job or the training you are going to sit
at home.''
   Spokesmen for the White House and the Transportation Department
did not return telephone calls on the subject Wednesday.
   The administration's legal brief filed by the Justice Department
contended that the 3rd Circuit decision would cost local transit
authorities $270 million a year to provide wheelchair lifts on
buses.
   The Justice Department contends that federal laws ``do not
require this wholesale restructuring of mass transit services or
the imposition of the attendant financial burdens on an already
overburdened public transportation system.''
   It also said such policy decisions should be left to the
Transportation Department, not made by the courts.
</TEXT>
