<FIRST>r w PM-BaseClosings     04-13 0519</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Base Closings,520</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lawmakers Facing Lost Bases Criticize Closing List</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA CASSATA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lawmakers facing the loss of military bases in
their home states claim a federal commission's list of
installations recommended for closure should be rejected because it
is based on erroneous information.
   ``The commission's report and recommendations are flawed,'' Rep.
Ed Madigan, R-Ill., said Wednesday during consideration of a House
resolution to disapprove the suggestions of the Commission on Base
Realignment and Closure.
   The panel recommended last December closing 86 bases, partly
closing five others and changing the mission of 54 other
installations at an estimated savings of $694 million a year, with
20-year savings estimated at $5.6 billion.
   Former Defense Secretary Frank C. Carlucci approved the
recommendations and the House Armed Services Committee voted 43-4
to support the commission's decision.
   The full House, which is scheduled to vote on the resolution
next Tuesday, is expected to follow the committee's action.
According to law, the commission's recommendations must be accepted
in their entirety, and if the resolution of disapproval fails, the
plan will go into effect next month. Base closings will then begin
in 1990.
   ``I hear the pain of many members whose bases will be closed in
their districts,'' said Rep. Pat Schroeder, D-Colo., as debate got
under way on the House floor. ``That is the bill the House voted
for,'' she said, referring to the legislation setting up the
commission.
   Representatives from New Jersey, Illinois and California as well
as other states acknowledged that they will likely lose the fight
but expressed concerns over the commission's methodology and its
recommendations.
   Congressmen cited a General Accounting Office report released
Wednesday that found that the commission ``may have made its
recommendations for realignments and closures based on incomplete
and inaccurate data.''
   The GAO, Congress' investigative arm, said the commission used
erroneous data in its analysis of Army training centers, including
Fort Dix in New Jersey. The agency also found errors in the data
and weaknesses in the methodology in the analysis of Air Force
technical training bases, including Chanute Air Force Base in
Illinois.
   But Frank Conahan of the GAO said that ``some of the data used
by the commission that had been questioned were, in fact, correct.''
   ``I need to emphasize that the issues I have discussed and
questions I have raised about the commission's work are not
intended at this point to imply disagreement with the commission's
overall conclusions,'' Conahan said.
   Rep. Christopher Smith, R-N.J., said he found it ``highly
disturbing that the GAO office, in findings released today, used
faulty information.''
   Rep. Jim Courter, R-N.J., said most of the savings cited by the
commission would come from reductions in troop strength. In
addition, the commission's decision to close a number of bases,
including Fort Dix in New Jersey, was based on ``incorrect
information and clerical error,'' he contended.
   Madigan said no member of the commission or its staff visited
the Chanute Air Force Base in Illinois, and charged that the panel
made its decision based on ``inaccurate information and will not
achieve the allege cost savings.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
