<FILEID>AP-NR-04-13-89 0322EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-US-Germany     04-13 0541</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Germany,540</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ambassador-designate Says Questionable German Exports Key Issue</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALEXANDER G. HIGGINS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush's choice to be U.S. ambassador
to West Germany says a central point of his job will be pressing
the Bonn government to curb exports of chemical weapons and other
military technology to the Third World.
   Vernon Walters, praised by the Democratic and Republican members
of the Senate Foreign Relations Committee, is certain of winning
confirmation from the full Senate, said Democratic Senator Joseph
Biden, chairman of the subcommittee on European affairs.
   ``One of the things the Germans look for ... is how well we
respect them by who we send them, and it's obvious (by the choice
of Walters that) we respect them a great deal,'' said Biden.
   ``I can think of no other relationship that is more important
today to the United States and to the West than the German-American
tie,'' Walters told the panel.
   ``The Federal Republic of Germany stands at the center of
East-West relations,'' he said. ``The West German public is the
main target of (Soviet) General Secretary Gorbachev's `charm
offensive' precisely because the Federal Republic is so important
to the alliance.''
   Recent U.S. differences with Bonn, such as problems over exports
and modernization of German-based U.S. nuclear missiles, are
inevitable in such a close relationship, he said.
   The differences ``reflect the very importance, variety and
intensity of our ties and our respective interests, rather than
fundamental differences,'' Walters said.
   Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C., cited West German press reports of a
range of sales of chemical, nuclear and missile technology to
countries such as Iraq and Libya.
   Helms, a sponsor of legislation that would impose sanctions on
German companies involved in the exports, said the West German
government had ignored U.S. diplomatic objections to the exports as
well as warnings from its own investigative agency.
   The United States has made more than 150 diplomatic
representations to the West German government over the past eight
years concerning ``improper exports'' to Libya, Iran, Iraq, Syria
and South Asia, Helms said.
   ``Since all of these areas continue to receive German equipment
and technology in the face of our diplomatic efforts, I guess we
ought to be sort of ashamed of our diplomatic results,'' he said.
   ``This will be a central problem for me, senator,'' said
Walters. ``You have mentioned the unsuccessful representations. I
will do my best to see they are more successful in the future.''
   The senators from both parties took turns in praising Walters,
71, for his long career of government service, starting with the
Army in 1941. He rose to the rank of lieutenant general and served
directly under presidents starting with Harry Truman. He was an
interpreter for President Dwight Eisenhower on his foreign trips
during the 1950s.
   Biden said he would be the first U.S. ambassador in two decades
to go to Bonn being able to speak German. A linguist, Walters also
speaks French, Spanish, Portuguese, Italian, Dutch and Russian.
   His diplomatic posts have included being a military attache in
Italy, Brazil and France, and he was involved in negotiations with
the North Vietnamese and Chinese in Paris from 1969 to 1972.
   He has been U.S. ambassador to the United Nations since 1985.
</TEXT>
