<FILEID>AP-NR-04-13-89 0322EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Hastings     04-13 0541</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hastings,540</SECOND>
<HEAD>Investigative Files Won't Save Impeached Judge, Lawmaker Declares</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Investigative files and other documents being
sought by impeached federal Judge Alcee L. Hastings from a
congressional panel contain nothing that will help him remain on
the bench, a key lawmaker says.
   ``He knows very well that we have no documents that exonerate
the defendant,'' Rep. John Bryant, D-Texas, said Wednesday. ``If we
did, why on earth would we be here? We have had no desire to spend
the last three years working on this matter.''
   Hastings, 52, is accused of plotting to get a bribe in 1981 and
lying about it two years later before a jury that eventually
acquitted him.
   Impeachment articles that the House approved 413-3 on Aug. 3
also accuse him in an unrelated matter of improperly divulging
secret wiretap information.
   The Senate must now decide whether to remove him from the bench
and stop payment of his $89,500 salary.
   Bryant told a 12-member Senate committee reviewing evidence
against Hastings that it should reject a defense plea for documents
and a 180-day delay to allow for questioning a lengthy list of
potential witnesses, including U.S. Chief Justice William Rehnquist.
   Bryant said the House committee that prepared the impeachment
articles has already given the defense many documents and offered
access to others. He said it was unreasonable to demand ``every
single document we ever reviewed.''
   Rep. George W. Gekas, R-Pa., also urged the senators to head off
questioning of such potential witnesses as Rehnquist. ``We find
that all of this evidence, that none of it is relevant to the facts
that must be presented to this committee,'' Gekas said.
   Defense attorneys are trying to get government-paid expenses
totaling $200,000 plus fees that could add up to as much as
$750,000. House prosecutors have taken no position on that request.
   Hastings attorney Terence J. Anderson said that as a law
professor, he could afford to take the summer off to work on the
impeachment case. But he said that without government funding
co-counsel Patricia Williams would be ``committing economic
suicide'' to stay with the case to the neglect of her law practice.
   The panel's chairman, Sen. Jeff Bingaman, D-N.M., told reporters
it would probably announce its decision on the requests later this
week. But Anderson said the mood of the senators appeared less than
encouraging.
   ``I felt an awful lot like the train is continuing to run down
the track,'' he said after the session.
   Sen. Arlen Specter, R-Pa., expressed misgivings about the
request for taxpayers funds to finance the legal battle.
   ``You're making an unprecedented request for compensation which,
just speaking for myself, I don't think you're going to have
available,'' he said.
   According to the defense, Hastings knew nothing of any plot.
   Washington attorney William Borders, a friend and one-time
classmate of Hastings, was convicted of conspiring to shake down
two defendants sentenced to prison by Hastings. The idea was that a
$150,000 payment would get the punishment changed to probation.
   Arrested after accepting a cash-stuffed garment bag from an
undercover agent, Borders eventually was sent to prison.
   Throughout the affair, however, Borders was merely ``blowing
smoke,'' according to Anderson. He says Hastings was simply not
involved.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
