<FIRST>r w PM-WhiteHouse-Taxes     04-13 0502</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-White House-Taxes,480</SECOND>
<HEAD>Quayle Got Sizeable Speaking Fees</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dan Quayle earned over $50,000 in speaking
fees as a member of the Senate last year before he accepted the
Republican vice presidential nomination.
   In so doing, Quayle got roughly $17,000 more than senators are
allowed to accept in speaking honoraria. But he gave the excess
fees to charity and deducted the contributions on his 1988 tax
form, thus complying with the honoraria limit.
   This transaction was made public Wednesday as Quayle's office
released his tax returns simultaneously with the White House's
release of President Bush's tax forms.
   Bush earned $155,662 last year from business holdings kept in a
blind trust, well above the $115,000 salary he drew from the
government as vice president. He and his wife, Barbara, reported an
adjusted gross income of $287,171.
   That was based on Bush's $155,662 in interest-and-dividend
earnings through partnerships and other interests, masked by the
blind trust, plus his government salary. Also included was $7,147
in other interest along with $12,362 in income from other sources,
primarily profits that Bush made from his partnership in a firm
that leased a liquefied natural gas transportation barge in
Louisiana.
   When his 1988 federal tax liability of $62,106 was deducted from
the $94,884 total in money withheld or prepaid, Bush had overpaid
by $32,778. White House press secretary Marlin Fitzwater said he
applied $15,000 to next year's tax liability and kept the remaining
$17,778.
   Estimates on Bush's net worth have varied substantially,
although records show that the president, who made the bulk of his
money as an oil entrepreneur in Texas, has assets worth well over
$2 million.
   Fitzwater said he thought that reports of Bush's wealth ``are
vastly overestimated. Most of his net worth is in the Kennebunkport
(Maine) estate.''
   The Quayles, who records show hold assets worth more than $1.4
million, reported an adjusted gross income of $156,546 last year,
the bulk of that coming from Quayle's $89,500 Senate salary.
   Quayle listed charitable contributions totaling $17,304, or just
a little more than the $16,997 in speaking fees that he could not
keep for himself.
   The vice president's press secretary, Dave Beckwith, said Quayle
had written off the excess speaker's fees in an appropriate fashion.
   ``He earned more in honoraria than he's allowed to keep, so he
gave all the excess to charity,'' Beckwith said.
   The spokesman said Quayle gained no tax advantage by writing off
the extra speaking fees as charitable contributions, saying ``you
have (approximately) $17,000 more in income and $17,000 more in
deductions, so it's a wash.''
   Quayle earned all his speaking fees before August, when the
Republican Party nominated him to be Bush's vice presidential
running mate.
   The balance of his $156,546 income came from interest, dividends
and capital gains relating to his family's Central Newspapers, Inc.
Quayle also made $2,000 as a director of Central Newspapers _ a
position he would have to relinquish under ethics legislation that
Bush proposed to Congress Thursday.
</TEXT>
