<FIRST>r w PM-StateDepartment     04-13 0368</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-State Department,370</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Authorizes Spending for International Affairs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIANE DUSTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House has authorized the State Department
and other government international agencies to spend $4.6 billion
next fiscal year, $257 million less than President Bush wanted.
   The House, by a 338-87 vote, approved the measure Wednesday
authorizing a wide range of expenditures with cuts in many areas of
the administration's proposal.
   However, the amount is still $512 million more than fiscal 1989,
primarily because of:
   _restoration of U.S. contributions to the United Nations that
were withheld in 1985 as a way to pressure the U.N. for budget
reforms;
   _the expense of new U.N. peacekeeping efforts in the Persian
Gulf, Namibia and Angola;
   _construction of a new radio transmitter in Israel to improve
U.S. broadcasting to the Soviet Union; and
   _television Marti, a new broadcast service to Cuba.
   As an authorization bill, the measure does not directly result
in spending. In many cases, Congress does not appropriate the full
amounts authorized.
   The House voted $25 million for the National Endowment for
Democracy, an organization that awards grants to private
organizations to promote democracy and pluralism. That is $9.2
million more than Bush requested.
   An amendment offered by Rep. Paul Kanjorski, D-Pa., would have
brought the amount down to the $15.8 million sought by the
administration, but failed on a 216-209 vote.
   The bill authorizes $412 million for migration and refugee
assistance, $32 million more than Bush wanted. The Foreign Affairs
Committee said it raised the amount because of a recent increase in
refugees, particularly from the Soviet Union and Southeast Asia.
   The bill also authorizes $100 million in additional funds for
fiscal 1989 to assist Soviet citizens moving to the United States
and for African and Southeast Asian refugees.
   The House approved an amendment to the measure that would
withhold the U.S. contribution to U.N. peacekeeping activity in
Angola unless all Cuban troops are withdrawn from that country
according to the stipulations of the Tripartite Agreement.
   The bill also authorizes $4.96 billion for 1991 for the State
Department and related agencies.
   Those agencies are the U.S. Information Agency, the Board for
International Broadcasting, the Inter-American Foundation and the
Asia Foundation.
</TEXT>
