<FIRST>r w PM-Lujan-Exxon     04-13 0408</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lujan-Exxon,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lujan Says Company Not Forthcoming With Cleanup Money</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Exxon Corp. has yet to open its checkbook
despite promises by the giant energy company to atone for the
massive oil spill off Alaska's coast, Interior Secretary Manuel
Lujan says.
   Lujan called in reporters Wednesday to complain about the lack
of progress in 10 days of negotiations aimed at getting Exxon to
pay $15 million in ``up front'' money to help assess the
environmental damage caused by the oil spill and plan for a
recovery.
   Asked whether he thought Exxon had lived up to its repeated
promises to do everything possible to rectify damages caused by the
Exxon Valdez tanker spill in Prince William Sound, Lujan replied:
``They have not yet because they haven't given us the $15 million
for the long-term assessment.''
   Lujan said Exxon lawyers ``are negotiating hard'' and ``trying
to get any advantage that they can.''
   Les Rogers, spokesman for Exxon Co. USA in Houston, said the
company was ``surprised'' and baffled about Lujan's complaints.
   ``There has never been any question that Exxon is willing to
appropriately fund the study,'' said Rogers, reading from a
prepared statement. ``Exxon offered to advance funds that may be
needed while discussions were ongoing.''
   Rogers said the negotiations, which involved three other
agencies in addition to Interior, were scheduled to continue.
   Steve Goldstein, the secretary's chief spokesman, said that
Lujan is concerned that the reluctance by Exxon to open its
checkbook, as reflected by these negotiations, ``will in many ways
dictate the approach that is going to be taken (by Exxon) in the
future.''
   ``He (Lujan) thought Exxon was going to come (to the
negotiations) with a check in their back pocket,'' said Goldstein.
   Government lawyers told Exxon attorneys they wanted $15 million
in advance for developing a long-term recovery plan and assessing
the extent of damage to wildlife, waterfowl and fish and public
lands. Eventually these costs, separate from the direct cleanup
costs, are likely to be ``in the tens of millions'' of dollars,
said Lujan.
   Lujan said the government wants to distribute $8 million
immediately to officials representing a number of government
agencies already working in Alaska and put the other $7 million in
reserve. He said one reason Exxon has balked is that the company
complained the money would not be earning interest if it is turned
over to the government in a lump sum.
</TEXT>
