<FIRST>r w PM-Coelho-Bonds     04-13 0366</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Coelho-Bonds,360</SECOND>
<HEAD>Unusual Coelho Junk Bond Purchase Reported</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rep. Tony Coelho bought a $100,000 junk bond
three years ago through Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc., and company
records said the purchase was made by the Democratic leader's
campaign committee, a published report says.
   During the same time he held the bonds, the California
congressman was chairman of the House Democratic Congressional
Campaign Committee, The Washington Post reported in today's
editions.
   The committee has received some of its largest donations from
Drexel's Political Action Committee and from indicted junk bond
pioneer Michael Milken, the Post said.
   Coelho also received speaking honoraria from Drexel in 1986 and
1987, the Post said. And Coelho had worked to prevent the closing
of Drexel's Beverly Hills office as part of an expected settlement
of a long civil fraud investigation of Milken and Drexel, according
to a Los Angeles Times story cited by the Post.
   But Coelho told the Post that at the time of the investment, he
didn't know Drexel was connected with the high-risk, high-yield
bond. He said it was recommended by a friend he declined to
identify.
   The issue was used to help finance the takeover of Beatrice
Foods by BCI Holdings.
   ``My decision to purchase the bond had nothing to do with
Drexel, Milken or an employee of Drexel,'' Coelho said.
   Coelho, the third-ranking Democrat in the House, said in the
letter he assumed the Drexel records listing his campaign as the
purchaser were the result of a ``computer error'' and he bought the
bonds with his own money.
   House rules forbid members to convert campaign funds for
personal uses.
   Drexel's list ``Coelho for Congress'' as the initial purchaser
of the funds on April 10, 1986, the Post said. The Post said the
purchase was generally available only to institutional investors
and regular customers of the Wall Street investment firm.
   According to Coelho's letter, the purchase was ``corrected'' and
his accountant sent Coelho's personal payment to Drexel three weeks
after the initial order date, the Post said.
   Coelho, the House majority whip, earned about $12,000 in
interest and profits during the six months he held the bonds,
according to his disclosure statement, the Post said.
</TEXT>
