<FIRST>r i PM-Obit-Funaro     04-13 0212</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Obit-Funaro,0218</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Brazilian Finance Minister Dead At 55</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dilson Domingos Funaro, the former
Brazilian finance minister who was instrumental in instituting
Brazil's debt moratorium in 1987, has died of lymphatic cancer. He
was 55.
   Funaro died Wednesday at Osvaldo Cruz Hospital in Sao Paulo,
said hospital supervisor Vera Tavares.
   Funaro, born in Sao Paulo, the nation's financial and industrial
center, was named head of the powerful Finance Ministry in August
1985 in the midst of Brazil's worst inflationary crisis.
   Internationally known for refusing to accept monitoring of the
Brazilian economy by the International Monetary Fund, Funaro
announced the 10-month moratorium on the nation's foreign debt
interest payments in February 1987.
   ``We aren't here to sacrifice ourselves and our economy to
maintain Citibank profits,'' Funaro told journalists shortly before
announcing the moratorium.
   Funaro was also a key player in launching the failed 1986
anti-inflation ``Cruzado Plan.'' The plan, which froze wages and
prices to combat rampant inflation, led to a consumer spending
spree that created serious shortages and a drop in exports and cash
reserves.
   After the freeze collapsed and inflation soared to an annual
rate of 500 percent, Funaro's popularity among politicians and
citizens fell. He stepped down from the post in March 1987.
  
</TEXT>
