<FIRST>u i AM-Japan-Markets     04-13 0270</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets,0278</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Off Slightly, Stocks Retreat</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Concern about possible intervention by Japan's
central bank pushed the U.S. dollar down slightly against the
Japanese yen Thursday, while the main index on the Tokyo Stock
Exchange also lost ground, traders said.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, which gained a
marginal 8.07 points Wednesday, lost 192.51 points, or 0.58
percent, to finish at 33,063.94. The index was higher in early
trading, but then declined.
   The dollar closed at 132.80 yen, down 0.05 yen from Wednesday's
132.85-yen finish. The currency opened higher at 133.03 yen and
ranged from 132.75 to 133.20 yen.
   The dollar started to fall in the afternoon session as investors
began to sell the currency after the Bank of Japan checked exchange
rates, said a dealer with the Bank of Tokyo, who spoke on condition
of anonymity.
   ``After the dollar surpassed the 133-yen level, the majority of
participants withdrew to the sidelines, fearing possible
intervention by the Bank of Japan,'' an analyst with a commercial
bank said.
   In early April, Japan's central bank intervened by selling
dollars to support the yen when the U.S. currency reached the
133.50-yen level.
   Traders also said investors were reluctant to make major moves
ahead of Friday's release of U.S. trade and wholesale price figures
in Washington.
   On the stock exchange, dealers said the Nikkei index fell as
investors took profits ahead of the release of the U.S. economic
figures.
   Institutional investors stayed on the sidelines due to lingering
political uncertainties and the dollar's current strength, said a
dealer with a major securities firm in Tokyo, speaking anonymously.
</TEXT>
