<SECOND>PM-Washington in Brief,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thornburgh Repeals Meese Independent Counsel Order</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attorney General Dick Thornburgh has revoked a
regulation that his predecessor issued as a parting shot to his
critics.
   The order by Thornburgh on Wednesday rescinds an order by
outgoing Attorney General Edwin Meese III last summer that had
required the Justice Department to appoint independent counsels to
investigate members of Congress.
   Thornburgh's action returns to the Justice Department _ at least
while Congress studies the legislation _ its traditional role in
investigating allegations of criminal wrongdoing by members of
Congress.
   ``The Congress has been asked to review the role of the
independent counsel,'' Thornburgh, who had expressed doubts about
the Meese order, said in a statement.
   The order was issued hours after Bush proposed in his ethics
package to extend to members of Congress the law providing for
court appointment of independent counsels to investigate high
government officials.
