<SECOND>PM-Israel-Lebanon,0170</SECOND>
<HEAD>Israeli-Allied Militiamen Capture Four Shiite Guerrillas</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli-allied militiamen in southern Lebanon
captured four Shiite Moslem guerrillas in Israel's self-proclaimed
security zone after wounding one guerrilla in a firefight, the army
said today.
   There were no casualties among the militiamen belonging to the
South Lebanon Army, an Israeli-trained 2,500-member militia, the
military command said.
   It said the guerrillas carried a cache of weapons but that their
affiliation could not immediately be determined.
   The clash occurred Wednesday night near Markaba, a village two
miles from the Israeli border, the army said.
   Israel's national Itim news agency said the guerrillas were
apparently on their way to plant a roadside bomb and mines in the
security zone.
   The zone is a six-to-10 mile buffer strip along the border that
Israel carved out in 1985 after withdrawing the bulk of its troops
from Lebanon. The zone is jointly patrolled by the South Lebanon
Army, a mostly Christian militia, and about 1,000 Israeli troops.
