<FIRST>r a PM-Hoffman-Reax     04-13 0643</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hoffman-Reax,0668</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hoffman Remembered As Radical True To Cause</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEPHANIE NANO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Abbie Hoffman was ``an American legend' who stayed true to his
beliefs long after his contemporaries sold out to the establishment
he had rallied young people against during the 1960s, friends and
family said.
   ``It's the end of an era,'' said Hoffman's younger brother, Jack.
   Abbie Hoffman was found dead in his home in Bucks County, Pa.,
by a neighbor Wednesday night. The cause of death was not
immediately known.
   ``He was 52 years old and I think he gave up,'' said Jack
Hoffman in a telephone interview from his suburban Boston home.
``My brother packed in a lot of miles in his life. Maybe he was
tired. I know he was disappointed in the young people of today. He
didn't feel he was getting through to them.
   ``He was disenchanted.''
   Hoffman gained national attention as a member of the Chicago
Seven, a group of radicals who led hundreds of protesters at the
1968 Democratic National Convention in Chicago.
   He remained steadfast to his leftist beliefs to the end.
   ``To me he was a genius who was able to organize large numbers
of people, motivate them and reach them in ways that nobody else
could do,'' said Hoffman's attorney, Gerald Lefcourt, of New York
City. ``His approach was always unique and amusing but also
convincing and who dedicated his life to the things that he
believed in changing.''
   Said John Oakes, Hoffman's publisher: ``He was somebody who
stayed true to what he believed in unlike so many of his
contemporaries who sold out and became just what they detested when
they were 20 years old.
   ``I find him inspiring and I hope a whole new generation will
find his example something to aspire to.'' said Oakes.
   Hoffman, however, criticized today's campuses as ``bastions of
rest,'' and last week said the interest young people have in the
'60s disturbed him.
   ``Nostalgia is a sign of middle-age,'' he said before an
appearance last week at Vanderbilt University in Nashville, Tenn.
``We're reminiscing about our youth. When you see young people
nostalgic for a youth they didn't even experience, it's a little
sad. They're supposed to be out making one for themselves.''
   At Vanderbilt, Hoffman participated in a panel discussion with
other '60s activists, including psychedelic drug guru Dr. Timothy
Leary.
   ``Oh, God. I'm stunned. He was brilliant,'' remarked Leary when
reached at his Los Angeles home Wednesday night and told of
Hoffman's death.
   Later, after collecting his thoughts, Leary added:
   ``Abbie Hoffman was an American legend. He was up there in the
hall of fame with rebel Huck Finn, rowdy Babe Ruth, crazy Lenny
Bruce. He was the Pete Rose of the '60s counterculture, a hustler,
a base stealer, a wild free spirit and a gambler. He is a historic
figure and a great American and I loved the guy.''
   Lefcourt remembered Hoffman's sense of humor, which ``really
covered his outrage at a lot of injustice that he saw.'' Hoffman
made a few appearances as a stand-up comedian last year.
   ``He threw money on the (American) stock exchange floor in the
late '60s and was able to show in that satirical event _ when
hundreds of people on the stock exchange on Wall Street chased
flying money on the floor _ how silly it all was,'' said Lefcourt.
   Jack Hoffman said he hoped history would treat his brother more
kindly than did life.
   ``He was a great patriot,'' he said. ``He loved America and he
loved the system because it allowed him to do what he did:
protest.''
   Now, Hoffman said, a great American story has ended.
   ``I guess now they can make the movie,'' he said. ``We talked
about writing a script, but there were always problems with the
ending. I guess now we know how it goes.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890413-0058 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-13-89 0524EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Japan-Markets     04-13 0294</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0305</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stocks, Dollar Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Tokyo Stock Exchange's main index declined
today, while the dollar slipped slightly against the Japanese yen.
   The dollar closed at 132.80 yen, down 0.05 yen from Wednesday's
close of 132.85 yen. It opened at 133.03 yen, but traders said it
started to fall following hints of intervention by the Bank of
Japan. It ranged between 132.75 yen and 133.20 yen.
   Traders said the central bank had been calling to inquire about
rates, a tactic that implies intervention and often is used to
indirectly discourage dollar-buying.
   The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average, an 8.07-point gainer the
previous day, shed 192.51 points, or 0.58 percent, closing at
33,063.94.
   Dealers said investors held back, awaiting the announcement of
U.S. major economic indicators and watching whether the dollar
would remain stable.
   On Friday, Washington is to announce U.S. trade figures for
February and the wholesale price index for March.
   Nomura Securities analyst Yoshiro Inouye said investors also
were discouraged by news reports that Saudi Arabia has decided to
cut crude oil shipments to Japan in May by 40 percent from normal
levels.
   A feeling of political instability still was bothering
investors, he added.
   Volume traded on the first section was estimated at 850 million
shares, down from Wednesday's 1 billion.
   In currency dealings, the dollar moved little while the market
awaited Friday's announcement of the U.S. economic indicators,
traders said.
   After the Bank of Japan's rate checking, most participants
withdrew to the sidelines, fearing possible central bank
intervention if the dollar rose above 133 yen, said a dealer with
the Bank of Tokyo, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   In early April, the central bank sold dollars to support the yen
when the U.S. currency reached the 133.50-yen level.
</TEXT>
