<FIRST>r i PM-DamagedConcorde     04-13 0343</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Damaged Concorde,0353</SECOND>
<HEAD>Engineers Flying From London To Fix Crippled Concorde</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SYDNEY, Australia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   British engineers headed for Australia
today to install a new rudder on a British Airways Concorde jet
that lost part of its tail while trying to set speed records on an
world-circling journey.
   The Concorde was flying at about 1,500 miles per hour from
Christchurch, New Zealand, to Sydney on Wednesday when a large
chunk of the tail fin disintegrated at about 40,000 feet over the
Tasman Sea, the airline said.
   Spokeswoman Katherine Wilson said specialists due in Sydney
today would ``work through the night'' to repair the damage so the
plane can leave on the next leg, Perth in Western Australia, on
Friday as scheduled.
   In London a company spokesman, speaking anonymously in keeping
with British custom, said spare parts left London on Wednesday with
two engineers.
   The three-week journey started in London April 1 with 100
American passengers including commentator William F. Buckley who
each paid $39,000 to travel supersonic for 38,343 miles.
   The plane's pilot, Capt. David Leney, said he was climbing out
of Christchurch at Mach 1.8, nearly twice the speed of sound, when
there was a ``very slight bang.''
   ``There was no indication at all what it was,'' he told a news
conference. ``We decided to carry on. The airplane was carrying on
perfectly in every way.''
   Leney said he had no idea what was wrong until he was alerted by
the control tower at Sydney's Kingsford-Smith International Airport.
   ``I was very surprised to see just what was missing,'' he said.
``I felt slightly shaken. One doesn't like to see one's airplane
with a piece missing.''
   Passengers contacted by the AP said the plane ``shuddered''
about 25 minutes out of Christchurch.
   British Airways would not detail the extent of damage but
photographs of the plane showed a large chunk missing from the rear
section.
   News reports said the plane is about 10 years old and one of the
newest in the airline's fleet of seven Concordes, built by a joint
British-French consortium.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
