<DOCNO> AP890413-0062 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-13-89 0712EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-PeoriaFire     04-13 0554</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Peoria Fire,0574</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Charged In Fire Deaths Skipped Judge's March Jail Order</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT LEE ZIMMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PEORIA, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A vagrant forced out of an apartment house
hours before it was set on fire has been charged with nine arson
deaths, and authorities say he should have been in jail for another
case but ignored a judge's order.
   Joe Pickens, 34, never reported to the Peoria County Jail on
March 31 to serve a 30-day sentence for a misdemeanor, court
records show.
   No arrest warrant was issued, and now Pickens faces more serious
crimes: nine counts of first-degree murder and two counts of
aggravated arson in the worst fire in the history of this central
Illinois city.
   ``I don't fault the sheriff or the jail,'' State's Attorney
Kevin Lyons said Wednesday.
   The missed jail date was included on the jail's list of
violations to be brought to Lyons' attention _ an action the jail
takes about every two weeks, the prosecutor said.
   Pickens, a native of York, Ala., was charged with the deaths
Wednesday, one day after a fire set in a vacant first-floor
apartment spread and killed seven children and two young mothers on
the second floor.
   Pickens confessed to setting the fire after saying it started
accidentally, according to Police Superintendent Allen Andrews.
   Pickens apparently stayed at the two-story house in the past and
``was put out of the house (Monday night), but he came back,'' said
Fire Chief G. John Parker.
   Parker said he did not know why Pickens had been forced to leave.
   Circuit Judge Robert A. Barnes set bond at $2 million, and
scheduled a hearing for May 5.
   Neighbors in the working-class area of town expressed shock.
   ``I'm angry and hurt and surprised he'd so something like that
to those folks,'' said Claudie Garner, who lives across the street
with her husband, Jim, and their nine children. ``They were nice
and never did anything to hurt anyone.''
   Pickens was supposed to surrender to serve the month for
resisting arrest, his 22nd misdemeanor conviction since 1983, court
records show.
   The records show his most frequent address was the Peoria Rescue
Mission, where superintendent Richard Brienen recalled an incident
in which Pickens threw bricks at the building after being ejected
for violating house rules.
   ``My nickname for him was `Trouble,''' Brienen said. ``The guys
used to call him `Trash Can Joe.' Sometimes when he'd get kicked
out of here he would just go crawl out in the trash cans to sleep.
Well, the next day he'd smell like it.''
   More than 200 people attended a memorial service Wednesday for
the victims.
   The Rev. John Gibson, pastor of Rising Sun Missionary Baptist
Church, said a funeral was scheduled for Friday for all nine
victims.
   ``Everybody is devastated by this situation,'' Gibson said.
``It's shocking.''
   The victims were Terry Davis, 27, and three of her children,
Arnisha, 7, Karlissa, 2, and Tanoa, 10; Mrs. Davis' sister, Wanda
Hobbs, 20, and her children, Felicia, 4, Ashley, 1, and Eugene
Roberts Jr., 2 months; and Jacolby Thomas, 2, the daughter of Joyce
Barnes, one of the survivors.
   All died of smoke inhalation.
   Ms. Barnes, 30, and Eric Davis, 14, son of Terry Davis, were in
fair condition at the burn unit at Franciscan Medical Center in
Rock Island.
</TEXT>
