<FIRST>r a PM-Northwest     04-13 0517</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Northwest,0533</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two More Bidders For Northwest Airlines Identified</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An investment company founded by former
U.S. Treasury Secretary William Simon and three former Marriott
Corp. executives have been identified as suitors for Northwest
Airlines, according to reports published today.
   The two groups are contending with Los Angeles billionaire
Marvin Davis, who has submitted a $2.62 billion bid to take over
the nation's fourth largest airline.
   Amid speculation of bidders other than Davis, the stock of NWA
Inc., Northwest's parent, closed Wednesday up 1{ at 90{, surpassing
Davis' offer of $90 a share.
   One of the other bidders is Wesray Capital Corp., a New York
investment company founded by Simon, the St. Paul Pioneer Press
Dispatch reported today.
   Bruce Retrum, a union leader for some of Northwest's 6,500
flight attendants, told the newspaper that Saunders Miller, a
Minneapolis financial consultant, contacted him to try to set up a
meeting with union leaders and a Wesray representative to discuss a
leveraged buyout.
   ``There were no specifics, but my assumption was that he wanted
to talk about an ESOP (employee stock ownership plan) or some
employee stock ownership,'' said Retrum, secretary-treasurer of
Teamsters Local 2747.
   The meeting was scheduled for today but then postponed by
Miller, Retrum said. Miller declined to comment.
   Last week, a spokesman for Simon said he wasn't interested in
buying Northwest.
   Meanwhile, the Star Tribune in Minneapolis reported today that
the third suitor includes Gary L. Wilson, a Walt Disney executive
who left Northwest's board in November, Al Checchi, a Los Angeles
businessman, and Frederick Malek, a former member of the Nixon
White House and campaign adviser to President Bush.
   All three are former executives of Marriott, a travel
conglomerate that provides Northwest and other airlines in-flight
meal service.
   William Genoese, airline director for the International
Brotherhood of Teamsters, said Checchi and Wilson have informed him
that their group owns 4.9 percent of Northwest's stock and wants to
buy the company, the Star Tribune reported.
   Checchi, through an assistant in his Los Angeles office,
declined to comment. Wilson was traveling in Europe and was
unavailable for comment.
   But a spokesman for Malek confirmed the existence of Checchi's
group. The spokesman said Malek is a ``passive investor in a
partnership headed by Mr. Checchi.''
   On March 28, Northwest disclosed the Checchi group's existence,
but not its identity. Northwest said the group suggested a friendly
leveraged buyout. The company's board rejected that overture and
also announced the adoption of a corporate ``poison pill'' to
discourage a hostile takeover.
   The disclosure sent the carrier's stock price soaring and
spurred Davis, who holds a 3 percent stake in Northwest, to make
his $90 per share bid. The board rejected Davis' bid last week.
   Davis, an oil mogul with interests in real estate and
entertainment, has said he plans a shareholder proxy fight to win
control of the airline's board at NWA's May 15 shareholders meeting.
   Northwest has asked a federal judge to prevent Davis from
meddling with its unions, while Davis has filed a separate lawsuit
seeking to invalidate Northwest's ``poison pill'' anti-takeover
plan.
</TEXT>
