<FIRST>r a PM-TrailsideSlayings     04-13 0503</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Trailside Slayings,0519</SECOND>
<HEAD>Juror Misconduct Ruling Could Earn New Trial for Convicted `Trailside
Killer'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The forewoman of a jury that convicted a man of
five northern California trailside murders improperly knew about
his criminal past, a judge has ruled.
   Although Wednesday's finding could lead to a new trial for David
Joseph Carpenter, Superior Court Judge Herbert B. Hoffman did not
overturn Carpenter's conviction or vacate the death sentence
imposed for the 1980 Marin County parkland slayings.
   ``I'm absolutely convinced that the evidence in this case is
overwhelming beyond a shadow of a doubt as it applies to
(Carpenter's) guilt and sentencing,'' Hoffman said. ``That's one of
the reasons I find this decision distasteful to make.''
   Prosecutors were given until May 1 to file briefs stating their
reasons why Carpenter, 58, of San Francisco should not be retried
on grounds that jury forewoman Barbara Durham's misconduct tainted
the jury's findings.
   Defense attorneys will have three weeks to file their reply
before both sides return to court June 1.
   ``Whether this juror misconduct is something that will overturn
this conviction is something we'll have to decide,'' Hoffman said.
   The ruling culminated a three-month hearing involving
allegations that Durham found out during Carpenter's six-month
trial that he already was on death row for two similar 1981
killings in Santa Cruz County.
   ``I'm confident my decision regarding Mrs. Durham's jury
misconduct is correct, but it does not please me,'' said Hoffman,
who expressed sorrow for the victims' families.
   ``This has to be something that is going to be devastating to
them,'' Hoffman said about the possible retrial.
   Two acquaintances of Mrs. Durham testified during the hearing
that she indicated in a March 26, 1988, dinner conversation that
she knew about Carpenter's involvement in the Santa Cruz killings.
   Defense attorneys who filed the retrial motion contend such
knowledge was prejudicial enough to Carpenter's defense to warrant
a new trial.
   Hoffman had issued a pretrial ruling that barred jurors from
knowing about Carpenter's previous conviction and death sentence.
   Michael Lustig, a San Diego businessman, and his former
girlfriend, Barbara Duran, both quoted Mrs. Durham as saying, ``I'm
not supposed to know this, but the defendant has been convicted of
doing the same thing in another county and has been sentenced to
death.''
   Mrs. Durham denied she made such a statement.
   But Hoffman said Mrs. Durham appeared extremely nervous when she
took the stand to respond to the allegations and the judge added he
felt her ``memory was selective.''
   The judge said he would leave it up to the San Diego County
district attorney's office to decide whether Mrs. Durham should be
prosecuted for discussing the case before the end of the trial.
   Carpenter, who has spent most of his adult life behind bars, was
convicted last May of the nine-week murder spree at Point Reyes
National Seashore and Mount Tamalpais State Park.
   The death penalty automatically will be appealed to the state
Supreme Court, where Carpenter's appeal of the Santa Cruz
conviction is pending.
</TEXT>
