<HEAD>Clear Skies Over Much Of Nation's Middle; Thundershowers In Texas</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Most of the nation's middle had clear skies this morning, but
thunderstorms developed over Texas. South Carolina was chilly, with
temperatures hovering near the freezing point.
   Scattered rain showers spread across much of the southern Plains
on Wednesday. Widespread thunderstorm activity occurred this
morning around Houston.
   Farther west, snow fell in northern New Mexico, including 5
inches at Angel Fire. A snow advisory remained in effect this
morning for some of the state's mountains. In Albuquerque, easterly
winds gusted to 51 mph.
   A mixture of rain and snow occurred along a cold front from
western New York into much of the Ohio Valley. The rain and snow
showers were expected to move into New England today.
   Heavier rainfall during the six hours ending at 2 a.m. EDT
included more than a quarter inch at Cleveland and at the Texas
communities of Beaumont, Port Arthur and Corpus Christi.
   Clear skies prevailed from the upper Great Lakes across the
central Great Plains and central Rockies to the Great Basin. Skies
also were clear over the mid-Atlantic coastal states and the
Tennessee Valley.
   Temperatures continued on the cool side across the eastern half
of the nation.
   The high temperature in the nation Wednesday was 95 degrees at
Palm Springs, Calif., and Borrego Springs, Calif.
   Today's forecast: showers and a few thunderstorms across the
southern Plains and the lower Mississippi Valley; thunderstorms
over northwest Texas; rain and snow showers over the northern
Atlantic coast states; and rain showers over northern Minnesota and
northwest Wisconsin.
   High temperatures were to be in the 60s and 70s over much of the
nation; in the 50s from northern North Dakota across the upper
Mississippi and Ohio valleys to the middle Atlantic Coast, and from
the central Rockies to the Texas Panhandle; in the 40s from the
Great Lakes region to New England; in the 80s in southern Florida,
the southern tip of Texas, southwest Oregon and western Nevada; and
in the 80s and 90s over the desert Southwest and interior
California.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 17
degrees at Marquette, Mich., to 78 degrees at Phoenix.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 47 fair; Boston 36 partly cloudy; Buffalo 33
snow; Charleston, S.C., 42 fair; Cincinnati 40 rain; Cleveland 36
fair; Detroit 29 fair; Miami 75 fair; New York 41 partly cloudy;
Philadelphia 37 fair; Pittsburgh 41 cloudy; Portland, Maine, 34
cloudy; Washington 42 fair.
   _Central: Bismarck 35 partly cloudy; Chicago 34 fair;
Dallas-Fort Worth 54 rain; Denver 34 fair; Des Moines 31 fair;
Indianapolis 34 fair; Kansas City 38 fair; Minneapolis-St. Paul 35
cloudy; Nashville 40 fair; New Orleans 61 cloudy; St. Louis 41 fair.
   _West: Albuquerque 45 windy; Anchorage 39 fair; Las Vegas 66
fair; Los Angeles 60 foggy; Phoenix 77 fair; Salt Lake City 43
fair; San Diego 61 cloudy; San Francisco 52 fair; Seattle 53 fair.
   _Canada: Montreal 39 cloudy; Toronto 34 cloudy.
