<FIRST>r a PM-Shamir     04-13 0260</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Shamir,0266</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shamir Says PLO Talk May Be Sweet, But Still Unrealistic</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir said talk
of peace is seductive, but negotiations with the Palestine
Liberation Organization would only lead to war.
   ``I would sit with anyone if I thought for one minute that it
would bring a just and lasting peace to our country and to our
region,'' Shamir told the Foreign Policy Association on Wednesday.
   ``But I know, and everyone who is familiar with our region
should know, that negotiations with the PLO will not bring peace.
They are a sure prescription for war. And while I shall do anything
I can for peace, I shall not lend myself to moves which will make
another war inevitable.''
   Shamir's speech before the Foreign Policy Association, a
non-profit organization whose goal is to promote public
understanding of international issues, concluded a 10-day U.S.
visit in which he met with President Bush in Washington. Shamir was
to leave for home today.
   The Israeli government is under pressure from the United States
to open talks with the PLO now that its leader, Yasser Arafat,
publicly recognized Israel's right to exist and renounced terrorism.
   During his Washington visit, Shamir proposed allowing
Palestinians who live in the West Bank and Gaza Strip to elect
representatives to negotiate a form of self-rule. The proposal
received support from U.S. officials.
   The PLO said Monday that any elections in the territories should
be held after an Israeli withdrawal and under international
supervision, according to the PLO news agency, Wafa.
