<HEAD>Eds: Retransmitting to CORRECT category code</HEAD>
<HEAD>Stench of Death Lingers At Ranch Where 12 Bodies Were Excavated</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Satanic Slayings, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Note contents.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos XBRO1,XBRO2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOEL WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MATAMOROS, Mexico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stench of death lingers at the
ranch where police dug up the bodies of 12 men who cult members say
were used in ritual sacrifices or klled for drug-related revenge.
   Inside a small hut with tar paper siding and a corrugated metal
roof, the odor of decomposing tissue was overwhelming Wednesday
afternoon.
   Police say suspects told them the building was used for carrying
out the killings.
   Scattered on the stained, fetid floor of the approximately
15-by-30-foot shack were bullet casings, cigars, chili peppers,
broken glass and empty liquor bottles.
   Outside the door, a cast-iron caldron held brains and other
organs, a turtle shell, a horseshoe and other objects in a thick,
dark liquid. Smaller bowls nearby held a dead rooster, charred goat
heads and other objects that had been cooked.
   A windowsill held what looked like a bird's nest made of tissue
paper and human hair.
   What appeared to be skin from a human hand was floating in a
yellowish liquid inside a piece of tractor tire about 20 yards
away, near the grave of Mark Kilroy, a 21-year-old University of
Texas student who disappeared March 14 while on spring break in
Matamoros.
   The victims were exhumed Tuesday from nine shallow graves in or
near a corral on the 20-acre ranch area that borders on farm fields.
   Cult members said they were involved in the killings for about
nine months, according to investigators. Kilroy and some other
victims were hacked to death with a machete, authorities said.
   ``It's beyond belief of anybody that lives in a civilized
nation,'' said Texas Attorney General Jim Mattox, who visited the
site.
   He said Kilroy was found with a wire inserted in his spine and
the cult had planned to use it later to extract the vertebrae for
use in necklaces.
   Mexican Federal Judicial Police have arrested five men, and were
searching for several other people, including the cult's
``godfather'' who told members the ritual killings would bring them
demonic protection from enemies.
   ``We killed them for protection,'' one of the suspects, Elio
Hernandez Rivera, 22, of Matamoros, told reporters at a news
conference.
   Cult members were importing about 1,000 pounds of marijuana a
month into the United States, Mattox said.
   ``Very clearly they believed the human sacrifices and the animal
sacrifices put a magical shield around them that protected them
from evil or harm, even up to bullets,'' Mattox said.
</TEXT>
