<FIRST>r a PM-SatanicSlayings-Leader     04-13 0435</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Satanic Slayings-Leader,0446</SECOND>
<HEAD>Drug-Cult Leader Raised In Santeria Family</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Satanic Slayings, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The leader of a drug trafficking gang accused of
ritually killing 12 people near Matamoros, Mexico, grew up in a
Cuban-American family that practiced Santeria animal sacrifices,
authorities believe.
   Residents of the middle-class neighborhood in west Dade County
where Adolfo de Jesus Constanzo, 26, lived until 1984 said they
found headless chickens, geese and goats on their doorsteps and in
the streets near his home, The Miami Herald reported today.
   Such animals are ritually sacrificed by followers of Santeria, a
religion that mixes elements of Christianity with African animism.
   ``The mother was in Santeria,'' said Norma Brito, who bought the
Constanzos' house after their bank foreclosed in 1984. Ms. Brito
said she found the remains of an altar with candles, wax and fruit
when she moved in.
   ``They had sheep and chicken in the back yard,'' said Carmen
Reigada, another neighbor. ``They were troublemakers.''
   Mrs. Reigada said she discovered a headless chicken on her
doorstep after her son quarreled with Constanzo's mother, Aurora
del Valle de Posada, the Herald reported. Constanzo was the oldest
of four children.
   Both Mexican and U.S. police said the suspects in the killings
described the rituals as Cuban Santeria sacrifices taught to them
by Constanzo.
   There is no evidence, however, that Santeria has ever sanctioned
human sacrifices, said Mercedes Sandoval, an anthropology professor
at Miami-Dade Community College who has studied the religion for
three decades.
   ``These may have been a group of deranged people who may have
started with Santeria and ended with these barbarities,'' she said,
``but what they did is not Santeria.''
   Santeria was introduced to Cuba by African slaves, who blended
their polytheistic beliefs with Roman Catholic dogma, identified
African gods by the names of Catholic saints, and carried out
animal sacrifices to summon those gods, Sandoval said.
   Metro-Dade police said they couldn't confirm whether Constanzo,
whom they arrested twice for shoplifting in 1981, was the same man
being sought as the ``godfather'' of the drug-smuggling ring.
   Officer George Gabito of the Cameron County Sheriff's Department
in Brownsville, Texas, said authorities suspect Constanzo is the
gang's leader. U.S and Mexican authorities were searching for him
today, and said they believe Constanzo is in the United States.
   After one of his 1981 shoplifting arrests, Constanzo told police
he was born in Miami Beach and was a student at Miami-Dade
Community College. The registrar at the college said Constanzo took
classes there about 1980-81 but did not graduate.
   Neighbors said Constanzo traveled back and forth to Mexico
shortly thereafter, the Herald reported.
</TEXT>
