<FIRST>r a PM-FloridaBrushfires     04-13 0164</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Florida Brushfires,0167</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fires Dwindle After Thunderstorms</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fires that scorched 32,000 acres of dried-out
sawgrass and threw a haze over South Florida dwindled after
thunderstorms, and only a few scattered hot spots remained today.
   A cold front moving down the Florida peninsula shifted the wind
and blew away the dense smoke cover, which had forced the temporary
evacuation of nearly 750 would-be immigrants from a detention
facility at the edge of the Everglades.
   The state Division of Forestry announced late Wednesday that
large brushfires in western Dade county and smaller blazes in Palm
Beach county had been contained, with ``just a few pockets''
burning.
   Larry Lahiff of the National Weather Service said forecasters
expected continued showers tonight. He said a strong shift in wind
direction dispersed the smoke, but sent some of it over Key West
and the Fort Myers region.
   ``There's still some haze, but in the lower levels of the
atmosphere it's been keeping fairly clear,'' Lahiff said.
