<HEAD>Cabinet Changes in West Germany</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The following is a list of Chancellor
Helmut Kohl's Cabinet appointments announced Thursday.
   _Gerhard Stoltenberg, 60, from finance minister to defense
minister, a position now held by Rupert Scholz who is being dropped
from the Cabinet.
   _Theo Waigel, 59, replaces Stoltenberg as finance minister.
   _Wolfgang Schaeuble, 46, replaces Friedrich Zimmermann as
interior minister. Schaeuble has been Kohl's chief of staff.
   _Zimmermann, 64, becomes head of the Transport Ministry,
replacing Juergen Warnke.
   _Warnke, 57, becomes minister for economic cooperation,
replacing the ministry's former head, Hans Klein.
   _Klein, 58, a journalist, replaces chief government spokesman
Friedhelm Ost, with that post now upgraded to minister and Cabinet
status. Ost is leaving government service.
   _Rudolf Seiters, 51, replaces Schaeuble as chief of staff.
   _Gerda Hasselfeldt, 38, replaces Construction Minister Oscar
Schneider, who is being dropped from the Cabinet and assigned to
head the government office overseeing a major construction project
to erect national museums in Bonn and Berlin.
   Cabinet members remaining in their previous posts:
   _Foreign Minister Hans-Dietrich Genscher, 62. Genscher is also
the country's vice chancellor.
   _Hans A. Engelhard, 54, minister of justice.
   _Helmut Haussmann, 45, economics minister.
   _Ignaz Kiechle, 59, minister of agriculture.
   _Norbert Bluem, 53, labor minister.
   _Dorothee Wilms, 59, minister of inter-German relations.
   _Ursula Lehr, 58, family and health minister.
   _Christian Schwarz-Schilling, 58, post and communications
minister.
   _Juergen Moellemann, 43, education minister.
   _Heinz Riesenhuber, 53, minister of research and technology.
   _Klaus Toepfer, 50, minister of environment.
