<HEAD>Communist Party Ousts Four Conservatives, Reformers Added</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 2nd graf pvs, ``The changes...'' to CORRECT that Soviets
did not invade Hungary. Pickup 3rd graf pvs, ``Last month...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TEDDIE WEYR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four conservatives have been removed
from the ruling Politburo and replaced by two reformers in a move
that appears to strengthen Communist Party leaders who favor
introducing a multiparty system.
   The changes in the party's senior guard Wednesday follow its
endorsement in February of ending the Communists' political
monopoly in this country, where a 1956 anti-Soviet uprising was
brutally crushed by Soviet tanks.
   Last month, the party leadership further committed itself to at
least partially free parliamentary elections next year.
   Among those removed Wednesday was the chief party ideologist,
Janos Berecz, who was voted into the Politburo in 1987 and until
last year was considered a prime candidate to replace long-time
party leader Janos Kadar.
   New party leader Karoly Grosz and the party's two leading
reformers, Imre Pozsgay and Rezso Nyers, received important votes
of confidence at Wednesday's closed-door session of the
policy-setting Central Committee. State media also reported Premier
Miklos Nemeth was also re-elected to his top party post.
   Grosz and his entire team had offered to resign on Tuesday
during a meeting of the 108-member Central Committee, party
spokesman Laszlo Major told state television.
   Grosz gained the top party post at a national party conference
last May.
   Major said the four members who left the Politburo either were
not nominated to the new Politburo or asked not to be nominated. He
did not elaborate.
   The other three ousted conservatives are Judit Csehak, minister
of social affairs and one of two women on the ruling body, party
bureaucrat Janos Lukacs, and Istvan Szabo, who was in charge of
agriculture, an area targeted for broad reform under the new
economic policies.
   Elected new members to Politburo was the secretary of the
influential Budapest Communist Party, Mihaly Jasso, and Pal
Vastagh, who heads the reform-oriented Csongrad county party
committee in southern Hungary.
   According to a brief statement carried by the state news agency
MTI, the Central Committee said the party was ``struggling with
political, ideological and organizational structural problems.''
   Major told state television that there have been increasing
complaints from the party's membership about too many
``contradictory statements'' by the ruling body's leaders.
   He indicated the changes were intended to increase unity among
party leaders, saying claims of a split in the party were now
``groundless'' in view of the new Politburo.
   Major quoted Grosz as telling the closed-door meeting it was
time to activate the membership of the party ``for the coming
struggles ahead.''
   He said former party chief Kadar attended the second half of
Wednesday's meeting. Kadar has been absent from several Central
Committee meetings, reportedly for health reasons.
</TEXT>
