<FIRST>u i PM-SriLanka 2ndLd-Writethru   04-13 0636</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sri Lanka, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0530,0654</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tamil Bomb Kills 38; Eight People Stabbed In Retaliation</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 11 grafs to UPDATE casualties. CORRECTS that eight
Tamils stabbed but only one dead. Picksup 7th, ``Indian troops...'' TRIMS.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A car bomb exploded outside a hotel in
the northeastern city of Trincomalee today, killing at least 38
people and injuring 57 in an attack military officials blamed on
Tamil rebels.
   Shortly after the blast, a group of angry Sinhalese attacked
Tamil residents in the city with knives, killing one and injuring
seven, military officials in Colombo said on condition of
anonymity. Officials denied earlier reports from witnesses that
eight Tamils were killed in the stabbing.
   The explosion in the port city, 145 miles northeast of Colombo,
occurred as more than 100 Sinhalese in a marketplace adjacent to
the hotel hunted for gifts and sweets to celebrate the Sinhalese
and Tamil New Year holidays.
   An Indian diplomat in Colombo, speaking on condition of
anonymity, said the explosives were rigged in a black Morris Minor
car.
   The midmorning blast flattened four neighboring shops, the
military officials said. Sketchy reports reaching Colombo did not
say whether the hotel was still standing or how large it was.
   At least 24 of those killed in the blast were Sinhalese, the
military officials said. The others were Tamils and Moslems.
   Rescue workers dug through the brick and mortar rubble rubble
looking for more victims of the blast and officials said the death
toll could rise.
   Military officials blamed Tamil separatists for the attack. But
the largest Tamil rebel group, the Liberation Tigers of Tamil
Eelam, denied responsibility for the blast, a spokesman for the
group said in Colombo.
   Normal communications between Trincomalee and most other parts
of the island have been severed in the 6-year-old Tamil
separatists' war against the Sinhalese majority.
   The Indian diplomat said the casualty reports were from Indian
peacekeeping troops, who have been deployed in northern and eastern
Sri Lanka since 1987 in an effort to disarm Tamil guerrillas and
enforce a peace accord.
   Indian peacekeeping forces patrolling the area imposed an
indefinite curfew on the city shortly after the blast.
   Officials in Colombo said hundreds of Sinhalese living on the
outskirts of Trincomalee were moved to a naval dockyard. They did
not give any details.
   Indian troops patrolling the region were rushed to the area to
prevent further ethnic violence and imposed a curfew, officials
said.
   The blast occurred a day after the beginning of a cease-fire
that the government called for the New Year holiday.
   According to government spokesmen, 26 militants of the Marxist
Sinhalese People's Liberation Front surrendered their arms on
Wednesday, giving themselves up at temples and government offices
converted into reception centers for rebels who give up violence.
   The government has set up 228 such centers across the country.
   Tamil rebels on Wednesday ambushed an Indian army patrol in
northern Sri Lanka and killed at least seven soldiers shortly after
the government's cease-fire took effect, officials said today.
   Tamil rebels have rejected the cease-fire and an amnesty offered
by the government until Indian troops are withdrawn from the island
nation, spokesmen for the rebels said.
   The government has suspended military operations against
anti-government Tamil and Sinhalese militants for a week and
offerred a general amnesty to those willing to surrender arms.
   President Ranasinghe Premadasa, seeking to end six years of
ethnic violence that has claimed 12,500 lives, announced the
amnesty and cease-fire on April 2 as part of a plan that includes
seats in Parliament and jobs for the militants.
   India sent more than 50,000 troops in 1987 to disarm Tamil
rebels and patrol the north and eastern provinces after signing an
accord with the Sri Lankan government aimed at ending the Tamil
insurgency.
</TEXT>
