<FIRST>u i PM-Lebanon 1stLd-Writethru   04-13 0696</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lebanon, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0525,0718</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shelling Resumes in Beirut On 14th Anniversary Of War</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 14 grafs to UPDATE casualties and fighting. Pickup
16th graf, ``The spokesman...''</HEAD>
<HEAD>With Lebanon-War, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RODEINA KENAAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Syrian and Christian gunners battled
across the capital's dividing Green Line today, blasting harbors
and residential districts as French envoys tried to arrange
evacuation of the wounded to a hospital ship.
   The shelling complicated the task of an Arab League mediation
panel seeking to enforce a cease-fire and open the way for
constitutional reforms that could end the sectarian conflict.
   The civil war, which entered its 15th year today, has claimed
more than 150,000 lives.
   Police said at least four people were killed and 10 wounded in a
fierce bombardment of residential districts this morning.
   In addition, four soldiers were killed during the night by
shells that hit the presidential palace in suburban Baabda and the
Defense Ministry in neighboring Yarze. Police said the palace and
defense ministry came under attack again today.
   The casualties brought the overall toll to 200 killed and 687
wounded since the latest fighting broke out March 8 between the
mainly Christian units of army commander Gen. Michel Aoun and an
alliance of Syrian soldiers and Druse militamen.
   Rockets fired from multibarreled launchers stationed around
Moslem west Beirut rained on and around Christian emplacements in
Beirut and Jounieh at midmorning, said a police spokesman who
cannot be named under standing rules.
   Christian gunners retaliated with 155mm barrages aimed at west
Beirut's Ein Mreisseh seaside residential district and Syrian
batteries stationed near the airport on the city's southern edge,
the spokesman said.
   Aoun, 53, who also heads a Christian military Cabinet in
Lebanon's dual government, renewed his demand or a Syrian
withdrawal from Lebanon. He accused Syria of moving gunboats into
northern Lebanon territorial waters.
   The Syrian military headquarters in Lebanon denied the charge.
   Bernard Kouchner, France's minister for humanitarian assistance,
said French helicopters would soon begin evacuating wounded
Lebanese to the hospital vessel La Rance.
   Kouchner, who arrived Tuesday, said Moslems were to be flown to
the ship from west Beirut's Bain Militair beach and Christians from
the port of Jounieh, 12{ miles north of Beirut.
   He did not say where the La Rance, equipped with 90 beds and an
operating theater, planned to drop anchor. But the leftist Beirut
newspaper As-Safir said it was to remain eight miles off Beirut.
   A spokesman for Acting Prime Minister Salim Hoss, who heads the
Moslem Cabinet, said ``the operation will go into full swing on
Friday.''
   The spokesman, who requested anonymity, said another French navy
auxiliary vessel, the tanker Penhors, planned to sail into Lebanese
waters Friday to unload six tons of fuel oil at the Moslem terminal
of Zahrani south of Beirut and the Christian Zouk harbor north of
the capital.
   As-Safir said that under a compromise worked out by Kouchner and
Hoss the tanker was to unload two tons in Zahrani and four in Zouk,
site of Beirut's main power plant.
   The plant has produced electricity for just one hour a day for
the past three weeks because the conflict has created a fuel
shortage.
   Hoss withdrew his objections to accepting French aid Wednesday
night after President Francois Mitterrand of France asserted that
his country was not choosing sides in Lebanon.
   France, which has traditional ties with the Christian community,
ruled Lebanon from the end of World War until its independence in
1943.
   The rival governments emerged in September after outgoing
President Amin Gemayel named Aoun, a Maronite Catholic like
himself, to head an interim Cabinet until a new head of state was
elected.
   Leftists and Moslems rejected the appointment on the ground it
violated an unwritten national covenant making the premier a Sunni
Moslem, the president a Maronite and the Parliament speaker a
Shiite Moslem.
   The current fighting erupted after Aoun imposed a naval blockade
on illegal militia ports that were siphoning off an estimated $100
million yearly in unpaid customs fees.
   Syrian forces joined in artillery barrages by Druse militiamen
and backed their siege of the 310-square mile Christian enclave
east and north of the divided city.
</TEXT>
