<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Prison, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0542,0320</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Foil Hostage Incident at Prison; Kill Inmate</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with incident over, hostages safe. ADDS
byline.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN-THOR DAHLBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two armed inmates seized eight hostages at a
high-security prison and were allowed to leave the facility, but
police killed one and wounded the other when the men threatened to
kill a captive, Tass said today.
   The official news agency said all the hostages were freed
unharmed.
   Armed with ``self-made firearms and knives,'' the two men
sneaked into the administrative building at the high-security
prison colony in the Voroshilovgrad region of the Ukraine at 10:30
a.m. Wednesday. They took eight female employees hostage, the
official news agency said.
   Tass said the inmates barricaded themselves in the building and
demanded a bus and guarantees they would be allowed to leave the
colony, 500 miles south of Moscow.
   During negotiations with regional police and KGB chiefs, the
inmates were persuaded to release two captives, ``but the criminals
wouldn't set the others free unless authorities agreed to their
demands,'' Tass said.
   It identified the inmates as V. Maximov serving a 15-year term
for murder and theft, and O. Korzh sentenced to eight years in
prison for robbery and malicious hooliganism. It said both were
repeat offenders.
   After authorities decided to meet the criminals' demands, a bus
took them and their remaining hostages out of the penal colony.
Negotiators tried again to negotiate with the men before the bus
reached the highway, Tass said.
   The criminals demanded the release of another inmate and
threatened to kill one of the hostages immediately if that wasn't
done. After negotiations failed, authorities decided to attack,
Tass said.
   ``A carefully planned operation sprang into life,'' it said.
``Korzh was killed on the spot and Maximov wounded.''
   Tass said the situation had returned to normal at the prison.
</TEXT>
