<FIRST>r i PM-India-Carbide     04-13 0219</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-India-Carbide,0229</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Orders Immediate Relief for Bhopal Victims</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today ordered the
government to pay relief money to victims of the Bhopal gas
disaster until a $470 million settlement with Union Carbide can be
distributed, news reports said
   ``We are interested in providing relief to those who were
seriously injured,'' a three-judge panel ruled, Press Trust of
India reported.
   The court told the government to submit proposals for a relief
plan by Friday. It said victims should be paid from the state
treasury.
   Survivors of the Dec. 2, 1984 disaster requested immediate
relief after disbursal of compensation money was held up by legal
considerations.
   More than 3,400 died and 20,000 were injured when methyl
isocynate leaked from the indian subsidiary of Union Carbide Corp
in Bhopal. At least 500,000 people said they were affected by the
poison gas leak.
   The government sued the Danbury, Conn.-based firm for $3 billion
but reached a $470 million settlement with the company on Feb. 14.
   Many government critics have said the settlement is inadequate.
   A petition filed with the Supreme Court has challenged a law
empowering the government to act as sole representative of the
claimants, while another questions the way the settlement was
reached.
   A separate five-judge court panel is hearing the petitions.
</TEXT>
