<HEAD>Words From Dolphins' Dan Marino Help Prompt Coma Patient's Recovery</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS two grafs after 9th graf, `Then in' to UPDATE with doctor's
comment on talk therapy; picks up 10th graf, `Brent began...'. Version
moving on sports wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By COLLEEN BARRY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An 18-year-old injured in a motorcycle accident
says words of encouragement recorded by Miami Dolphins quarterback
Dan Marino helped pull him out of his three-month coma.
   ``I think Dan Marino is just the greatest football player there
is, and the tape I got from him was really good encouragement,''
said Brent Doyle, who is preparing to leave the Mediplex Rehab
Hospital in Thornton, a Denver suburb, on Friday, a day before his
19th birthday.
   ``He just said, `You can snap out of it. Just keep up the hard
work. Me and all the Dolphins are cheering for you 100 percent. If
you get better soon you can watch the Dolphins, and you can watch
me perform,''' Brent said Wednesday.
   Don Doyle, Brent's father, said he played Marino's recorded
message for his son daily, often two or three times, during Brent's
coma.
   ``The first prognosis was really dim. They didn't give him much
hope at all,'' the father said. ``It's a miracle in my opinion.''
   Brent sustained serious head injuries last October when he lost
control of his motorcycle while riding through the Rocky Mountains
foothills west of Boulder.
   ``Maybe a day or two after the accident, a boy and a girl from
work came up and I was thinking Brent was such a Dolphins fan, it
sure would be nice to get something from Dan (Marino) to give him
when he gets out of the hospital,'' the older Doyle said. ``They
heard me say this and pursued it.''
   Marino's tape arrived in November.
   Then in mid-February, a little more than two months after
receiving Marino's taped message, Brent emerged from the coma.
   Dr. Joshua Yurfest, a physician at Mediplex, said the ``talk
therapy'' Doyle received is controversial among doctors, who refer
to it as ``coma stim,'' short for coma stimulation.
   ``We believe it makes a difference, but we don't know,'' he said.
   Brent began walking again in time for his best friend's wedding
in March and can now prepare his own meals. ``He's 97 percent
recovered,'' his father said.
   Brent says he plans to go ahead with his plans to study acting
once he completes his rehabilitation.
   ``The greatest thing now _ other than getting through this and
still being alive, and for the Dolphins _ it's really nice just to
go home,'' Brent said.
</TEXT>
