<FIRST>r a PM-MarcosTransfer     04-13 0298</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Marcos Transfer,0306</SECOND>
<HEAD>Marcos Moved Out Of Intensive Care Unit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Philippine President Ferdinand Marcos
will be attended by private nurses, as well as hospital staff, now
that he has been moved out of a hospital's intensive care unit,
says his wife, Imelda.
   The transfer to St. Francis Medical Center's telemetry unit,
reserved for monitoring heart patients, also will reduce the chance
of infection because it is not as large as intensive care, Mrs.
Marcos said Wednesday.
   Another reason for Wednesday's move is that the telemetry unit
is less expensive that intensive care, Mrs. Marcos said.
   The ousted leader has more than $250,000 in unpaid bills at the
hospital. Mrs. Marcos claims the U.S. government should pay the
bills and that she is financially unable to do so.
   Marcos, 71, remained in guarded condition. He has been
hospitalized since Jan. 15 for treatment of heart and respiratory
ailments.
   ``His condition hasn't really changed, but we're trying to free
up a room in ICU for a patient who may need it more,'' hospital
spokeswoman Norma Kop said. ``He'll still be getting very close
care, but in a different unit.''
   Asked if she believed her husband would ever be well enough to
be released from the hospital, Mrs. Marcos said: ``I am always
hopeful. I always believe in miracles.''
   The Marcoses are under U.S. indictment on criminal racketeering
charges accusing them of stealing more than $100 million from their
homeland and stashing it in the United States.
   Prosecutors have concluded Marcos is too ill to stand trial and
have temporarily severed him from the case, but are proceeding with
the case against Mrs. Marcos.
   The Marcoses fled here in February 1986 after an election and
popular revolt catapulted Corazon Aquino to power, ending Marcos'
20-year rule.
</TEXT>
