<SECOND>PM-Philippines,0250</SECOND>
<HEAD>Guerrillas Free Tourists In Philippines</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DAVAO, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Communist guerrillas released three
tourists and their Filipino interpreter unharmed today, a week
after they seized the mountain climbers and accused them of spying.
   A local physician pronounced the cheerful mountaineers in good
health as they were turned over to church and government officials
at the foot of Mount Apo in Astorga, 615 miles southeast of Manila.
   ``It's great to be back,'' said Gerald Leo Christopher Kennedy,
22, a chemistry graduate student from Ireland. ``They treated us
very well.''
   Telephone engineer Trevor Anderson, 35, from Tauranga, New
Zealand, said they felt safe with the New People's Army guerrillas
until Wednesday, when the captives heard shelling near the rebel
camp.
   ``Everytime we heard a bang, we dived into the foxhole, maybe
seven times,'' he said. ``It wasn't good fun yesterday.''
   James Andrew Smart, a 40-year-old cave explorer from Bristol,
England, said he was not happy to hear they had been suspected of
spying.
   The three were unshaven and looked haggard as they shook hands
with guerrilla leader Benzar Sarabia and an escort of 25 armed
guerrillas.
   ``Investigations have shown that these three climbers are
innocent, thus we are releasing them,'' a rebel statement said
before the captives were freed.
   The foreigners were among more than 300 climbers trekking to the
9,690-foot Mount Apo, the country's highest peak, as part of the
annual convention of the National Mountaineering Federation of the
Philippines.
