<DOCNO> AP890413-0091 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-13-89 1124EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Cheney-Budget     04-13 0525</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cheney-Budget,500</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cheney Hints That High-Tech Projects May Get Budget Ax</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defense Secretary Dick Cheney, struggling to
cut more than $6 billion from the fiscal 1990 budget, has dropped a
strong hint that the B-2 stealth bomber and other high-tech weapons
that haven't yet gone into production may be prime targets.
   Defense sources said Cheney also is considering a slowdown in
the production of Trident missile submarines _ building one every
two years instead of one a year _ and might also order some cuts in
troop strength.
   In an interview Wednesday with a small group of newspaper
reporters, Cheney said he intended to meet an April 25 deadline for
presenting the administration's military budget proposal to
Congress and that all programs were still on the table _ even
personnel levels.
   The new defense chief agreed he had made some tentative
decisions but declined to discuss details.
   Cheney was then asked, however, for his views on ``stretchouts''
_ slowing the production line for a weapon to reduce the number
purchased during the year. Stretchouts frequently end up costing
the Pentagon more over the long run because of less efficiency on
the production line.
   In phrasing the question, the reporter cited the B-2 bomber and
the C-17 cargo plane _ two new aircraft programs that are nearing
the production phase.
   ``It seems to me that if you are talking about relatively
complex new weapons systems, or you are dealing with new technology
or we don't have a lot of experience, then lots of times delay or
deferral may make sense because you will learn more in the interim
process, get some of the bugs worked out and maybe find ways to
reduce cost,'' Cheney replied.
   ``If, on the other hand, you are talking about systems where you
already have a good deal of knowledge, experience ..., then when
you do a stretchout what you do is raise the cost of each item. So
I am in the process of resisting efforts to stretch out where it
adds significantly to the unit cost.
   ``When you are talking about new technology, then I'm more
sympathetic to the notion or argument that we ought to defer or
delay or stretch out the procurement.''
   A transcript of Cheney's interview was released this morning.
Spokesmen for the secretary declined to elaborate on his remarks.
   Other defense officials, however, who insisted on anonymity,
said Cheney was, in fact, urging a delay in production of B-2
stealth bombers but hadn't decided how long it should be.
   The plane, described by the Air Force as a revolutionary advance
in aviation, is designed to be invisible to enemy radar. The first
of the planes was unveiled publicly last November, but has yet to
fly.
   Cheney, who became defense secretary last month after the Senate
rejected President Bush's first choice, former Sen. John Tower, is
trying to cut roughly $6.4 billion from the fiscal 1990 budget
proposed by former President Reagan.
   Bush already has promised Congress he will make those cuts to
the Reagan plan, which totaled $315.2 in budget authority for
military and nuclear programs.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
