<SECOND>PM-Preschool Molest,0462</SECOND>
<HEAD>McMartin Trial Judge In `Death Struggle' To Send Case To Jury</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The judge in the McMartin Preschool child
molestation trial says he is considering having the court pay one
juror's full salary to make sure he can keep a 12-member jury and
avoid a mistrial in the nearly 2-year-old trial.
   ``I can't think of anything worse than not getting a decision
from this jury. That's my nightmare,'' Superior Court Judge William
Pounders told reporters in an unusual interview in his chambers
Wednesday. ``If it isn't forthcoming, it's a major disaster.''
   He said he took the rare step of talking to reporters while the
trial was in progress to pressure attorneys to speed their
presentations.
   As the trial's second anniversary approaches next week, Pounders
said the proceeding is costing taxpayers $100,000 a month, with the
total cost of the case since its inception in 1984 reaching $15
million.
   McMartin Preschool director Peggy Buckey, 62, and her son,
Raymond, 30, are charged with 65 counts of child molestation and
conspiracy.
   The trial was originally being heard by 12 jurors and six
alternates. However, two of the six have been dismissed for medical
reasons, two for hardships related to their jobs and one for being
inattentive during the proceedings.
   Pounders expressed concern that if he now lets one juror leave
the trial because of financial hardship he will risk a mistrial
because there will be no alternates left if another juror becomes
ill.
   Jurors still must hear another several months of defense
testimony, prosecution rebuttal and final arguments.
   The judge said juror Mark Bassett told him the company he works
for in financial trouble and he fears he may be laid off or that
the company may go out of business. He said he might have to leave
jury duty _ for which he's paid $10 a day _ to seek other
employment.
   ``It may be obvious to the county of Los Angeles that it would
cost less to pay him than to mistry this case,'' Pounders said. The
judge called such action highly unusual but not unprecedented.
   Pounders said Tuesday he will begin cutting all but the most
critical witnesses to speed the trial, rejecting eight defense
witnesses.
   Pounders also said he was not speaking figuratively when he told
defense attorney Danny Davis that the case would go to the jury
over Davis' dead body.
   ``It is a death struggle for me as far as I'm concerned,'' the
judge said. ``If I put the stress on him and he has a heart attack
or if he puts the stress on me and I have a heart attack, that is
the way it will be.''
</TEXT>
