<HEAD>Syria Aplogizes for Attack on Soviet Ships</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with Syria apologizing. CORRECTS name
of injured sailor and spelling of ship name in penultimate graf. No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Syrian helicopters fired rockets at two Soviet
naval vessels in the Mediterranean, and Syria apologized for the
raid that injured at least seven sailors, the Foreign Ministry said
today.
   The attack occurred Tuesday morning near the Syrian port of
Tartus, spokesman Gennady I. Gerasimov said at a news briefing.
   ``Two helicopters with Syrian markings attacked two Soviet
auxiliary vessels with rockets, namely a sea tugboat and a divers'
boat in the Mediterranean Sea,'' Gerasimov said.
   According to an initial probe, the attack was a result of
``erroneous actions of one of the Syrian helicopters,'' Gerasimov
said.
   He did not say what type of helicopters were involved or further
describe the Soviet vessels.
   The Soviets provide Syria with much of its military equipment.
   Gerasimov said seven Soviet crew members were injured, one
critically. The military newspaper Red Star identifed the
critically injured man as E. Shkitchenko and said, ``there is
little hope to save him.''
   ``The Syrian side expressed regret at the accident and offered
its official apology,'' the spokesman said.
   The Soviet media played down the incident with Syria, its
staunchest ally in the Middle East.
   The attack was first reported in a three-paragraph story in Red
Star.
   The official Tass news agency carried a two-paragraph dispatch
on Gerasimov's remarks. The evening newspaper Izvestia did not
mention the incident.
   Following the attack, the submarine-tracking ship Kraszny Kavkaz
and the cruiser Leningrad, on a routine patrol in the eastern
Mediterranean, hurried to the aid of the attacked vessels.
   The Soviets have maintained military facilities at Tartus since
1969.
   Gerasimov said a joint investigation commission has been set up
to determine why the helicopters attacked the Soviet vessels.
