<FIRST>r a PM-FamilyStabbing     04-13 0444</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Family Stabbing,0458</SECOND>
<HEAD>Four Family Members, Including Mom Eight Months Pregnant, Killed
In Rampage</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAMPA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man police say confessed to the bloody
killings of four members of a family, including an eight-months
pregnant mother, made a brief appearance before a judge today but
said nothing.
   Newton Carlton Slawson, described by police as a ``walking time
bomb,'' is charged with four counts of first-degree murder and one
of manslaughter in the deaths of Gerald Wood, his expectant wife,
Peggy, their two toddlers and the male fetus. Wood was a onetime
co-worker of Slawson's.
   The 34-year-old defendant, with a smooth-shaven head and droopy
mustache, was taken into a tiny jailhouse courtroom for an advisory
appearance before Hillsborough County Judge Vincent Giglio.
   ``You remain silent. Don't say a thing,'' public defender Ronnie
Gabriel told Slawson.
   No arraignment date was set. Slawson is being held without bail.
   Slawson, a former soldier and sailor from Concord, N.C., told
police he flew into a rage that he couldn't control in the Woods'
apartment.
   ``We just don't know why,'' said Deputy Police Chief Tom
DePolis. ``I guess the guy was a walking time bomb.''
   DePolis said Slawson was charged with manslaughter in the
killing of the fetus because he told police he cut a foot-long gash
in Mrs. Wood's belly in order to save it.
   The family was attacked Tuesday evening. Mrs. Wood, 21, died
Wednesday after surgery at Tampa General Hospital.
   ``She was shot several times, then cut in the stomach which
caused the loss of the infant,'' said police Sgt. Wiley Howell.
``The infant, a boy, was actually cut and died at the scene.''
   She managed to crawl downstairs from their apartment and next
door to her parents' house, and told her mother Slawson attacked
the family, police said.
   Police said they picked Slawson up about 10 blocks away and
recovered a .357-caliber Magnum pistol and a six-inch folding knife
from his car.
   ``During questioning, the suspect admitted to detectives that he
killed the family members,'' police spokesman Steve Cole said. ``No
clear-cut motive has been established.''
   Slawson told detectives he went beserk after Wood tried to force
crack cocaine down his throat, but ``we believe this is an excuse
he's using,'' Cole said today. There's no evidence of drugs, he
said.
   Slawson apparently met Wood when they both worked at a manure
plant, one of a series of jobs Slawson took since coming to the
Tampa area from North Carolina late last year.
   ``It surprises me that they knew each other. It surprises me
more than that Newton could do something like that,'' said Michael
Lange, manager of the Black Gold Compost Co.
</TEXT>
