<DOCNO> AP890413-0097 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-13-89 1208EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-AIDSDrug     04-13 0410</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AIDS Drug,0417</SECOND>
<HEAD>In Test Tube, Drug Selectively Kills, Inhibits Reproduction of HIV</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Latin AIDS, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A drug derived from a Chinese plant root
selectively killed AIDS-virus infected cells and inhibited virus
reproduction in healthy cells during test-tube experiments,
researchers announced today.
   The scientists working for the University of California at San
Francisco and Genelabs Inc. also have shown for the first time that
macrophages, cells that form the body's first line of immune system
defense, can be reservoirs of infection with the human
immunodeficiency virus, which causes AIDS.
   Tests results from about two years of work were reported today
in the Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences. Listed as a
co-author was Hin-Wing Yeung, a scientist from Chinese University
of Hong Kong who first brought the chemical to the attention of
researchers in San Francisco.
   The drug, GLQ223, is a highly purified form of the plant protein
trichosanthin, which is found in the root of a Chinese plant from
the cucumber family.
   The scientists cautioned that the drug has not been tried on
people, and that extensive studies will be required to determine
whether it will be safe to administer to AIDS patients. Genelabs of
Redwood City, Calif., has applied to the U.S. Food and Drug
Administration for permission to begin human testing.
   The drug has been tested in laboratory animals for toxicity,
said Michael S. McGrath, an assistant professor of medicine and
director of the AIDS-Immunobiology Research laboratory for San
Francisco General Hospital. The animal toxicity results were not
published, and the researchers said the drug had not yet been shown
to kill the virus in the animals.
   The scientists also said they did not know the exact mechanism
by which trichosanthin killed HIV-infected cells and inhibited HIV
reproduction in test tubes.
   After treating HIV-infected blood samples from eight individuals
with a single dose of the GLQ223, the scientists said they found no
macrophages with evidence of virus production five days later. The
drug also inhibited replication of HIV in laboratory cultured
cells, the report said.
   The study showed that 2 percent to 7 percent of macrophages in
the blood of AIDS patients are infected with HIV. Microphages,
which are found in every organ of the body and are difficult to
kill, direct the body's response to infection. Without functioning
macrophages, an individual is more likely to succumb to the
diseases and infections that kill patients with acquired immune
deficiency syndrome.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
