<FIRST>u a PM-YellowstoneConference     04-13 0379</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Yellowstone Conference,0390</SECOND>
<HEAD>Governor Challenges Symposium To Find Answers For Yellowstone's Future</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LARAMIE, Wyo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Mike Sullivan opened a three-day
symposium on the future of Yellowstone National Park today by
accusing the Bush administration of ``feudalism'' for asking the
state to pay for firefighting there.
   ``I would hope that George Bush's vision of a kinder and gentler
nation does not envision burning someone's back yard and then
charging them for the privilege,'' he said.
   Wildfires spurred by high heat and drought eventually burned
across nearly half of the park's 2.2 million acres.
   Sullivan said cooperation among state and federal agencies in
managing the world's first national park is being sorely tested by
Bush's proposal to pay for last summer's firefighting with the
state's share of federal mineral royalties, money paid to the
government for mining and oil drilling on federal land.
   ``Bluntly stated, this idea is feudalism and not federalism.
Western states are not vassals on some vast medieval estate owned
by absentee landlords in Washington, but this proposal would treat
us as such,'' Sullivan said.
   The governor, who is a Democrat, said he has urged that this
``ill-conceived idea'' be reconsidered.
   The symposium featuring speakers from across the nation is to
discuss various issues involving managing land and wildlife in the
Greater Yellowstone area. About 300 people attended the first
morning of the conference, which runs through Saturday morning.
   Sullivan said management of the more than 12 million acres of
federal land in and around Yellowstone is complicated by a mix of
land forms and controls, including 85 federal laws and executive
orders.
   ``These mandates vary widely, from the strict constraints in the
wilderness acts to the more production-oriented multiple-use laws.
Additionally, nine major forest plans and park master plans guide
the management of individual administrative units in the region,''
he said.
   Part of the conference's mission is to discuss how management of
the park can be coordinated better.
   Sullivan said he hoped participants would consider how to
protect the economy of Wyoming while protecting the future of the
park.
   ``The national parks and wilderness areas contribute
significantly to the tourism industry becoming increasingly
important to a state reeling from the impacts on energy and
agriculture economies,'' he said.
</TEXT>
