<HEAD>D.C. Mayor's Friend Indicted</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Charles Lewis, former Virgin Islands official
and friend of District of Columbia Mayor Marion Barry Jr., was
indicted today on 10 felony counts stemming from Barry's visits to
his hotel room last December.
   The grand jury indicted Lewis, who also is facing cocaine
possession charges in the Virgin Islands, on three counts of
cocaine possession and seven counts of giving false statements to
the grand jury.
   The perjury charges center on questions Lewis was asked about
visits Barry made to his hotel room and what went on there,
according to sources close to the case.
   On Dec. 22 police were inexplicably called off an attempt to
make an undercover drug purchase from Lewis, 48, a former city
government employee, after Barry showed up at his hotel room. Barry
has acknowledged contacting police officials looking into the
affair but has said he was only trying to speed up the probe.
   The grand jury also was hearing testimony on a joint personnel
project involving the D.C. and Virgin Islands governments. Lewis,
the project's director, was fired a year ago after Virgin Islands
officials expressed concern about cost overruns.
   Lewis is in the Virgin Islands awaiting trial April 17 on two
counts of possession of a controlled substance with intent to
distribute.
   He was arrested March 3 in a St. Thomas hotel room after
allegedly selling 24 bags of crack cocaine to a female FBI
undercover agent.
   Barry, who has described Lewis as a friend, had no comment on
the indictment.
</TEXT>
