<FIRST>r w PM-PanAmFlight 4thLd-Writethru a0582 04-13 0503</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Pan Am Flight, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0582,470</SECOND>
<HEAD>Investigators Looking At Several Suspects In Pan Am Bombing</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts graf 8, Meanwhile the, with lord advocate saying there
has been a narrowing of the investigation.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal investigators have identified several
passengers who may have unwittingly carried aboard the bomb that
blew up Pan Am Flight 103 over Scotland on Dec. 21, a Bush
administration official said today.
   CBS-TV news reported Wednesday that suspicion for having planted
the bomb was focused on a member of the Popular Front for the
Liberation of Palestine-General Command who is a relative of Hafez
Dalkamoni, who CBS said reportedly set up the network that carried
out the attack.
   An administration official knowledgeable about the investigation
disputed the CBS account that investigators believe the passenger
who unwittingly carried the bomb was Khalid Jaafar, a young
American-Lebanese college student returning to Michigan from
Frankfurt for the Christmas holidays.
   Federal Bureau of Investigation agents have questioned Jaafar's
parents at the family-run gas station in Detroit but the parents
insist he was not involved.
   The official said Jaafar was only one of several passengers
suspected of unwittingly bringing the explosive aboard. ``And no
one in the Popular Front is talking,'' said the official, who spoke
on conditionof anonymity.
   Another government source said the ``chief theory'' of
investigators is that the bombing was the work of the
Syrian-sponsored Popular Front for the Liberation of
Palestine-General Command.
   Investigators theorize that the terrorist group, headed by Ahmed
Jibril, may have carried out the attack at the request of Iran,
said the source, who also spoke on condition of anonymity.
   Meanwhile, the lord advocate of Scotland, Lord Fraser, said in a
statement in London that ``there has been a narrowing in the focus
of the inquiry but it would be inadvisable for me to comment on
these reports at this stage.''
   CBS said many of the leads in the case are coming from a member
of the Popular Front for the Liberation of Palestine who is
cooperating with investigators.
   It said the Popular Front has its headquarters in Syria but the
investigation has uncovered evidence linking the Pan Am bombing to
Iran.
   The London Daily Telegraph reported investigators have narrowed
the number of people suspected of having been duped into carrying
the bomb aboard to between three and five American passport holders
who probably joined the flight in Frankfurt.
   It said FBI agents are searching European cities to find the
terrorist who gave the passenger the radio-cassette player in which
investigators have confirmed the bomb was placed.
   The Pan Am jumbo jet crashed in southern Scotland, killing all
259 people aboard and 11 other people on the ground.
   Dalkamoni was in prison at the time of the bombing, having been
picked up last October following a raid on one of his safe houses.
Along with weapons, German police found three Toshiba radio
cassette players similar to the one used to blow up Pan Am 103, CBS
said.
</TEXT>
