<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Prison     04-13 0368</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Prison,0378</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Thwart Hostage Incident at Prison; Kill Inmate</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN-THOR DAHLBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two armed convicts fled a high-security prison
colony in a bus after seizing eight hostages, but police killed one
of the men and wounded the other, and all captives were released
unharmed, Tass said Thursday.
   The men _ one a convicted murderer and the other a convicted
robber _ entered the Ukrainian prison colony's administrative
building Wednesday morning armed with homemade firearms and knives,
the official news agency said.
   The incident occurred about 500 miles south of Moscow in the
Voroshilovgrad region.
   According to Tass, the men took eight female employees hostage,
then barricaded themselves in the building and demanded a bus and
guarantees they would be allowed to leave the prison.
   Regional police and KGB chiefs began negotiating with the
inmates and persuaded them to release two hostages, ``but the
criminals wouldn't set the others free unless authorities agreed to
their demands,'' Tass said.
   It identified the inmates as V. Maximov, serving a 15-year term
for murder and theft, and O. Korzh, sentenced to eight years in
prison for robbery and malicious hooliganism. It said both were
repeat offenders.
   After authorities decided to meet the demands, a bus took the
men and their remaining hostages out of the penal colony.
Authorities tried again to negotiate with the men as the bus neared
the highway, Tass said.
   The criminals then demanded the release of another inmate and
threatened to kill one of the hostages immediately if the demand
was not met. At that point, police decided to act, Tass said.
   ``A carefully planned operation sprang into life,'' it said.
``Korzh was killed on the spot and Maximov wounded.'' It said all
the hostages were freed unharmed.
   On Dec. 1, a team of men commandeered a bus of children on a
field trip to the Caucasus city of Ordzhonikidze, and traded them
for drugs, money and a flight to Israel. Israel, which has no
diplomatic relations with Moscow, allowed the plane to land, but
deported the hijackers the next day. The four men, plus an
accomplice, were sentenced to prison terms of up to 15 years on
March 17.
</TEXT>
