<FIRST>u w PM-Bush-Poland 1stLd-Writethru a0584 04-13 0390</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush-Poland, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0584,390</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush to Announce Economic Aid Measures for Poland, Source Says</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts graf 3, Another official, with Bush considering a trip
to Poland.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush will travel to a
Polish-American community in Michigan to announce economic aid
measures aimed at demonstrating U.S. gratitude for reform steps
undertaken by the communist government in Warsaw, an administration
source said today.
   This official, declining to be named publicly, said Bush will
visit the Detroit enclave of Hamtramck, which is roughly 60 percent
Polish-American, to outline the administration's plans on Monday.
   Another official, also speaking anonymously, said consideration
is being given to a trip by Bush to Poland, although no time frame
was suggested. ``The option is still in abeyance,'' the official
said, adding that no trip plans would be announced during Monday's
Michigan appearance. Bush visited Poland in September 1987, just
days before formally announcing his presidential candidacy.
   The Warsaw government recently reached agreement with Solidarity
leader Lech Walesa to legalize the trade union movement that was
outlawed during a martial law crackdown in 1981 and scheduled the
first free elections in the country since the end of World War II.
   Bush hailed the April 5 accord, and administration officials had
signaled in recent days that plans were afoot to reward the Warsaw
government with unspecified economic measures.
   Speculation has centered on granting Poland trade advantages
under the General System of Preferences (GSP) and taking steps to
encourage private investment in the Eastern European nation through
the Overseas Private Investment Corp.
   A U.S. aid package to economically beleaguered Poland could
include tariff exemptions under the GSP that would increase exports
to the United States.
   The trip Monday would be Bush's first visit to Michigan since
being elected president last November.
   ``The president needed a backdrop to address the Polish-American
community about the changes in Poland,'' Hamtramck City Council
President Paul Odrobina told the Detroit Free Press. He said White
House advance personnel told him that Bush ``wants to make an
announcement about the American government's policy toward Poland.''
   In 1981 and 1982, the U.S. government imposed economic sanctions
against Poland following the declaration of martial law and the
outlawing of Solidarity.
   Some sanctions were lifted in 1987, after the Polish government
moved toward a reconciliation with the union.
</TEXT>
