<FILEID>AP-NR-04-13-89 1315EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Flight103-Losses     04-13 0260</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Flight 103-Losses,0266</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pan Am Says Lockerbie Crash Expected to Cost $50 Million</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Flight 103</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The bombing of Pan Am Flight 103
will cost the airline about $50 million, a company official said
Thursday.
   That estimate includes the loss of the Boeing 747, a drop in
passenger traffic on some routes and the anticipated cost of
lawsuits filed after the crash on Dec. 21, said Peter T. McHugh,
senior vice president for marketing for Pan American World Airways.
   ``We don't have the exact figures yet, but we expect that sum to
be about $50 million,'' McHugh told reporters.
   Bookings have rebounded somewhat, however, because of the
Eastern Airlines strike, which ``amounted to an increased earnings
of $50 million,'' he said.
   McHugh said the losses from the bombing would not threaten the
airline because Pan Am had a cash reserve fund of $285 million at
the end of 1988.
   According to McHugh, the airline expects to spend about $15
million this year to improve security, plus an additional $6
million for installation of more devices to detect plastic
explosives.
   British officials have traced the crash of Flight 103 to what
they believe was a radio cassette player packed with plastic
explosives and an air pressure-sensitive detonator. The plane
exploded as it flew over Lockerbie, Scotland, killing all 259
aboard and 11 people on the ground.
   Pan Am bookings decreased by 10 percent during the first quarter
of this year because of the Lockerbie crash, said Siegfried
Ruffert, head of Pan Am's office in Frankfurt.
</TEXT>
