<FIRST>u i PM-Poland 1stLd-Writethru a0583 04-13 0611</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Poland, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0583,0627</SECOND>
<HEAD>Walesa Pressed To Run For Presidency</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to CORRECT that Walesa says he considering the presidency,
not a seat in the newly created Senate. No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lech Walesa _ whose Solidarity trade union
helped force the government to adopt sweeping, democratic reforms _
said today his supporters want him to run for the newly created
post of president.
   In a telephone interview from his home in Gdansk, Walesa said he
would not run in June for a seat on the newly created Senate. But
he said he may not refuse if a member of the existing Sejm or the
new Senate nominates him when the two houses of parliament meet
later this year to elect a new president.
   If that doesn't happen, Walesa said, he will probably run in the
next presidential election scheduled six years from now.
   ``I am a man of big interests,'' he said. ``I'm being strongly
pressed ... And I plan to be a candidate for the highest government
body (presidency) that is going to be in Poland.''
   Before today, the electrician, who won the Nobel Peace Prize
after founding Solidarity, had said he wanted to concentrate on
union issues.
   ``Solidarity plans to win these elections as much as is
possible. The elections will tell exactly who is right. I wish well
to all. Let the better candidates win,'' Walesa told reporters at
his home earlier today.
   Also today, Solidarity filed an application with the government
requesting that it be made legal again after a seven-year ban.
   In another development, Poland's leader, Gen. Wojciech
Jaruzelski, met with Roman Catholic primate Cardinal Jozef Glemp to
discuss relations between his communist government and the dominant
religion in Poland.
   Walesa said he expects the Warsaw Regional Court, where
Solidarity applied today, to register the union by Monday, thus
formally ending the ban.
   ``We are in a very good mood,'' Tadeusz Mazowiecki, the
opposition leader who negotiated trade union freedoms, told
reporters outside the court after he filed the application for
Solidarity.
   ``We do hope registration will take place within the nearest
days, that the factory and local commissions will be able to get
organized without any obstacles, and Solidarity will return to life
as a powerful union,'' he said.
   Today's events were made possible by a historic agreement
reached April 5 by communist authorities and the opposition.
   After two months of talks, the government agreed to legalize
Solidarity in exchange for the union's participation in elections
which still guarantee the communist-led coalition a majority.
   Solidarity, which has previously advocated election boycotts,
met today to discuss which candidates it will support.
   The voting will create a new 100-member Senate. Opposition
candidates also can run for 35 percent of the 460 seats in the
existing Sejm. The rest will be guaranteed for the communist-led
coalition. Anyone who can get 3,000 voters' signatures can run in
the elections.
   The PAP state news agency reported today the balloting will take
place June 4 with run-off voting June 18.
   PAP reported that Jaruzelski and Glemp discussed regularizing
the status of the church, relations between the government and
Vatican and the elections.
   Work on a law to regulate the legal status of the church and
``pave the wave for full normalization of relations between Poland
and the Holy See'' has been completed, said a joint communique
published by PAP.
   Vatican sources last year said the Polish government offered to
provide a legal basis for church activities in exchange for
establishing diplomatic relations. An agreement that existed
between the church and Polish government before World War II was
not renewed after the communists seized power.
</TEXT>
