<HEAD>Two Planes Lost In Navy Training Crash, One Killed</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with two pilots killed, other detail. CORRECTS
location of crash to 50 miles sted 15 miles north of airfield. No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MACON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A pair of Navy training jets crashed today
in a rural area, killing two pilots, officials said. Two other
airman ejected from the planes and were taken to a hospital.
   The Navy did not say whether the two aircraft had collided when
the crash occurred at approximately 9 a.m., some 50 miles north of
the Meridian Naval Air Station. However, Lt. j.g. Mary Chamberlain,
spokeswoman at the station, did confirm that the two planes were
involved in a training mission at the time.
   She said both planes went down in about the same area, which
local authorities said was near the U.S. 45 Bypass highway about
seven miles south of Macon in rural east-central Mississippi.
   The names of the airmen were not released pending notification
of relatives, said Chamberlain.
   There was no immediate word on the two survivors, who were flown
by search and rescue helicopters to Noxubee General Hospital in
Macon, a few miles north of the crash site. Officials at the
hospital declined to give information on the conditions of the two.
   Chamberlain said the airmen were members of air station's
Training Squadron 19 and two piots each were in T-2C Buckeye jets,
aircraft used to train Navy and Marine pilots.
   Chamberlain said local and state authorities had joined air
station rescue personnel in rushing to the crash site. She said an
investigation into the crash was already under way.
   Witnesses reported seeing at least three parachutes, but Navy
officials could not confirm that report.
</TEXT>
