<FIRST>r w AM-InventorsoftheYear     04-13 0332</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Inventors of the Year,330</SECOND>
<HEAD>Four Californians Share Inventor Award</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writwe</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Researchers who developed a drug to dissolve
blood clots in heart attack victims were honored Thursday as
Inventors of the Year for 1989.
   David V. Goeddel, William J. Kohr, Diane Pennica and Gordon A.
Vehar, researchers for Genentech Inc. of South San Francisco,
Calif., shared the honor presented annually by the Intellectual
Property Owners Foundation, which represents holders of patents,
copyrights and trademarks.
   The team developed the drug known as t-PA _ human tissue
plasminogen activator. It is used to help dissolve blood clots
immediately following heart attacks.
   The foundation, which works to encourage innovation, announced
its awards at a news conference. The winners of the top award will
share a $4,000 prize.
   ``Invention is the heart of American society,'' commented Robert
P. Freese, one of several other inventors also honored by the
foundation.
   Among those listed as ``distinguished'' inventors of 1989 were
Freese and several co-workers who developed an optical computer
storage disk capable of holding up to 1,000 times more information
than the popular floppy disks now in use.
   Developers of the disk were Freese, Richard N. Gardner and
Thomas A. Rinehart of Alphatronix Inc., at Research Triangle Park,
N.C., and Leslie H. Johnson of the 3M Company in St. Paul, Minn.
   Others receiving distinguished inventor honors were:
   _James L. Ferguson of Menlo Park, Calif., who invented a device
using liquid crystals to protect eyes from laser beams.
   Ferguson said his product scatters laser light and can be used
to protect scientists working in laboratories and also to help
military personnel who could be blinded by laser weapons or even by
laser range-finding devices.
   _Charles A. Chidsey of Boulder, Wyo., and Guinter Kahn of North
Miami Beach, Fla., who developed minoxidil, a drug to treat
baldness.
   Kahn said development of the drug has not curtailed ``snake oil
salesmen'' who have been peddling fake baldness cures for thousands
of years.
</TEXT>
