<FILEID>AP-NR-04-13-89 1407EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a PM-Bush 3rdLd-Writethru a0599 04-13 1066</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0599,1,040</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Says Will, Not Money Needed to Improve Schools</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 2nd graf to update that speech delivered; inserts 3 grafs
on stop at school after 14th graf, ``Our goal''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERENCE HUNT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP White House Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNION, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush said today Americans should
try to correct the ills of the nation's schools by relying less on
the taxpayers' wallets and ``more on the collective will.''
   ``A nation that worships money _ or sees money as a cure for all
that ails it _ is a society in peril,'' Bush told an educational
conference here.
   ``More spending isn't the only right answer or even the best
answer,'' he said. ``What we need is better value for what we spend.
   ``What we need ... is a shared determination on the part of
every American to get involved with our schools,'' Bush added. ``We
must reestablish the value of teaching and learning in this
country.''
   After abruptly scrapping a vacation in Maine, Bush decided to go
ahead with a trip to Union High School here to drum up support for
a $441 million education package intended to reward good teachers
and schools.
   The program has been sharply criticized by Democrats as
inadequate.
   In his remarks, Bush called for ``partial deregulation of
education,'' saying: ``We want to waive some regulations for poorer
communities, allowing them to pool state and federal funds in
exchange for higher accountability and performance.''
   He did not elaborate, but Education Secretary Lauro Cavazos told
reporters on Air Force One en route here that the proposal was
designed to ``get funds to local schools without a lot of
paperwork.''
   Cavazos said the proposal was not contained in the president's
education package last week but would become part of the
administration's overall education program. ``There are so many
regulations and so much bureaucracy, we've got to clear some of
this away,'' he said.
   Bush spoke of the work of volunteers in schools and said, ``One
need matches another, and a wonderful thing happens. You come up
with an answer that money just can't buy.
   ``That's one reason we need to rely less on the collective
wallet and more on our collective will,'' the president said.
   Bush told the educators that children always have been taught
about the exploration of new frontiers, such as the first trips
across the ocean, the move West across America and journeys into
space.
   ``But we must now draw the attention of a new generation to a
larger, almost limitless horizon: the frontier of the mind,'' he
said.
   ``Our goal for education must be as ambitious as it's been for
the West or for space exploration or for any other American
frontier.''
   Thousands of flag-waving children lined the streets of this
residential community to cheer the president as his limousine
passed by.
   Bush stopped his motorcade briefly at Hamilton School to meet
Gina Marie Sisco, a sixth-grade pupil who had written him last week
to complain that she was not among those students who would get a
chance to meet him.
   In her letter, Gina said the students selected to see Bush were
chosen on the basis of winning the President's Academic Fitness
Award. ``I am proud of them but I feel it's unfair to show you just
the smart kids,'' she wrote.
   After greeting the girl, Bush shook hands for four minutes with
school children before traveling on to his speech.
   Today's stop in Union was supposed to have been the jumping-off
point for a three-day trip to Bush's seaside home in Kennebunkport,
Maine.
   However, the vacation segment was canceled Wednesday when Bush
decided to remain in Washington during a visit by his son Jeb and
his wife Columba, who are in town from Florida.
   ``Basically, they just didn't want to go,'' said White House
press secretary Marlin Fitzwater. ``Presidents have the right to do
that.''
   Fitzwater said cancellation of the trip also meant Bush would be
on hand in case White House and congressional negotiators reached
agreement on a budget and deficit-reduction package.
   Bush's education proposal calls for cash rewards for successful
schools and good teachers, scholarship funds for students gifted in
science and math, financial grants to encourage magnet schools
offering specialized educational programs and special aid for urban
school districts with severe drug problems.
   It also would provide funds allowing states to set up programs
using teachers who lack standard education courses and other
certification requirements.
   Today's trip came on the heels of a speech and
question-and-answer session by Bush on Wednesday before the
convention of the American Society of Newspaper Editors, where he
outlined a series of steps to tighten ethical rules for Congress,
judges and the executive branch.
   Proposing a major change in the way congressional races are
financed, Bush called for a ban on campaign contributions by
political action committees. In last year's congressional races,
PACs spent more than $151 million directly on House and Senate
candidates. Democrats received the lion's share of that money, $99
million.
   Responding to questions on other issues, Bush said for the first
time the federal government may have been too slow in taking a
major role in cleaning up the Alaska oil spill.
   ``Maybe I should accept some criticism'' for not acting a week
sooner, said Bush, who last Friday put the government in virtual
control of the cleanup operation and authorized federal troops to
help out.
   On the other hand, he said the federal overnment ``moved much
more quickly and more boldly than it gets credit for.''
   Bush rejected suggestions that the spill should derail
administration hopes of oil and gas exploration in environmentally
sensitive areas.
   ``I simply do not want this disaster ... to weaken the national
security interest by making us further and further dependent on
foreign oil,'' he said. ``We're about up to 50 percent now and that
is not a good enough standard.''
   He was asked if he would give a full accounting of his role in
the Reagan administration's secret supply effort for the Nicaraguan
Contras, once the trial of former White House aide Oliver North is
concluded.
   ``I think I've given a full accounting,'' Bush responded.
Referring to stories coming out of the North trial, Bush said, ``I
don't like reading charges that I happen to feel are untrue but I
have to stand on that. And that just goes with the territory.''
</TEXT>
