<FIRST>r w AM-Bush-Poland     04-13 0527</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Poland,500</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush To Reward Warsaw For Reform Measures</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Poland, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush will reward the communist
government of Poland for newly instituted reform measures,
including its commitment to hold free elections for the first time
since 1946, an administration source said Thursday.
   Bush has chosen the Detroit Polish-American enclave of Hamtramck
as the setting to announce a series of measures aimed at
stimulating Poland's beleaguered economy, said the source, who
spoke on the grounds of anonymity.
   This official also indicated that consideration was still being
given to a Bush trip to the Eastern European nation, although no
general time frame has been established.
   Bush, as vice president, visited Poland during a nine-nation
European tour in September 1987, meeting with Solidarity leader
Lech Walesa and leaders of the communist government, just before
formally launching his campaign for the presidency.
   The Bush administration on April 5 hailed the agreement to
reinstate the Solidarity trade union movement as a legal force in
Polish society and its companion agreement to free elections in
June for a two-house parliament, in which some seats will be set
aside for Solidarity representatives.
   Walesa _ whose Solidarity organization helped force the
government to adopt sweeping, democratic reforms _ said Thursday
that his supporters want him to run for the newly created post of
president.
   In a telephone interview from his home in Gdansk, Walesa said he
would not run in June for a seat in the newly created Senate. But
he said he may not refuse if a member of the existing Sejm or the
new Senate nominates him when the two houses of parliament meet
later this year to elect a new president.
   If that doesn't happen, Walesa said, he will probably run in the
next presidential election scheduled six years from now.
   The White House hailed the April 5 accord as a ``historic step''
that would improve Polish-American relations.
   Speculation on new U.S. economic aid for Poland has centered on
granting the Warsaw government trade advantages under the General
System of Preferences (GSP) and steps to encourage private
investment in the Eastern European nation through the Overseas
Private Investment Corp.
   In 1981 and 1982, the U.S. government imposed economic sanctions
against Poland following the declaration of martial law and the
outlawing of the Solidarity trade union movement. Some sanctions
were lifted in 1987, after the Polish government moved toward a
reconciliation with the union. The United States, however, has
continued to pressure Western banks and governments against
extending credits to Warsaw.
   A Polish government spokesman said last week that it was asking
the United States to give the green light to loans from the
International Monetary Fund, the World Bank and Western governments.
   ``What we want does not lie in the bilateral range of things,
not trade,'' said Polish Embassy spokesman Mierik Miernik.
   Poland's efforts to rebuild its shattered economy have been
hampered by an inflation rate running from 60 percent to 100
percent and by a $39 billion foreign debt. The Polish government
would like U.S. support in persuading bankers and governments to
reschedule repayment of the loans, Miernik said.
</TEXT>
