<FIRST>r w AM-RetailSales     04-13 0663</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Retail Sales,650</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sluggish Sales Seen as Sign of Economic Slowdown</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NANCY BENAC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Retail sales edged up a meager 0.1 percent
last month after dropping sharply in February, the government said
Thursday in a report analysts cited as evidence that cautious
consumer spending is moderating economic growth.
   Sales totaled a seasonally adjusted $139.42 billion last month,
held back by sluggish business at department stores and auto
dealerships, the Commerce Department reported. Sales had plunged
0.6 percent in February.
   The weak figures for the past two months are consistent with a
series of recent government reports that suggest slower economic
growth lies ahead as the record peacetime expansion stretches into
its seventh year.
   ``I don't think we are going to see a big slowdown or a caving
in, but there is definitely a softer tone to growth and it is being
driven by softer consumer spending,'' said economist Allen Sinai of
the Boston Co.
   White House press secretary Marlin Fitzwater said the retail
sales figures ``provide further evidence of a pattern of slower
consumer spending in recent months. We continue to believe the
economy is sound, showing steady growth with low inflation.''
   For the third straight month, overall sales in March were held
down by a decline in spending on autos, which account for almost
one-fourth of the retail total.
   Automotive sales edged down 0.1 percent in March after declining
2.5 percent in February and 1.9 percent in January. It was the
first time auto sales have dropped for three straight months in
nearly five years.
   Carmakers in recent weeks have launched a new round of incentive
programs in hopes of luring customers back to showrooms during the
prime spring selling season despite higher interest rates for loans.
   Excluding the automotive category, retail sales last month still
were up just 0.2 percent for March after holding virtually even
during February.
   Retail sales account for about one-third of overall economic
activity and are closely watched as a measure of the economy's
health.
   Analysts said the weakness in retail spending has occurred even
though consumer confidence remains high and income growth has been
strong, and appears to reflect the effects of higher interest
rates, rising inflation and a tapering off of demand after years of
heavy spending.
   ``People are probably just taking a deep breath and stepping
back a bit,'' said economist Lea Tyler of the WEFA Group in Bala
Cynwyd, Pa. ``I would interpret it as a bit of belt-tightening on
the part of the consumers.''
   Many analysts expect the economy to lose steam this year in
response to a campaign by the Federal Reserve Board to push up
interest rates and thus dampen demand and restrain inflation. Some
economists have expressed concern that the Fed's campaign could
unintentionally tip the country into a recession.
   Ms. Tyler said that based on recent reports showing weakness in
consumer spending and other sectors of the economy, ``the risk of a
recession arriving some time in the latter half of this year or
early next year has risen.''
   However, she said the economy is more likely to experience
slower growth and ``skirt a recession without actually dipping into
one.''
   In the key category of department and other general merchandise
stores, sales fell 1.2 percent in March to $15.6 billion after
declining 1.5 percent in February.
   Sales of durable goods, ``big ticket'' items expected to last
three or more years, were down 0.2 percent last month after
plunging 1.7 percent in February. Sales of non-durable goods,
meanwhile, rose 0.3 percent in March after climbing 0.2 percent
during the previous month.
   Among the categories of goods to report sales increases last
month were: food and grocery stores, up 0.2 percent; gasoline
service stations, up 0.5 percent; and bars and restaurants, up 0.5
percent.
   Categories posting declines included building and hardware
stores, down 1.9 percent; furniture stores, down 0.2 percent;
clothing and accessory stores, down 0.4 percent; and drug stores,
down 0.2 percent.
</TEXT>
