<DOCNO> AP890413-0126 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-13-89 1436EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a PM-Fusion-Wash 1stLd-Writethru a0614 04-13 0621</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Fusion-Wash, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0614,0632</SECOND>
<HEAD>Washington Researchers Duplicate Fusion Experiment, With Control</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 11 grafs to UPDATE with detail from news conference.
Picks up 9th graf pvs, `Harold Furth...'.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Fusion</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE TIBBITS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two University of Washington researchers detected
indications of cold fusion in an experiment they conducted with
heavy water, but could not get the same results using a control
experiment with ordinary water, the researchers said today.
   Graduate students Van L. Eden and Wei Liu said they did not
duplicate exactly a highly publicized experiment by University of
Utah chemist B. Stanley Pons and Martin Fleischmann of the
University of Southampton, England. Pons and Fleischmann said they
apparently produced nuclear fusion in a tabletop experiment using
ordinary lab equipment.
   But Eden and Liu said they did get indications that fusion may
have taken place in their experiment last week.
   Eden said that in their experiement, a mass spectrometer
detected a possible indicator of tritium, a radioactive isotope of
hydrogen commonly produced in fusion reactions.
   The indicator was found when the experiment was run using
deuterium, a hydrogen isotope found in seawater and known as
``heavy water.'' Eden said the indicator was not detected when the
test was repeated with ordinary water.
   Both researchers, who specialize in molecular studies, cautioned
the results were preliminary and needed review by other scientists.
They also said they had not ruled out any other explanations for
what they observed.
   They said scientists expect a fusion reaction to produce
substantial quantities of neutrons, but they did not detect any,
although they were not using a particularly sensitive detector for
them.
   The pair used a test tube containing deuterium oxide in which a
palladium electrode and gold wire were placed and connected to a
power source. The palladium electrode, actually a hollow rod with
one end sealed, was connected to a vacuum chamber, which in turn
was connected to the mass spectrometer, which detects indications
of nuclear particles.
   Two weeks ago, Pons and Fleischmann announced they had achieved
fusion at room temperature using ordinary laboratory equipment.
   The announcement stunned and confused researchers around the
world, some of whom have spent more than 25 years and millions of
dollars trying to develop controlled nuclear fusion.
   Pons and Fleischmann said their experiment used a rod of
palladium and a coil of platinum immersed in a beaker of ``heavy
water'' _ water made with deuterium, an isotope of hydrogen. When
electricity was applied to the coil for about 100 hours, it forced
deuterium atoms into the palladium until the atoms fused, producing
energy in the form of heat, Pons said.
   Harold Furth, director of plasma physics at Princeton
University, appeared with Pons on Wednesday at a meeting of the
American Chemical Society in Dallas.
   Furth said top physicists will not take the Utah findings
seriously until the precise process involved is explained and
demonstrated with control experiments, and some experts believe the
energy detected in the Utah experiment is actually a chemical
reaction that is not understood.
   But Furth said that if the experiment worked using heavy water
but not ordinary water, it would suggest the reaction actually did
involve some sort of deuterium fusion.
   Pons admitted he was not sure how the experiment causes fusion
and exactly what role each of the chemicals play in producing
energy.
   Fusion, the energy process that powers the sun, the stars and
the hydrogen bomb, holds promise of becoming the ultimate energy
source.
   The fusion of atoms in only 1-250th of an ounce of deuterium
would give an energy equivalent of 300 gallons of gasoline, and
deuterium can be extracted from the oceans for only pennies per
gallon of seawater.
</TEXT>
