<FILEID>AP-NR-04-13-89 2023EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Colombia-Drugs     04-13 0358</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Colombia-Drugs,0370</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Find Drug Ring Torture Center</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAVIER BAENA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police raided a farmhouse equipped with
torture chambers, tunnels to hide kidnap victims and a shooting
range, and they said the complex was used by a paramilitary group
linked to the Medellin drug cartel.
   In the raid Wednesday, police said they arrested 10 gunmen and
freed two kidnap victims from the center in a country home near
Envigado, 10 miles from Medellin, Colombia's second-largest city.
   Members of the paramilitary group were warned of the raid by a
sophisticated alarm system, and at least 10 escaped, said Col.
Antonio Sanchez Vargas, the police chief of Medellin.
   Police found powerful communications equipment, weapons and cars
at the site, he said.
   Martin Alonso Alvarez, one of two people released from the
tunnels, said he was kidnapped Wednesday and beaten by gunmen who
asked him if he belonged to the Cali drug cartel.
   The Cali cartel is Colombia's second-largest drug trafficking
ring and is battling the Medellin group for control of the
billion-dollar New York drug market. Medellin reportedly is the
world's largest drug ring and controls about 80 percent of U.S.
drug markets.
   More than 120 people have died in the 15-month battle between
the cartels, and there have been more than 30 dynamite and firebomb
attacks against property owned by leaders of the rings, army
officials said.
   Between them, the cartels control 13 private armies and about
2,000 men, said Gen. Miguel Maza Marquez, the head of the secret
police, in a report to President Virgilio Barco.
   Maza Marquez said at least one of the paramilitary groups was
trained in Puerto Boyaca, 70 miles northeast of Bogota, by British
and Israeli experts. He did not elaborate.
   Drug trafficking rings trained the paramilitary groups to
protect themselves and kill those who interfere with their drug
business, according to Maza Marquez.
   Last week, another training center also linked to the Medellin
cartel was discovered on a farm near Puerto Lopez, 90 miles east of
Bogota.
   On the grounds, police found secret tunnels, training centers
for hired gunmen and the graves of five people.
</TEXT>
