<FIRST>r a AM-DWIArrests     04-13 0253</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-DWI Arrests,0262</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Arrest One for Drunken Driving, Get Two Free</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BREWSTER, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   State troopers pulled over a motorist,
charged him with drunken driving, then filed the same charge
against his friend and then his sister when they came to the police
station to pick him up.
   ``It's strange but it happens,'' state police Trooper Edward
Meyers said Thursday.
   Steven Finning, 22, of Danbury, Conn., was pulled over early
Monday for speeding and driving erratically on Interstate 84. He
was charged with driving while intoxicated.
   A friend of Finning's, Robert Fuda, 21, was driving behind him
and saw the arrest. He followed the patrol car to the state police
barracks, according to Finning's sister, Eve.
   After troopers talked with Fuda, he too was charged with driving
while intoxicated. Both men refused to take breath tests, Meyers
said.
   The men then called Eve Finning. When she arrived, troopers
began questioning her.
   ``They said my eyes looked glossy,'' Miss Finning said. ``I
mean, it was 4 a.m. They charged me, too, and I definitely was not
drunk.''
   She agreed to take the sobriety test, failed it and also was
charged with drunken driving, Meyers said.
   Anyone driving with a blood-alcohol level above 0.10 percent in
New York state is considered legally drunk. Meyers said he could
not say what Miss Finning's blood alcohol level was.
   All three were arraigned and released on $100 bail.
   Miss Finning said they called another friend to come pick them
up. That friend was not arrested.
</TEXT>
