<FIRST>u w AM-DrugPolicy-Contras     04-13 0736</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Drug Policy-Contras,730</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kerry Says Independent Counsel Checking Contra-Drug Probe Obstruction</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-North Trial Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Iran-Contra independent counsel is
investigating allegations that Reagan administration officials
obstructed a Senate investigation into links between the Nicaraguan
Contras and drug traffickers, Sen. John Kerry, D-Mass., said
Thursday.
   Kerry, who directed the investigation, said several people who
testified before his Foreign Relations subcommittee informed him
they were interviewed by investigators for independent counsel
Lawrence Walsh.
   A former Justice Department official and the former U.S.
attorney in Miami both told The Associated Press they were
interviewed by Walsh's investigators. Both denied any wrongdoing.
   Walsh's office, which is currently prosecuting former National
Security Council aide Oliver North, declined to comment.
   Kerry mentioned the obstruction investigation at a news
conference that he called to discuss the 437-page report of his
Subcommittee on Terrorism, Narcotics and International Operations.
   Despite Kerry's allegations of obstruction, the committee held
extensive hearings last year, concluding in its report that the
Reagan administration ``delayed, halted or interfered'' with its
own international anti-drug operations in order to protect its
Central America policy.
   The report said the administration looked the other way when law
enforcement agencies learned that drug traffickers were protected
and aided by some Nicaraguan rebels, known as Contras, by members
of the Honduran military, Panamanian leader Manuel Antonio Noriega
and Bahamian officials.
   The report also included a section on the alleged obstruction,
saying the Justice Department ``provided information to the
committee that tended to discredit'' allegations about Contra drug
links.
   The department, according to the report, kept telling the
subcommittee ``the persons who had made the allegations ... had
significant credibility problems'' and ``there was no truth to the
allegations.''
   The subcommittee concluded, however, that such links existed and
devoted a large section of the report to them.
   The report said a former assistant U.S. attorney in Miami,
Jeffrey Feldman, told the subcommittee that he learned of possible
obstruction of Kerry's committee during a meeting with Justice
Department officials on Nov. 18, 1987.
   Feldman said department officials told him that representatives
of the Justice Department, the Drug Enforcement Administration and
the FBI met in 1986 ``to discuss how Sen. Kerry's efforts could be
undermined.''
   Feldman, who helped uncover secret U.S. aid to the Contras
during a congressional ban on such assistance, told Kerry's panel
that he believed the Justice Department may have delayed his
investigation, too.
   ``It made sense that if the department didn't support your
investigation, then they wouldn't support my investigation,'' the
report quotes Feldman as telling the subcommittee.
   Feldman's former boss Leon B. Kellner, who was U.S. attorney in
Miami, said in an interview he was questioned by a Walsh
investigator late last year.
   Kellner said the interview concerned a confidential transcript
of a committee executive session that found its way to Kellner's
files.
   He said he received the transcript from the Justice Department,
but added he could not remember who gave it to him. And the copy he
received, Kellner added, did not indicate ``it was the transcript
of an executive sesssion'' on the committee's Contra investigation.
   Kenneth P. Bergquist, an assistant secretary of the Navy who
formerly served in the Justice Department's congressional affairs
office, said, ``I can confirm I was interviewed by an FBI agent
making inquiries about obstruction of Kerry's committee, about a
month ago. The FBI agent was working for Walsh.''
   The Kerry report said Bergquist was among the Justice Department
officials who tried to discredit the information the committee was
receiving on the Contras.
   Bergquist called the obstruction charges ``patently ridiculous.
It is unbelievable. Kerry is very quick with charges and I'm tired
of his lame accusations.''
   Bergquist said he attended the 1986 Justice Department meeting
during which Feldman said there was talk of undermining the
committee. But Bergquist said, ``No one said that the purpose of
that meeting was to undermine anybody.''
   Kerry told the news conference that anti-drug efforts in the
Reagan administration took second place to foreign policy mainly
``for fear of jeopardizing the war in Nicaragua.'' But he said that
same war provided an ``opportunity for drug traffickers to link up
with the Contras _ and they did.''
   Sen. Mitch McConnell, R-Ky., ranking Republican on the
subcommittee, said in a written statement that while he agreed with
``substantial portions'' of the report, there were ``inaccuracies
in the representations of fact'' on the Contra-drug issue.
</TEXT>
