<FIRST>r w AM-Drugs-Peru     04-13 0357</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Drugs-Peru,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Campaign Against Peruvian Drug Traffickers Temporarily Suspended</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN SKORNECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. paramilitary campaign against
Peruvian drug traffickers has been suspended temporarily as the
agents assigned to the operation reinforce their base camp, the
State Department said Thursday.
   Operation Snowcap, which involves agents of the Drug Enforcement
Administration who advise Peru's Civil Guard in eradicating coca
fields and cocaine-processing labs, was suspended in mid-February,
said Catherine Shaw of the department's office of International
Narcotics Matters.
   ``The operation's been suspended since mid-February,'' she said.
``They're regrouping, looking for ways to make the base camp more
secure.''
   Ms. Shaw said she was not aware of any particular threats
against the agents, but said, ``There have been, over the years,
many threats against the eradication workers.''
   Twenty-seven Peruvians were killed several years ago in the
eradication program, but she said it was not clear if the
assailants were drug traffickers or members of the violent Maoist
Sendero Luminoso (Shining Path) guerrillas, a rebel group that has
gained strength in the past few years.
   In late January, U.S. officials said the chief security officer
at the embassy in Lima was shot and wounded while on a helicopter
inspection of the area.
   ``When we're conviced and the Peruvians are convinced (the base
camp) is safe, we'll resume work,'' Ms. Shaw said. ``We're hoping
it won't be too far in the future.''
   Cornelius Dougherty, a DEA spokesman, said, ``There has been no
actual withdrawal of DEA agents. There's just been the normal
rotation.'' Agents who participate in Operation Snowcap are all
volunteers who spend only 90 days in the country at a time.
   ``There's a group down there now,'' Dougherty said. Although
they aren't participating in eradication measures, ``there's other
kinds of work that can be done down there, such as intelligence,
that sort of thing,'' he said.
   Neither Ms. Shaw nor Dougherty would reveal how many agents are
involved in Operation Snowcap, which has operations in Peru and
Bolivia.
   The suspension was disclosed Wednesday by Rep. William J.
Hughes, D-N.J., at a hearing of the House judiciary subcommittee on
crime, which he chairs.
</TEXT>
