<FIRST>r w AM-Justice-Antitrust     04-13 0205</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Justice-Antitrust,200</SECOND>
<HEAD>Assistant Attorney General Rule Leaving for Law Firm</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Assistant Attorney General Charles F. Rule,
who heads the Justice Department's antitrust division, will leave
April 28 to become a partner at the Covington &amp; Burling law firm
where he will work on antitrust matters, the law firm announced
Thursday.
   At the 250-attorney law firm, Rule will counsel U.S. clients and
will help the firm's newly opened London office in advising foreign
clients affected by U.S. antitrust policy.
   Last week, Rule said in a speech to American Bar Association
antitrust lawyers that the ``internationalization of antitrust
regulation'' is the most significant antitrust development of the
decade.
   Rule, who will be leaving the department on his 34th birthday
and joining the law firm May 1, joined the antitrust division in
1982. He graduated from Vanderbilt University and earned his law
degree at the University of Chicago.
   A leading candidate to replace Rule is James F. Rill, a senior
partner at the Washington law firm of Collier, Shannon, Rill &amp;
Scott.
   Rill, 56, who has been a chairman of the American Bar
Association's antitrust section, was described by an administration
official as ``one of the most highly regarded guys in the antitrust
bar.''
