<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Army     04-13 0467</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Army,0480</SECOND>
<HEAD>Defense Minister Rejects Call for Small, All-Volunteer Army</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANN IMSE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The defense minister has rejected suggestions for
converting the Soviet armed forces into an all-volunteer unit half
its current size.
   ``I am shaken by the incompetence and light-mindedness of the
authors of such `innovations' when they approach the most important
state question, the guarantee of the security of the country,''
Dmitri T. Yazov said in a front-page signed article published
Thursday in the military newspaper Red Star.
   Yazov seemed to support the unilateral reductions already
announced by President Mikhail S. Gorbachev. They would cut the
armed forces by 500,000 men to 3,760,000. Yazov also said weapons
production is being cut by one-fifth.
   But he was sharply critical of suggestions the army could be cut
in half, indicating the top Soviet brass was in favor of
maintaining compulsory military service for males.
   Deferrals for university students were announced last month.
They still must serve in the armed forces after graduation,
although their term of service has been reduced to one year.
   A highly paid volunteer army would become an elite class in
society, contradicting the nature of a socialist army where
everyone is drafted, Yazov said. Ideals of duty to the country
would be replaced by materialism, he said.
   Yazov also said a volunteer army under capitalism serves the
interest of the ruling class _ a criticism that brings Communist
ideology back into a debate that often has centered on efficiency
and budget-cutting.
   Lt. Col. Alexander Savinkin opened the debate last fall with an
article in the Moscow News weekly calling for a smaller, more
professional, all-volunteer army with better training in
high-technology weaponry.
   Yazov said the current two- to three-year hitch is sufficient
for the average soldier to learn discipline and the use of certain
arms.
   A separate article in the Communist Party newspaper Pravda
written by the armed forces' deputy political director, Adm. A.
Sorokin, said one-fifth of the 500,000 troops cut from the military
would be officers, typically those with only a few years service.
Cadets in military academies also will be trimmed, he said.
   Generally, the troop cuts will be among older soldiers ready to
retire because they have qualified for pensions or received
apartments, Sorokin said.
   In addition, he wrote, ``We are not keeping a secret of the fact
that we are trying to get rid of those who are not in harmony with
morality, honor and duty.''
   Sorokin admitted that finding homes for 500,000 released
soldiers will be no easy task in a country already struggling with
a severe housing shortage.
   Plans have been made to build 7,500 apartments for former
officers, but for the rest, the Communist Party leadership and
local authorities ``must take urgent measures'' to find housing, he
said.
</TEXT>
