<FILEID>AP-NR-04-13-89 1623EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Flight103 1stLd-Writethru a0645 04-13 0718</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Flight 103, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0645,690</SECOND>
<HEAD>Probers Have Identified Those Who Unwittingly May Have Brought Bomb
Aboard</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Adds 3 grafs, Bush to visit Lockerbie.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal investigators have identified a
handful of passengers who unwittingly may have brought aboard the
bomb that blew up Pan Am Flight 103 over Scotland in December, a
Bush administration official said Thursday.
   CBS reported Wednesday that suspicion had centered on a member
of the Popular Front for the Liberation of Palestine-General
Command who is a relative of Hafez Dalkamoni. CBS said Dalkamoni
reportedly set up the network that carried out the attack in which
270 people, including 189 Americans, perished.
   An administration official knowledgeable about the investigation
disputed the CBS account that investigators had concluded the
passenger who carried the bomb aboard was Khalid Jaafar, a young
American-Lebanese college student returning to Michigan from
Frankfurt for the Christmas holidays.
   Federal Bureau of Investigation agents have questioned Jaafar's
parents at the family-run gas station in Detroit but the parents
insist he was not involved.
   The official said Jaafar was only one of several passengers
suspected of unwittingly bringing the explosive aboard. ``And no
one in the Popular Front is talking,'' said the official, who spoke
on condition of anonymity.
   Another government source said the ``chief theory'' of
investigators is that the bombing was the work of the
Syrian-sponsored Popular Front for the Liberation of
Palestine-General Command.
   Investigators theorize that the group, headed by Ahmed Jabril,
may have carried out the attack at the behest of Iran, said the
source, who also spoke on condition of anonymity.
   The group was identified Wednesday in a State Department
terrorism report to Congress as having carried out numerous
cross-border attacks against Israel and violently opposed to the
Palestine Liberation Organization.
   Jabril is identified as a former captain in the Syrian army. The
group is closely allied with Syria and probably receives directions
from Syria, its chief sponsor.
   CBS said many of the leads in the case are coming from a member
of the front who is cooperating with investigators. But the U.S.
official told The Associated Press that ``there is nothing that
links the command directly right now with Flight 103.''
   The London Daily Telegraph reported, meanwhile, that
investigators had narrowed the number of people suspected of being
duped into carrying the bomb aboard to three to five American
passport holders who probably joined the flight in Frankfurt.
   The newspaper said FBI agents were searching European cities to
find the terrorist who gave the passenger the radio-cassette player
in which investigators have confirmed the bomb was placed.
   Investigators have narrowed the probe's focus, the investigation
chief said Thursday. The Lord Advocate, Lord Fraser, Scotland's
chief law officer who is ultimately responsible for the crash
investigation, said in a statement:
   ``There has been a narrowing in the focus of the inquiry but it
would be inadvisable for me to comment on these reports at this
stage. Any statement I make on the progress of the investigation
must be based on firm evidence and not on the basis of comment or
conjecture attributed to official sources.
   ``If there is firm evidence which can be revealed without
prejudicing the inquiry or the prospects for a criminal
prosecution, disclosure of that will be authorized.''
   The Pan Am jumbo jet crashed in southern Scotland on Dec. 21,
killing all 259 people aboard and 11 people on the ground.
   Dalkamoni was in prison at the time, having been picked up last
October following a raid on one of his safe houses. Along with
weapons, German police found three Toshiba radio-cassette players
similar to the one used to blow up Pan Am 103, CBS said.
   Meanwhile, an administration source sadi Thursday that President
Bush will visit Lockerbie, stopping on the way back from a NATO
summit in Brussels, Belgium and visits to Italy, England and West
Germany. He is scheduled to leave Washington on May 26 and return
June 1 or 2.
   A White House survey team already has visited Lockerbie and an
advance team is expected to stop there within the next week for
further planning, said the source, speaking on condition of
anonymity.
   Bush recently met at the White House with a delegation of
relatives of victims of the Pan Am flight.
</TEXT>
