<FIRST>r w AM-ExtensionRecall     04-13 0202</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Extension Recall,200</SECOND>
<HEAD>Extension Power Strips Being Recalled</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A New Jersey company is recalling extension
power strips sold in North Carolina and the Washington, D.C., area
because they could give users a severe electrical shock, the
Consumer Product Safety Commission said Thursday.
   The power strip is a foot-long, beige-colored bar containing six
ordinary electrical receptacles, an on-off switch, a circuit
breaker and a three-wire power cord six feet long.
   The base is labeled ``Temporary Power Tap Model No. WP-002B,
Made in Taiwan, UL 46K7, E95914.''
   The receptacles might not be grounded, the commission said. So
far, no injuries have been reported.
   About 6,700 strips were sold for $10 to $20 in 1987 and 1988 by
Rose's Stores of Henderson, N.C., Colonial Pottery of Morehead
City, N.C., and Trak Auto Stores, which operate in the Washington
area from headqaurters in Landover, Md., a Washington suburb, the
commission said.
   The importer, Collins Company Ltd. of Mount Olive, N.J., said
owners could return the strips to Trak, Rose's or Colonial for a
refund, according to the commission.
   Owners also may write Collins at 450 Clark Drive, Mount Olive,
N.J. 07828 or call 1-800-645-7212 extension 207 for instructions on
returning the strips.
</TEXT>
