<FILEID>AP-NR-04-13-89 2031EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-FarmCo-ops     04-13 0223</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Farm Co-ops,210</SECOND>
<HEAD>Farm Cooperatives Show Sharp Rise in Net Income</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Agriculture Department report said Thursday
that farm cooperatives showed a sharp rise in net income in 1987,
reaching the highest level since 1980.
   The department's Agricultural Cooperative Service said net
income rose to $1.5 billion, more than double the $688 million
reported for 1986, and was ``the first major reversal in recent
declines'' suffered during the farm crunch of the early 1980s.
   According to the report, published in the agency's Farmer
Cooperatives magazine, the estimates covered 5,109 marketing, farm
supply and selected service co-ops having a 1987 combined gross of
$74 billion.
   ``All groups, except those marketing rice and sugar, and those
providing selected services, showed 1987 increases in net income,''
the report said. ``The largest recovery occurred in the farm supply
group. Those cooperatives earned net income of $351 million after
experiencing net losses of $66 million in 1986.''
   The report said other groups also showed ``generally strong
turnarounds'' in 1987. Those included co-ops marketing fruits and
vegetables; cotton; grain and soybeans; and livestock, wool and
poultry.
   Net worth of co-ops, total liabilities and total assets all grew
in 1987, the report said _ assets, 4.3 percent to $27.6 billion;
liabilities, 1.5 percent to $14.8 billion; and net worth, 7.8
percent to a record $12.8 billion.
</TEXT>
