<FILEID>AP-NR-04-13-89 2033EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-EPAFine     04-13 0218</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-EPA Fine,210</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Seeks Fines Against Illinois Manufacturer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government has filed a complaint, seeking
$1.4 million in fines, against an Illinois manufacturer of
catalytic converter replacement pipes that the Environmental
Protection Agency maintains are ineffective.
   The complaint was filed by the Justice Department on behalf of
the EPA in federal court in Chicago against Ced's Inc., of Addison,
Ill., the EPA said Thursday.
   The EPA accused the company, which also does business as
Products for Power, of failing to abide by a 1987 settlement
agreement in which the company allegedly said it would pay $75,000
in fines and stop selling the replacement pipes.
   ``Despite the widespread misperception that these pipes will
improve vehicle performance, they are merely lengths of plain
exhaust tubing cut to fit in place of catalytic converters and
offer no performance advantages over properly functioning catalytic
converters,'' said the EPA.
   The pipes ``dramatically increase emissions of
health-threatening pollutants by releasing untreated exhaust
gases,'' said Don Clay, acting EPA assistant administrator for air
and radiation.
   The action filed in federal court asks that the company pay
$135,000 in civil penalties for failing to comply with the 1987
agreement and $2,500 in additional penalties per day that it was in
non-compliance. The overall fine would exceed $1.4 million, the
agency said.
</TEXT>
