<FIRST>r w AM-Soviet-Ambassador 1stLd-Writethru a0597 04-13 0456</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Ambassador, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0597,450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Ambassador Says Bush Administration Moving Too Slowly on Talks</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: To update, inserts grafs 10-11, bgng ``Israeli Prime,'' with
Shamir remarks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Yuri V. Dubinin, the Soviet ambassador to the
United States, accused the Bush administration on Thursday of
moving too slowly on bilateral negotiations.
   Dubinin urged the administration, which has been conducting a
``strategic review'' of security policies, to spell out its
positions before Secretary of State James A. Baker III's scheduled
May 10-11 visit to Moscow. The review is to be completed by May 10.
   ``Soviet-American dialogue is essential to building new
international relations,'' Dubinin said in a speech at a meeting of
the American Society of Newspaper Editors.
   ``Apparently, this is the reason why more and more questions are
being asked in the U.S.S.R. and throughout the world as to when the
Soviet-American dialogue will be resumed in its entirety,'' he said.
   Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev voiced similar complaints
last week during a visit to Great Britain. Bush countered
Gorbachev's statements by saying that his administration was
``making a prudent review. ... Mr. Gorbachev knows there is no
foot-dragging going on.''
   Dubinin said that ``as to the Soviet Union, we are prepared to
resume the negotiations at any moment'' on strategic arms, human
rights, regional problems, bilateral relations and other issues.
   The ambassador brushed aside a question about whether the Soviet
sale of bombers to Libya contradicted its stated desire to shift to
a more peaceful foreign policy.
   ``Yes, we have sold several units of this aircraft to Libya. But
it was done a lot of time ago,'' said Dubinin.
   ``They are not modern aircraft. They are not so modern as those
that Israel has. ... That is why it is not at all a basis to put
into question the new policies in the Soviet Union, the new
thinking in our policy,'' he said.
   Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir, following Dubinin before
the same audience, said the sale worried his government.
   ``It obliges us to remain always ready to face any surprise,''
said Shamir. ``We are very sorry that we cannot see in this regard
any change in Soviet policy in our area. So far there is continuity
... the Soviets are selling arms to their clients,'' Libya and
Syria.
   U.S. officials said last week that the Soviet Union had sold
Libya Su-24 bombers, with ranges of up to 800 miles, enough to
reach Egypt or Israel, two nations with which Libya has hostile
relations.
   Last week, Soviet foreign ministry spokesman Gennady I.
Gerasimov said the Soviet Union sold six short-range bombers to
Libya under a 1986 contract, but did not identify the planes by
name.
</TEXT>
