<FIRST>r a AM-GuardGuns     04-13 0194</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Guard Guns,0199</SECOND>
<HEAD>National Guard Changes Weapons Policy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An incident in which a National Guard private
fired 14 shots from an M-16 rifle into the air in a neighborhood
has led to a policy change.
   Guardsmen will be forbidden to leave Guard property with a
weapon, said Col. Raymond Murphy, Massachusetts National Guard
chief of staff.
   ``This will really tighten things up,'' he said. ``The comander
of the battalion will know at all times where his weapons are.''
   Under the policy announced Wednesday, all weapons will be
transported in locked trucks to training sites and issued to
guardsmen there.
   Private Edward J. Silva carried his automatic rifle and 80
rounds of ammunition on a trip from Camp Edwards in Bourne to the
National Guard armory in Boston's Dorchester section April 1.
   He told investigators he found the armory closed, took the
weapon home, went drinking with friends and fired the gun to
impress them, authorities said.
   He pleaded innocent in Dorchester District Court to charges of
unauthorized possession of a machine gun, larceny, speeding,
discharging a firearm within 500 feet of a building, disorderly
conduct and receiving a stolen vehicle.
</TEXT>
