<FILEID>AP-NR-04-13-89 2101EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-PacificBasin     04-13 0295</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pacific Basin,300</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pacific Panel To be Formed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Members of Congress introduced legislation
Thursday calling for the creation of a Pacific Basin Forum that
would enable the United States and Asian nations to deal with
issues such as free trade and economic development.
   ``The United States has a pressing need to reinvigorate our
diplomatic efforts in the Pacific region, an area currently
undergoing a radical transformation,'' said Senate Democratic Whip
Alan Cranston of California in introducing the measure.
   Cranston, chairman of the Senate Foreign Relations subcommittee
on East Asian and Pacific Affairs, said China, Japan and South
Korea are experiencing an economic boom that is straining relations
with the United States, which has a trade deficit.
   ``I propose that the United States promote the establishment of
a Pacific Basin Forum to pursue such crucial issues as free trade,
economic development and security confidence building,'' Cranston
said.
   The forum also would hold annual summit meetings involving the
leaders of the Asian nations and the United States, establish a
permanent secretariat for research and encourage private sector
involvement in planning.
   Cranston said the forum would resemble NATO and the annual
economic summits with European leaders, but stressed that he wasn't
encouraging the creation of an ``Asian trading bloc to rival the
Common Market.''
   ``I do believe it is manifestly in the American interest to
design a forum for focused discussion of these and related issues
among Pacific Rim nations,'' he said. ``And I do believe it would
serve our purposes to remind our friends in Europe that we have
important trade interests elsewhere.''
   Additional sponsors of Cranston's legislation were Sens. Richard
Lugar, R-Ind.; Christopher Dodd, D-Conn.; Bill Bradley, D-N.J., and
Frank Murkowski, R-Alaska. Rep. Mel Levine, D-Calif., introduced
similar legislation in the House.
</TEXT>
