<FILEID>AP-NR-04-13-89 2107EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-ResearchandDevelopment     04-13 0512</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Research and Development,530</SECOND>
<HEAD>Help Need for R&amp;D</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARTON REPPERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Outgoing White House science adviser William
R. Graham Jr. on Thursday criticized ``overly rigid
compartmentalization'' of U.S. research and development efforts,
arguing that a more coordinated strategy is needed to meet the
challenges of global competition.
   Graham, a holdover from the Reagan administration, questioned
the feasibility of establishing a civilian counterpart to the
Pentagon's Defense Advanced Research Agency, which has funded
leading-edge research in computers and other areas.
   Instead, he urged better use of existing interagency groups to
derive greater benefit from the $65 billion a year that the federal
government is currently spending on research and development _
about $43 billion for defense programs and about $22 billion in the
civilian area.
   ``One of the luxuries we've had for the last 40 years is the
luxury of compartmentalizing our activities very tightly. This is
Defense (Department), this is Energy, this is Commerce and so on,''
Graham told a conference on federal science and technology policy.
   He noted that ``we've seen the difficulties that creates in such
areas as the FSX today, which had been an activity undertaken
largely for defense policy purposes by the U.S. government, while
there was a substantial component of industrial policy on the part
of the Japanese.''
   Graham was referring to a controversial project under which U.S.
and Japanese companies are to co-develop and co-produce the FSX
aircraft, an advanced version of the F-16 fighter, for deployment
by Japan in the late 1990s.
   A U.S.-Japanese agreement, signed late last year, had been
negotiated by the Pentagon and State Department. However, after the
Bush administration took office the deal came under criticism from
the Commerce Secretary Robert Mosbacher and U.S. Trade
Representative Carla Hills, expressing concern that broader
economic issues had not been fully taken into account.
   As a result, the administration has requested ``clarifications''
from Tokyo before the FSX agreement is formally submitted to
Congress.
   Graham said the United States needs to look for opportunities
where defense spending substantially helps U.S. civilian industry,
comparable to the mid-1950s when the Boeing Co.'s building of
KC-135 military tanker planes led to its successful development of
the civilian 707 jetliner.
   ``Many more such opportunities exist in defense and other
sectors -- I believe many more than we're taking advantage of today.
   ``And I believe the overly rigid compartmentalization with which
we've viewed these (R&amp;D programs) institutionally, both in the
government and in industry, is limiting the benefits that we derive
from the $65 billion that the federal government invests each
year,'' he said.
   Graham, who became presidential science adviser in October 1986,
has stayed on at the White House pending the appointment of a new
adviser by President Bush.
   Asked how soon he believes a replacement will be named, Graham
said ``I've learned that it's always hazardous to second-guess the
president'' but added that ``I would be surprised if it's too much
longer.''
   He spoke at a science and technology policy colloquium sponsored
by the American Association for the Advancement of Science.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
