<FILEID>AP-NR-04-13-89 2112EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Northrop     04-13 0512</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Northrop,480</SECOND>
<HEAD>Air Force Still Confident About Cruise Missile</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Pentagon said Thursday the Air Force is
still confident of the wartime abilities of its cruise missile,
even though charges filed this week against Northrop Corp. charge
the defense contractor falsified test data and installed defective
parts in the missile.
   Defense Department spokesman Fred S. Hoffman said Air Force
officials continue to believe the air-launched missile is ``mission
ready'' and added that ``any suggestion at this point that Northrop
may be suspended or dbarred is really speculative and premature.
...''
   The Navy and Air Force are following ``standard procedures'' for
dealing with contractors that have been indicted on federal
charges, the spokesman said. Under those procedures, special
administrative boards within the Navy and Air Force have requested
details of the Northrop indictment from prosecutors.
   At some point, the boards will decide if the allegations are
serious enough to warrant an immediate, temporary suspension of
Northrop's contracting rights.
   ``But that has not yet happened,'' Hoffman said.
   The aerospace giant and five current or former employees were
charged with conspiring to defraud the government in the
construction of part of the guidance system for the cruise missile
and in the building of a component of the Navy's Harrier attack jet.
   The allegations involving the missile were viewed as
particularly troubling, because that weapon is part of the nation's
nuclear arsenal. The 167-count indictment charged that Northrop and
the employees conspired to install parts for the missile's flight
data transmitter that failed to meet government specifications.
   Asked Thursday if the Air Force thought it could rely on the
weapon in view of the charges against Northrop, Hoffman noted the
allegations against the company first surfaced in 1987.
   ``And the Air Force ... has been taking a series of remedial
steps since then,'' he continued. ``So it is not something which
just burst on them. They were aware then and they have been taking
action.
   ``As things now stand, the Air Force has full confidence that
the air-launched cruise missile is reliable and capable of carrying
out its mission. According to the Air Force, it has a mission
readiness rate well within acceptable limits. That rate is 96
percent.''
   As for the AV-8B Harrier jump jet, flown by the Marine Corps,
Hoffman said the service had ``experienced higher-than-expected
failure rates over the life of the program'' for a flight sensor
assembly made by Northrop.
   ``However, the sensor involved is not essential for safe flight
and there have been no accidents nor any incidents, I'm told, that
can be attributed to the failure of this component,'' Hoffman said.
   Northrop is the nation's 32nd largest defense contractor, having
received contracts worth $532.6 million in fiscal 1988. The company
is a prime contractor on several key projects, however, including
the B-2 stealth bomber.
   Should either the Navy or Air Force impose a suspension on the
firm pending resolution of the charges, it would affect Northrop's
right to bid on and receive future contracts _ not those it already
holds.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
