<DOCNO> AP890413-0161 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-13-89 2112EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-US-JapanTimber     04-13 0380</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Japan Timber,370</SECOND>
<HEAD>Japan Charged With Destroying Rain Forests</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japan is speeding the destruction of tropical
rain forest in southeast Asia because of its demand for timber,
according to a report Thursday by the World Wildlife Fund, a
private environmental group.
   Co-authors of the report were Yoichi Kuroda, coordinator of the
Japan Tropical Forest Action Network, and Francois Nectoux, a
French economist who lectures at the South Bank Polytechnic in
London.
   ```South seas' tropical forests are being destroyed, for
ineffective plywood uses and even disposable chopsticks,'' said
Robert Buschbacher, director of the organization's forestry
program, in a statement.
   ``As forests are eradicated in Asia, Japan will look towards
South America _ specifically the Amazon _ to exploit.''
   The report, entitled ``Timber from the South Seas,'' said that
in 1987 Japan got 96 percent of its tropical hardwoods from Sarawak
and Sabah in Malaysia, and from Papua New Guinea. A statement by
the fund said some of the world's most biologically valuable
forests are threatened with destruction in Sabah and Sarawak, on
the island of Borneo.
   In the 1960s and 1970s Japan's hardwoods came mainly from the
Philippines and Indonesia, according to the report.
   A Japanese embassy official, who spoke on condition his name not
be used, questioned whether it took all the relevant facts into
account. He said Japan gives due consideration to environmental
matters in its import program. It is a big contributor to both the
United National Environmental Program and to the International
Tropicval Timber Organization in Yokohama, he added.
   According to the report, Japan has been the world's major
importer of tropical woods for nearly 20 years, taking about 2
billion dollars worth in 1986. It said Japan imports more than the
United States, and as much as the 12 countries of the European
Exconomic Community taken together.
   ``The time is ripe for many changes in Japan's relation towards
tropical forests,'' the report concluded. ``So far this
relationship has been mainly destructive.''
   It recommended a new policy to deal with both conservation and
Japan's timber needs, with increased aid for forest management,
concentration of imports on timber from areas where production can
be sustained, reduction of wasteful uses and substitution of
softwoods where hardwood is not necessary.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
