<DOCNO> AP890413-0163 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-13-89 1701EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Lebanon 1stLd-Writethru a0656 04-13 0761</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0656,0780</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shelling Stalls French Mercy Plan; Civil War in 15th Year</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with more casualties, postponement
of French mercy operation. No pickup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA ABU-NASR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Christian and Moslem gunners pounded
residential areas Thursday, stalling the evacuation of wounded to a
French hospital ship as the bitter civil war that has claimed
150,000 victims entered its 15th year.
   Police said 19 people were killed and 50 wounded, raising the
toll to 215 dead and 727 injured since the artillery battle began
March 8 between the Christian army units of Gen. Michel Aoun and
Druse militiamen aided by Syrian soldiers.
   Thursday's day-long bombardment was the fiercest since April 5,
when the Arab League called for a cease-fire to halt the worst
sectarian fighting since 1985. The truce, like others in the long
war, soon failed.
   Artillery and rocket fire blocked plans to ferry Moslem and
Christian wounded by helicopter to a French hospital ship in
neutral waters off Beirut.
   ``The evacuation has been put off indefinitely,'' a police
spokesman said on condition of anonymity. ``We do not know how long
the French hospital ship will wait for security conditions to
permit patients to be flown to it.''
   He said a rocket barrage at midday hit the main power
distribution plant in Jamhour, a Christian suburb, blacking out
Beirut and the surrounding area.
   ``All power distribution operations for the capital and its
suburbs have come to a standstill,'' said Fares Dagher of Beirut's
electricity authority. ``We do not know when any repairs can be
done.''
   A spokesman for the Moslem cabinet of acting Premier Salim Hoss
said earlier a French navy tanker was ready to unload six tons of
fuel oil Friday at the Moslem terminal at Zahrani in south Lebanon
and at Zouk, a Christian harbor north of Beirut where the capital's
main power plant is located.
   Shelling of storage depots has nearly wiped out the fuel supply
and the power authority had said even the limited electricity
supplied to Beirut would stop unless stocks were replenished.
   Attilo Iannucci, the Italian charge d'affaires, said the Italian
ship Isola Azzurra was hit by a shell off Beirut port shortly after
sunup but no one was hurt. He said the vessel, carrying 4,000 tons
of sulfuric acid, headed for Cyprus for repairs.
   ``Four shells were fired, but the captain avoided three and only
one hit the back of the ship way above water level,'' Iannucci said
in an interview.
   Bernard Kouchner, France's minister for humanitarian assistance,
announced the plans for French helicopters to evacuate wounded
Lebanese to the hospital ship Rance.
   The minister, who arrived Tuesday, said Moslem victims would be
flown from west Beirut's Bain Militaire beach and Christians from
Jounieh, a Christian-controlled port 12 miles north of the city.
   He did not give the location of the Rance, which has 90 beds and
operating facilities. The Beirut newspaper As-Safir said it would
anchor between Moslem and Christian waters eight miles out.
   Beirut hospitals had not asked that the ship be sent from
France, which ruled Lebanon until independence in 1943.
   Medical sources said it was not needed to treat most of the
wounded but could be useful for acute and specialized cases, such
as victims needing artificial limbs or 24-hour care.
   A source in the Hoss cabinet said the Bain Militaire and Jounieh
port were ``repeatedly targeted by the shelling Thursday.''
   Hoss and Aoun, who commands the 20,000 Christians in Lebanon's
army, have led competing Moslem and Christian governments since a
political crisis arose in September.
   The artillery battle started two days after Aoun's forces
blockaded illegal militia-run ports that deprive the five
government ports of about $100 million a year.
   Lebanon's civil war dates from April 13, 1975, when Christian
gunman killed 29 Palestinians in a bus ambush after a prominent
member of the rightist Christian Phalange party was assassinated.
   The political crisis began when President Amin Gemayel's
six-year term ended and Parliament could not agree on a successor.
He appointed Aoun, his army commander, to lead an interim
government and Moslems swore allegiance to Hoss, the incumbent
premier.
   When competing governments emerged, the army also split on
sectarian lines. The 22,000 Moslem soldiers, led by Maj. Gen. Sami
Khatib, are poorly equipped and have stayed out of the fighting,
but help Syrian troops blockade Christian territory.
   Syria has 40,000 soldiers in Lebanon under a 1976 peacekeeping
mandate from the Arab league and has become the country's main
power broker in the chaos of civil war.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
