<FIRST>u i AM-Soviet-Ship     04-13 0336</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Ship,0351</SECOND>
<HEAD>Syrian Helicopters Rocket Two Soviet Navy Ships</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two Syrian helicopters rocketed two Soviet navy
vessels in the Mediterranean this week, injuring seven Soviet
sailors, one critically, Foreign Ministry spokesman Gennady I.
Gerasimov reported Thursday.
   He said Syria apologized for the attack and that a preliminary
investigaton indicated the helicopter pilots attacked in error.
   The military newspaper Kraznaya Zvezda identifed the badly
wounded man as E. Shkitchenko and said, ``There is little hope to
save him.''
   Gerasimov told a news briefing the attack took place at 10 a.m.
Tuesday 35 miles off the Syrian port of Tartus.
   The Soviets have maintained military facilities at Tartus, where
two of the injured seamen were taken, since 1969.
   ``Two helicopters with Syrian markings attacked two Soviet
auxiliary vessels with rockets, namely a sea tugboat and a divers'
boat in the Mediterranean Sea,'' he said.
   Gerasimov did not say what type of helicopters were involved or
give details of the attack.
   According to an initial probe into the incident, the attack was
a result of ``erroneous actions of one of the Syrian helicopters,''
Gerasimov said.
   ``The Syrian side expressed regret at the accident and offered
its official apology.''
   He declined to say if the official apology was made in Moscow or
Damascus.
   The Soviet news media soft-pedaled the incident with Syria, its
staunchest ally in the Middle East. Damascus keeps close relations
with Moscow, its major arms supplier.
   The attack was first reported in a three-paragraph item in the
world news roundup of Krasnaya Zvezda on page three. The official
Tass news agency carried a two-paragraph dispatch on Gerasimov's
remarks. The government newspaper Izvestia did not mention the
incident.
   The submarine-tracking ship Kraszny Kavkaz and the cruiser
Leningrad, on a routine patrol in the eastern Mediterranean,
hurried to the aid of the attacked vessels, sea tugboat S.B.-524
and divers' boat-125, after the attack, according to the newspaper.
   Gerasimov said a joint investigation commission was set up to
determine why the helicopters attacked the Soviet vessels.
