<FIRST>u i AM-Poland 1stLd-Writethru a0688 04-13 0945</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0688,0965</SECOND>
<HEAD>Walesa Says He'd Like to Seek Presidency</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to tighten, and CORRECT translation from
news conference to ``thinking about'' being a candidate, stand ``plan to
be a candidate''; SUBS grafs 22-23 ``The new ...'' to ADD church-gov't
meeting and demonstrations.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH G. SEWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Solidarity founder Lech Walesa said
Thursday he was being pressured to run for office but would only
want the newly created post of president of Poland.
   Also on Thursday, Solidarity filed an application to register as
a trade union after a seven-year ban. The application at the Warsaw
Regional Court follows the historic agreement reached April 5 by
the opposition and communist authorities to restore the union's
legal status and allow independent candidates to run for parliament
in June.
   Walesa said he expects Solidarity to be registered by Monday and
added: ``Delaying of our activities doesn't serve us and doesn't
serve Poland.''
   He said he was under heavy pressure to run in the elections,
which the government Thursday set for June 4, with run-off voting
on June 18.
   ``I'm being strongly pressed. Different people are pressing me
and I am thinking about being a candidate to the highest organ that
is going to be in Poland,'' Walesa said at a news conference in his
home city of Gdansk.
   Walesa said later in a telephone interview that he would not run
either for the newly created 100-member senate, which will be the
East bloc's first freely elected legislative chamber, or the
existing 460-member Sejm, where the opposition can run for 35
percent of the seats.
   But he said he might like to be a candidate for president when
the post next becomes available in six years, although he wouldn't
exclude his name from being put forward now.
   ``I am a man of big interests,'' said Walesa, an electrician who
won the Nobel Peace Prize for founding the East bloc's first
independent trade union during a 1980 strike at the Gdansk shipyard.
   Any citizen can be nominated for president by one-fourth of the
Sejm, as the existing parliament is called, and the senate. The
president will be jointly elected by the Sejm and the senate.
   The first six-year term is widely expected to go to Commmunist
Party leader Gen. Wojciech Jaruzelski due to the majority still
guaranteed to the Communist Party and its allies in the larger Sejm.
   Walesa, who has indicated a preference for concentrating on
union matters, did not say who was pressuring him to seek office.
But there have been suggestions he should run to set an example for
other opposition members who might be reluctant to replace election
boycotts with participation the communist-dominated government.
   The Roman Catholic church, with which Walesa and Solidarity are
closely bonded, has called on members in general to participate in
the election.
   Solidarity won't directly field candidates for the elections,
but said it will support those named by a Solidarity Citizens
Committee that was formally created on Saturday and is composed of
top union leaders and adivsers.
   The committee said it will put forward candidates for all 100
senate seats and the 161 freely contested Sejm seats. Solidarity
national spokesman Janusz Onyszkiewicz said the names of the
candidates will be presented by the end of April or early May.
   About 125 Solidarity leaders and advisers from across Poland
gathered in a crowded church hall Thursday to hear about the
election procedures agreed upon at the talks and start planning the
campaign.
   A Solidarity commission of eight key activists was formed to
direct the election efforts under Walesa.
   ``Solidarity plans to win these elections as much as is
possible. The elections will tell exactly who is right. I wish well
to all. Let the better win,'' Walesa said at the news conference.
   He entrusted the task of filing the union's charter in court to
Tadeusz Mazowiecki, the opposition leader who negotiated trade
union freedoms in the talks with the government.
   Mazowiecki said the union had submitted the same charter it had
before Solidarity was banned after the December 1981 martial-law
crackdown.
   However, it contains a new section that suspends provisions
concerning strikes, in effect making Solidarity's charter adhere to
Poland's 1982 trade union law, which severely restricts the right
to strike.
   Walesa said he thinks there should be the right to strike, but
sticking stubbornly to the right to strike by an association is
``abnormal in abnormal times.''
   The new parliament is expected to revamp the trade union law,
possibly expanding the right to strike.
   Also on Thursday, Polish leader Gen. Wojciech Jaruzelski met
with Roman Catholic primate Cardinal Jozef Glemp to discuss
relations between the government and the church. They discussed
regulation of the legal status of the church, relations with the
Vatican, the outcome of the talks between the authorities and the
opposition, and upcoming elections, the state-run PAP news agency
said.
   Elsewhere in Warsaw, several hundred students marched to protest
conditions at the university library, and 1,500 elderly pensioners
gathered at the official union alliance seeking more benefits.
   Authorities proposed the talks on political and economic reform
in August 1988 at the peak of a nationwide wave of strikes in four
months. Walesa refused to participate until authorities agreed to
restore Solidarity's legal status. At a stormy plenum in January,
Jaruzelski pressed the Communist Party to accept a legal Solidarity
and the talks finally began Feb. 6.
   Authorities hope the restoration of Solidarity and opposition
participation in parliament will create a period of social calm to
give economic reforms designed to fight inflation, chronic consumer
shortages and a staggering foreign debt a chance.
</TEXT>
