<FIRST>u w AM-Wright-Democrats     04-13 0933</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Wright-Democrats,1st Ld-Writethru,a0678,890</SECOND>
<HEAD>Democrats Agonizing over Prospect of Stripping Wright from Post</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 4th graf pvs bgng: But the ... with 5 grafs to UPDATE with
Wright statement; Subs grafs 13-17 pvs bgng: Undoubtedly, if .. with 3
grafs to UPDATE. Picks up 18th graf pvs bgng: Rep. Barney ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   House Democrats, who re-elected Jim Wright as
speaker only four months ago, agonized Thursday over the prospect
that an ethics committee report might compel them to strip their
leader of his post.
   ``I think there's deep concern, both as to the person of the
speaker and the Congress itself,'' said Rep. Dale Kildee, D-Mich.
``Agony is probably the best word.''
   After a 10-month investigation, the ethics committee has found
reason to believe that the Texas lawmaker violated House rules in
receiving financial benefits from a Fort Worth developer who had an
interest in legislation, and that the speaker improperly sought to
evade limits on outside income with a book deal, according to
sources familiar with the probe.
   In a sometimes emotional defense Thursday, Wright denied
violating any rules and asked for a quick decision from his
colleagues.
   ``I will fight to the last ounce of conviction and energy that I
possess,'' Wright told reporters in the Capitol. ``I am confident
that in the 34 years I have served in the Congress I have not
violated any of those basic rules or any commonly accepted standard
of ethical conduct.''
   Rep. Steny Hoyer, D-Md., who lined up behind Wright with other
House leaders and Texas lawmakers, said the speaker was being
``leaked to death'' and needed to respond.
   ``I don't think the question is survival,'' he said. Once the
public hears Wright's case, he said, ``I think they are going to
conclude that he's absolutely telling the truth.''
   The full House, not the committee, is the final judge. Democrats
fear they'll have to choose between jettisoning a leader who over
three decades climbed to the top of their ranks, and facing a
political fallout that could harm them all.
   ``There's sort of a foreboding here about what the Congress has
to confront. This is all precedent setting,'' said one Democratic
lawmaker, who like many of those interviewed, spoke on the
condition his name not be used.
   Never has a House speaker been removed. It is far from a
foregone conclusion that Wright will be the first.
   ``I think all that's premature,'' said Rep. Pat Williams,
D-Mont., a Wright ally, when asked to speculate how Democrats would
react to the ethics committee report, expected to be issued in the
next few days.
   Williams was among those who said Wright's future as speaker
would depend in part on whether the ethics committee recommends
punishment, such as a formal reprimand or censure. The committee
decides that issue after the speaker is given a chance to respond
to its charges.
   ``The ground would start to move under him if he were
reprimanded,'' Williams said.
   If the committee merely scolds Wright, he can survive, but if it
recommends a reprimand or the more severe act of censure, then
there would be ``no option'' but to remove Wright as speaker, said
another Democrat.
   The investigation against Wright was begun following a complaint
by Rep. Newt Gingrich, R-Ga., who has since risen to the No. 2
position among House Republicans.
   The GOP intends to make hay with whatever sunshine the committee
provides. House Republican leader Bob Michel of Illinois said he
would use the rules to make sure that the full House votes on the
Wright matter regardless of what the committee recommends.
   Three House Democrats launched another part of the counterattack
in ``Dear Colleague'' letter Thursday, demanding that the Ethics
Committee publish only information related to the actual charges it
will level at Wright. Republicans had been pushing for a full
release of the special counsel's report, which contains material on
allegations rejected by the committee.
   ``Releasing the other material _ unsubstantiated charges,
rumors, innuendo and speculation _ on Speaker Wright would be a
terrible precedent for the House, threatens all members and makes a
mockery of fair play,'' said the letter from David Nagle of Iowa,
Bob Matsui of California and Jim Moody of Wisconsin.
   Undoubtedly, if Wright became a political liability for the
party, many Democrats would hope he'd leave quietly. But Wright
himself has indicated he won't easily give up the post that is the
pinnacle of his career.
   Rep. Barney Frank, D-Mass., said he believed Democrats will not
lightly discard their speaker for political advantage in their home
districts.
   ``I think people are less political than you sometimes think,''
he said.
   So far, lawmakers said they saw no sign that anyone was moving
against Wright in a power grab. ``I don't see any cannibalism going
on,'' said one.
   ``You have a person who has every right to be treated justly,''
Kildee said. ``I really think this is a very grave moral issue''
and, if a vote comes, each member will decide ``in the loneliness
of our consciences.''
   Several lawmakers expressed concern that the speaker was being
held up to standards that sometimes weren't clear and have changed
over the years.
   Rep. Charles Stenholm, D-Texas, said even members of the House
who have tried diligently to obey all ethical standards will wonder
whether they could have survived the same kind of million-dollar
investigation. He cited the familiar phrase about people who live
in glass houses.
   ``Most of us in the House are prepared to eat a steady diet of
glass for the next few weeks,'' he added.
</TEXT>
