<FIRST>r w AM-US-SouthernAfrica     04-13 0349</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Southern Africa,330</SECOND>
<HEAD>Official Says SWAPO Has Much To Answer For</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department's top official on Africa
on Thursday accused leaders of Namibia's SWAPO guerrillas of making
``a terrible decision'' in sending fighters on an armed incursion
that is threatening the U.S.-mediated peace accord in the region.
   Assistant Secretary of State Chester Crocker, just back from an
emergency meeting with Cuban, Angolan and South African
representatives, said he thought the agreement that went into
effect April 1 was now back on track.
   The pact, which grants independence to Namibia from South Africa
and envisions a Cuban pullout from Angola, was threatened by an
incursion of 1,200 to 1,800 armed SWAPO guerrillas from their bases
in Angola.
   ``It's still fragile,'' Crocker said. But he added that he was
struck by ``the extent to which the Cubans want to salvage this
thing.'' Cuba has undertaken to remove an estimated 50,000 troops
from Angola by July 1991.
   Crocker said the United States believes South Africa too is
determined to implement the agreements.
   Crocker said ``it was hard to explain the motive'' for the
decision made by Sam Nujoma, the head of the Soviet-backed SWAPO
group, to violate the agreement, which calls for the guerrillas to
remain in Angola until May 15.
   ``It was a terrible decision from SWAPO's own point of view,''
Crocker told reporters. SWAPO sent 300 of its fighters ``to their
death'' in Namibia, he said, ``and I would have thought the
leadership has something to answer for.''
   More than 260 SWAPO guerrillas have been killed in fighting with
South African-led security forces since their incursion began April
1. Some observers have suggested that local SWAPO commanders
thought they could return to Namibia the moment the pact went into
effect.
   Nujoma said initially that many of the fighters were already in
Namibia and had not crossed from Angola. But the U.N. peacekeeping
force on the ground has refuted the claim. Although Nujoma has
called on his fighters to retreat to Angola, it was unclear
Thursday how many had complied.
</TEXT>
