<FIRST>r a AM-Brite     04-13 0261</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brite,0269</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bright &amp; Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities say they've worked out
appropriate punishment for a 12-year-old who took a horse from a
carriage service and took it for a 1{-hour joyride downtown.
   He'll spend some time shoveling out the stalls at the Orlando
Police Department's horse stables.
   ``Under this agreement, he'll be punished... but he won't go
away with a felony criminal record,'' Assistant Public Defender
Barry Hepner said Wednesday.
   The boy and a 10-year-old companion took the horse, Baldy, from
the Orlando Carriage Co. They fashioned a bridle from rope and rode
the gentle horse around the downtown area on March 11.
   The 10-year-old was released to his parents, but the older boy's
family couldn't be located. Later, it was determined that his
father lives somewhere in Texas and his mother reportedly is in
Orlando but has a drug problem, Hepner said.
   ``He's a good kid, and he's very polite and does well in
school,'' Hepner said. ``But he was really just abandoned.''
   A felony charge of grand theft was filed against the boy because
he had a previous arrest for petty theft. He stole a toy car from a
store before Christmas, and is to be sentenced on that charge in
May. The other boy was not prosecuted because of his age and lack
of a criminal record.
   The 12-year-old, who was not identified because of his age, is
now living in a county-operated children's home until officials
decide whether he should be returned to a family member, placed in
a foster home or adopted.
</TEXT>
