<FILEID>AP-NR-04-13-89 2131EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Namibia     04-13 0395</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Namibia,0407</SECOND>
<HEAD>South Africa Says SWAPO Withdrawal Deadline May Be Extended</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WINDHOEK, Namibia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   South Africa said Thursday it may
extend a deadline for guerrillas to report to U.N. checkpoints for
safe passage out of Namibia.
   By Thursday night, only five fighters of the South-West Africa
People's Organization had reported to U.N. assembly points to take
advantage of an offer to return safely to Angola, territorial
officials said.
   South Africa says about 1,900 guerrillas infiltrated northern
Namibia after April 1, when Namibia's transition to independence
from South Africa was to begin. It was also the day a cease-fire
between SWAPO and South African forces was to take effect.
   But over the next eight days, 263 guerrillas and 27 members of
the South African-led security forces were killed in fighting.
   South Africa's largest daily newspaper, The Star of
Johannesburg, reported that two guerrillas were killed late
Wednesday in a new clash, the first since the weekend. A police
spokesman, Chief Inspector Kierie du Rand, said he knew of no such
incident.
   U.N. investigators have supported South Africa's contention the
guerrillas violated a peace accord requiring they stay at Angolan
bases at least until May 15.
   U.N. and South African military officers have expressed concern
that few guerrillas will report to the U.N. checkpoints. An
undetermined number already have gone back into Angola on their
own, and police say others are likely to try to remain in Namibia
in civilian guise.
   The territorial police said they probably would begin tracking
down guerrillas if it appeared only a few had left by a Saturday
deadline.
   However, South African Foriegn Minister Pik Botha said Thursday
the deadline could be extended indefinitely.
   Cedric Thornberry, second-in-command of the U.N. contingent in
Namibia, said verification of SWAPO's withdrawal was a precondition
for restoring the truce that was supposed to start April 1.
   He said verification would be difficult because some guerrillas
were bypassing the checkpoints and because of uncertainty as to the
size of the original incursion.
   SWAPO's exiled president, Sam Nujoma, has called on his fighters
to withdraw, but he has not specifically advised that they report
to the checkpoints.
   South Africa has ruled Namibia since World War I. In December,
it agreed to begin a transition to independence in exchange for
Cuba withdrawing its estimated 50,000 troops from Angola. SWAPO has
been fighting South African rule since 1966.
</TEXT>
