<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Space     04-13 0287</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Space,0293</SECOND>
<UNK>Soviet Space Official Defends Program Against Public Demands For Cuts</UNK>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The space program makes a profit, and people who
want it reduced in favor of more spending on food production and
housing are ignorant of its benefits, a Soviet scientist said
Thursday.
   Boris Chertok, a member of the Soviet Academy of Sciences, said
the program cost $2 billion last year but earned more than $3.2
billion in satellite business and technology transfers. His remarks
were reported by the official news agency Tass.
   Calls for reductions in the space budget emerged during the
recent Soviet election campaign. They were brought up by official
media Wednesday in the context of Cosmonauts Day, the anniversary
of the first manned space flight, made 28 years ago by Yuri Gagarin.
   Recent setbacks in the Soviet space program encouraged the
demands for reductions. Tass said Wednesday the orbiting space
station Mir would be left unmanned for three months because of
delays in preparing research modules.
   Late last month, Soviet scientists lost contact with the second
of two Phobos probes sent to Mars at a cost of $480 million.
   Speaking at an Academy of Sciences convention, Chertok said
demands to divert money from space to food production and housing
reflect ignorance of the benefits space technology brings the
national economy.
   ``Space research performed the role of `locomotive' which was
blazing the way for other sectors,'' Tass quoted Chertok as saying.
``Were it not for cosmonautics, our lag in such fields as computer
engineering would have been much greater than now.''
   He said the Buran shuttle program, criticized as uneconomical,
would help civil aviation and computer technology. Chertok said its
safety systems could be applied in nuclear power engineering.
</TEXT>
