<FILEID>AP-NR-04-13-89 2132EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Sudan     04-13 0398</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sudan,0408</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sudanese Rebels Order Bombardment Of Juba Garrison</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIDRIKKE SCHANCHE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sudanese rebels said Thursday they have
started shelling army garrisons in Juba, a city vital to a massive
U.N. emergency program to save 100,000 people from starvation in
the war-wracked south.
   However, relief officials in Nairobi said U.N. personnel
contacted by radio in Juba reported no shelling by Thursday
afternoon. The officials could not comment immediately on what
effect, if any, the rebel claim could have on the relief effort.
   In a broadcast monitored in Nairobi, the rebel Radio of the
Sudan People's Liberation Army said a long-range artillery
bombardment of army garrisons in Juba would last for four days. The
city is overcrowded with 300,000 residents and war refugees.
   Juba's airstrip is part of the ``corridors of tranquillity''
organized by the United Nations to stock 170,000 tons of food and
supplies in southern Sudan before seasonal rains make roads
impassable. U.N. officials warn that without such massive
intervention, 100,000 people could die of starvation.
   Juba, capital of Sudan's southernmost province of Equatoria, has
remained in government hands throughout the six-year war but
frequently has come under rebel fire. Rebels led by U.S.-educated
Col. John Garang have been tightening their siege of the city
throughout this year.
   Minority Christian and animist rebels took up arms against the
Moslem-dominated Sudanese government in 1983, demanding autonomy
and a larger share of Sudan's wealth and development for the south.
   They have shot down civilian and relief planes and attacked
truck, train and barge convoys, accusing the government of using
them to ferry supplies to troops.
   The international relief effort began April 1 after the Sudanese
government and the rebels agreed to let the emergency aid move
unhampered to rebel-controlled and government-held towns.
   Under the U.N. program, called Operation Lifeline, 108 tons of
food and supplies are being flown to Juba on six daily flights from
Entebbe, Uganda.
   Nils Enqvist, the Nairobi-based deputy coordinator of the
operation, said by Thursday afternoon he had heard no reports of
shelling from Juba. But, he said, if the rebels bombard Juba's
airstrip they will break their agreement to allow the $132 million
humanitarian effort to continue unhampered.
   Relief officials hope to avert a repat of the 1988 tragedy when
some 250,000 or more southern Sudanese died from starvation due to
flood, drought or war-induced famine.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
