<FIRST>u i AM-Israel 1stLd-Writethru a0635 04-13 0772</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0635,0793</SECOND>
<HEAD>Five Reported Killed in Village Raid</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 8 grafs to UPDATE with police tear gas Jerusalem
mosque. Picks up 4th pvs, `Maj. Gen....' with minor editing to trim</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto JRL1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN ALT POWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BETHLEHEM, Occupied West Bank (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli troops stormed into
a West Bank village before dawn Thursday in a search-and-arrest
raid, triggering one of the bloodiest clashes in the 16-month
Palestinian uprising. At least five Arabs were reported killed and
dozens wounded.
   Elsewhere, 16 Palestinians were wounded by gunfire in
confrontations with soldiers, including five shot in Bethlehem
riots to protest the death of a teen-ager who was wounded last
week, hospital officials said.
   In Jerusalem, Arab witnesses said riot police fired tear gas
into the grounds of the Al Aqsa and Dome of the Rock mosques, where
about 300 worshipers had gathered for evening prayers. Two
worshipers were slightly injured, Dr. Walid Elayan reported at
Mukassed Hospital.
   Mosque guard Abu Ahmed said police entered the walled compound
to make arrests. He said worshipers heard about the raid and ran
into the mosque courtyard chanting ``Allahu Akbar,'' Arabic for
``God is great.'' Police fired tear gas to disperse the crowd, he
said.
   Police spokesman Uzi Sandori said he was checking the report.
   A riot occurred in the mosque complex last Friday, first day of
the Moslem holy month of Ramadan. Thousands of worshipers stoned
police, who replied with tear gas and rubber bullets. More than a
dozen people were hurt.
   Thursday's violence came as Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir
concluded a 10-day visit to the United States, where he proposed to
President Bush that elections be held in the occupied territories
as a step toward peace.
   Maj. Gen. Amram Mitzna, the West Bank army commander, told
reporters he ordered an investigation into the incident in Nahalin,
about six miles southwest of Bethlehem.
   He said about 30 border police entered Nahalin to search for
Palestinians who were ambushing passing Jewish cars. They
encountered ``exceptional violence'' from about 100 Arab youths,
Mitzna said.
   Mitzna put the death toll at four and said at least 11 other
Palestinians suffered gunshot wounds in Nahalin.
   Arab villagers who showed an Associated Press reporter fresh
graves in the neighboring village of Hussan said a fifth person
from Nahalin was shot and killed in Hussan as he was driving to the
funeral of the four slain residents.
   An Arab doctor in the village said six died. The report could
not be confirmed by the army or hospitals.
   Doctors in hospitals said dozens of villagers were treated and
released. Fifteen were admitted, two in critical condition with
head wounds.
   Two hours of hit-and-run, stone-throwing attacks in Bethlehem
were sparked by the overnight death of 17-year-old Daoud Khaled
Nasser. He was wounded April 6, the day reporters saw soldiers open
fire without warning on fleeing protesters in apparent violation of
army regulations.
   His death and the five in Nahalin raised to 429 the number of
Palestinians killed since the uprising against Israeli rule began
in December 1987. Eighteen Israelis also have died.
   A curfew was clamped on Nahalin, a valley hamlet of about 2,000
people. Reporters were barred from entering.
   Mohammed Mustafa, 59, a farmer from Nahalin interviewed at
Mukassed hospital, said, ``It was a massacre.'' He added: ``The
army came to kill. They fired indiscriminately.''
   Israeli troops often raid before dawn to catch villagers by
surprise, but advancing border police were detected in Nahalin
where Moslems had arisen for a pre-dawn meal and prayers before the
daylong Ramadan fast, villagers said.
   Mohammed Ali, a teacher from Nahalin whose cousin was among
those killed, said about a dozen jeeps of border police troops
tried to enter the village about 4:30 a.m. He said village youths
blocked the roads with stones and threw rocks at soldiers, who
circumvented the barricades and entered on foot.
   ``Border police got on the roof and fired down on the people,''
Mohammed Ali said as he waited for neighbors being treated at Beit
Jalla Hospital. ``That's why there were so many head and chest
wounds.''
   Some villagers suggested Jewish settlers were involved in the
shooting, but Ali said he saw no civilians.
   The Nahalin death toll was the highest in a single incident
since Dec. 16, 1988, when four Palestinians died in clashes that
broke out at a funeral for a slain Palestinian in the West Bank
city of Nablus. Four other Palestinians died later of wounds
suffered at the funeral and subsequent clashes, since named ``Black
Friday'' by the Arabs.
   The highest single-day toll was 17 deaths recorded on April 16,
1988.
</TEXT>
