<DOCNO> AP890413-0182 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-13-89 2136EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-IndependentCounsels     04-13 0686</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Independent Counsels,690</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Proposes Law Change</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The attorney general would define the scope of
an independent counsel's investigation and could intervene in court
on legal issues under changes in the law proposed by President Bush.
   Besides extending the independent counsel statute to members of
Congress as well as high executive branch officials suspected of
wrongdoing, the proposals contain a number of changes in the
special prosecutor law.
   Bush's proposal would eliminate a controversial requirement that
independent counsels issue reports detailing their decisions not to
prosecute an official under investigation _ such as the lengthy
document issued last year on then-Attorney General Edwin Meese III.
   James C. McKay, the independent counsel who decided not to bring
charges last year against Meese drew criticism in legal circles
when the special court released his highly critical report of the
attorney general.
   Bush's plan would also empower the attorney general to ``define
the prosecutorial jurisdiction of the independent counsel'' without
any approval from the court that appoints the prosecutors,
according to a White House analysis of the proposals that was
released Wednesday.
   Under the current law, the attorney general submits a proposed
mandate to the special court, which has the power to widen or
narrow it.
   In the case of the Iran-Contra independent counsel, the special
court conferred a broader jurisdiction in its appointment of
Lawrence E. Walsh than was sought in late 1986 by Meese.
   Meese's application called for an independent counsel to examine
the diversion of U.S.-Iran arms-sale profits.
   Following a request from several members of Congress, the
special court issued a mandate that permitted Walsh to delve into
the full range of secret support the Reagan administration had
given the Nicaraguan rebels at a time such aid was barred by
Congress.
   Fred Wertheimer, president of the citizen lobby group Common
Cause, said this proposal ``kind of cuts back on the basic purpose
of the statute which was to get this outside of the ability of the
Justice Department to control the investigation.''
   Patti Goldman, an attorney for Public Citizen Litigation Group,
which supported the independent counsel when it was reviewed by the
Supreme Court last year, also criticized the proposal.
   Empowering the attorney general to set the jurisdiction ``gives
him control to keep the independent counsel from looking into
certain related things,'' Ms. Goldman said.
   Wertheimer predicted the proposals wouldn't ``be given serious
consideration in Congress,'' which voted in late 1987 to
reauthorize the law for five years.
   Under the Bush proposal, the special court would choose an
independent counsel from a list of 15 ``qualified prosecutors''
submitted by the attorney general. It has authority to appoint any
qualified attorney under the current law.
   The proposal would include a provision ``that the independent
counsel does not have authority to act for the attorney general
with respect to any matter which by law requires the persona action
of the attorney general,'' according to the White House summary.
   It also empowers the attorney general or the solicitor general
to intervene ``to address a matter of law'' in a case involving an
independent counsel rather than as a friend of the court.
   In the early stages of the Oliver North trial, U.S. District
Judge Gerhard A. Gesell ruled that the independent counsel _ not
the attorney general _ could speak for the Bush administration in
court on national security matters.
   Gesell rebuked the Justice Department for trying to intervene,
saying they could only the independent counsel could represent the
government in the case.
   Wertheimer and Goldman both defended the reporting provision of
the current law, saying it ensures accountability to both the
special court and the public.
   The reports are necessary, Wertheimer said, ``because we are
dealing with special circumstances... including the public
credibility of the investigation.''
   The White House summary said eliminating the reporting provision
would protect an official under investigation ``from unwarranted
speculation about crimes for which he or she will not be indicted.''
   This provision ``is consistent with longstanding prosecutorial
practice'' in which ordinary federal prosecutors do not explain
their decisions not to bring criminal charges.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
