<FIRST>r w AM-LewisIndicted     04-13 0348</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lewis Indicted,330</SECOND>
<HEAD>Barry's Friend Indicted for Perjury, Cocaine Possession</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD KEIL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Charles Lewis, a friend of Mayor Marion Barry
Jr., was indicted Thursday on seven counts of perjury and three
counts of cocaine possession stemming from an investigation into
Barry's visits to his hotel room last December.
   In the 10-page indictment, Lewis, a former District of Columbia
and Virgin Islands government employee, was charged with lying to a
federal grand jury about whether he possessed cocaine when Barry
visited him Dec. 22. Lewis is also charged with lying about using
cocaine with two separate individuals on Dec. 21, a day on which
Barry twice visited him.
   The federal probe began after city police on Dec. 22 were
inexplicably called off an attempt to make an undercover drug
purchase from Lewis, 48, after Barry showed up at his hotel room.
Barry has acknowledged contacting police officials looking into the
affair but has said he was only trying to speed up the probe.
   Lewis also is facing cocaine charges in the Virgin Islands.
   Federal investigators are also looking into Lewis' role in
coordinating a $260,000 joint project involving the city and Virgin
Islands governments. Lewis was fired from the project, which was
supposed to revise the islands government's personnel policies and
procedures, a year ago amid concerns about cost overruns.
   One of the perjury charges alleges that Lewis lied about whether
he possessed cocaine on Dec. 22, a day that Barry has acknowledged
visiting Lewis' room.
   ``That is the date...that the mayor was present at the Ramada
Inn,'' said U.S. Attorney Jay B. Stephens. Stephens also suggested
investigators will expand their probe into the events surrounding
those visits.
   Lewis also was indicted for lying about whether he bought from
or used drugs with two companions on Dec. 21. Barry reportedly
visited Lewis' room twice on that day.
   Barry, who has described Lewis as a friend, had no comment on
the indictment. He learned of the indictment while testifying on
the city's drug problem before a House District of Columbia
Committee panel.
</TEXT>
