<FIRST>r w AM-Armacost-Hearing     04-13 0399</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Armacost-Hearing,380</SECOND>
<HEAD>Armacost Denies Being at Meeting on Contra Aid</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush's nominee as ambassador to
Japan on Thursday denied assertions in the Iran-Contra trial that
he took part in a 1985 meeting where it was decided to reward
Honduras for backing the Contra guerrillas.
   A document released in the Oliver North trial said that Michael
H. Armacost, undersecretary of state in the second Reagan
administration, attended a meeting of a crisis pre-planning group
at the White House on Feb. 7, 1985, at which it was decided to
release military aid to Honduras in return for that nation's
continuing backing for the Contras.
   ``I read that ... in the paper with utter bewilderment,''
Armacost told a Senate Foreign Relations Committee hearing on his
nomination as ambassador to Tokyo.
   ``I did not attend that meeting on the 7th of February at the
White House. I am unable to reconstruct what they are talking
about,'' said Armacost.
   The Feb. 7, 1985, meeting had not been disclosed in
investigations of the Iran-Contra affair until the introduction at
the North trial of a 42-page admission of quid pro quo arrangements
that the Reagan administration reached with other countries.
   Evidence previously disclosed in the Iran-Contra investigations
said that Armacost and then-Secretary of State George P. Shultz had
raised objections to the secret sale of arms to Iran.
   North, a fired White House aide, is on trial for his role in
arranging the arms sale to Iran and diverting the profits to the
Contra guerrillas, who were battling the leftist government of
Nicaragua.
   Sen. Alan Cranston, D-Calif., who presided over the Armacost
hearing, asked Armacost to respond in writing to information on his
role that was contained in the document that the Bush
administration submitted as stipulated evidence in the North trial.
   Bush last week refused to comment on another portion of the
document that said he informed the Honduran president, Roberto
Suazo Cordova, that then-President Reagan had directed expedited
delivery of U.S. military items to Honduras in 1985.
   Bush's meeting took place shortly after Reagan approved slipping
more than $100 million in extra aid to Honduras in exchange for
that country's support of the Contras.
   Cranston said he expected the committee to approve Armacost's
nomination and send it to the floor of the Senate for a vote before
Congress enters a recess next Wednesday.
</TEXT>
