<FIRST>r w AM-NortheastPower     04-13 0488</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Northeast Power,470</SECOND>
<HEAD>Moore Sees Shoreham and Seabrook as Solution to Projected Shortages</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KIM I. MILLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Firing up the Shoreham nuclear plant on Long
Island and the Seabrook facility in New Hampshire would be a
solution to projected power shortages in the Northeast, an Energy
Department official said Thursday.
   Deputy Secretary W. Henson Moore of the Energy Department,
testifying before the Senate Energy Committee on the electricity
supply and demand outlook for the Northeast, said that ``we're
holding two birds in our hands and we're about to let them go in
hopes of finding one in the bush.''
   Moore called New England's energy outlook troubling ``because
reserve margins there could fall below acceptable levels as early
as 1993 if the recent robust demand growth continues.''
   ``If either demand growth exceeds projections as it has over the
last two years or if new capacity, including Seabrook, does not
come on line as planned, the situation in New England will be
exacerbated and reserve margins could fall below acceptable levels
as early as 1991 or 1992,'' he said.
   The energy situation in New York is generally good with the
exception of Long Island, he added.
   ``If (the Long Island Lighting Co.'s) peak demand grows by 4
percent this year, as it has averaged for the past six years,
LILCO's reserve margin would fall below 18 percent this year,'' he
said.
   But Peter Bradford, chairman of the New York State Public
Service Commission, testified that Shoreham ``would not have been a
great asset to the Long Island power supply situation in the near
future.''
   ``The fairest summary seems to be that if Shoreham ran well and
if oil prices rose rapidly, there might come a time when in the
next century it would be to the customers' net economic
advantage,'' he said. ``On the other hand, if oil prices remain
stable in real terms and Shoreham performs as erratically as many
nuclear plants, it would never be an asset economically on Long
Island.''
   Moore said the Energy Department would do everything in its
power to block the decommissioning of the Shoreham plant.
   ``We intend to throw up every roadblock we can find to do it,''
Moore said after the hearing. ``And if we have to create some,
we'll do that.''
   Asked what the department had in mind, he said, ``We don't know.
We're still looking at those opportunities, those alternatives. We
think it would just be foolhardy'' to decommission it.
   Moore said he'd rather see the $5.4 billion plant mothballed so
Shoreham will have another chance to operate later.
   ``When all the political rhetoric has died down and all the
hyper-opponents of nuclear power have gone their way and found some
other plant to demonstrate against, they'll start relooking at
those things and they will decide and tell their public officials
they'd like to have a reconsideration of this decision,'' Moore
told reporters.
</TEXT>
