<FIRST>r a AM-YellowstoneConference     04-13 0452</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Yellowstone Conference,0467</SECOND>
<HEAD>Politics, Ecology Mix At Yellowstone Symposium</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LARAMIE, Wyo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ecology and politics shared the stage
Thursday as participants in a symposium on the future of
Yellowstone National Park that rekindled the debate that arose
during the historic fires of 1988.
   The fires that charred about 1 million acres of the nation's
first national park drew attention to the shortcomings of
management plans in the park and surrounding national forests.
   ``The attention of the world conservation community is focused
on the park,'' Yellowstone Superintendent Bob Barbee told the
participants in the University of Wyoming conference.
   His goal is to develop a more ambitious control of the ecosystem
to oversee both the park and the forests.
   Barbee said the managers of the Greater Yellowstone area must
concentrate on protecting the area's natural resources while
maintaining the economic activities in the forests.
   ``These are easy things to say. They're hard things to
achieve,'' Barbee said. ``Our job is to cast a vote for posterity.''
   He noted that this week's conference may not offer any
solutions. About 300 people from across the nation came to Wyoming
to present research papers, debate and listen to speakers.
   Wyoming Gov. Mike Sullivan started the discussion on a political
note.
   He said cooperation among state and federal agencies in managing
and promoting Yellowstone is being sorely tested by a Bush
administration proposal to fund last summer's firefighting efforts
with the state's share of federal mineral royalties.
   ``Bluntly stated, this idea is feudalism and not federalism.
Western states are not vassals on some vast medieval estate owned
by absentee landlords in Washington, but this proposal would treat
us as such,'' Sullivan said.
   The governor said he has urged this ``ill-conceived idea'' be
reconsidered.
   Brian Stout, supervisor of the Bridger-Teton National Forest,
agreed that state officials need to be more involved in planning
the future of the Greater Yellowstone area.
   He said the many different demands on the federal land in
northwestern Wyoming make it tough to plan ahead.
   ``It is the diversity of demands upon this that are creating the
conflicts,'' Stout said. ``Conflicts aren't going to go away
because we are not creating any more acres.''
   Stout said he does not agree with some groups that say the
Yellowstone area should have one management plan. Currently there
are many government mandates controlling the use of public land in
the area.
   Stout said diversity is necessary because the variety of land
demands different management plans. Strong coordination efforts
will be the key to better management, he said.
   Last summer's fires brought the world's attention on the fact
that coordination has not been as effective as it should be, Stout
added.
</TEXT>
