<HEAD>White House Announces Michigan, ANPA, Other Trips</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Bush-Poland</HEAD>
<DATELINE>UNION, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush will go to Hamtramck,
Michigan, a Detroit suburb, on Monday to visit with Polish leaders
and give a foreign-policy speech, the White House announced
Thursday.
   Administration officials, who spoke on the condition of
anonymity, said Bush would unveil a series of steps to aid the
Polish economy during the appearance.
   The steps are in reaction to the recent concessions given the
trade union, Solidarity, by the government of Poland, the officials
said.
   The White House also announced that the president would make a
series of speeches on his ``legislative agenda'' later this month.
   He will address the annual meeting of The Associated Press in
Chicago on April 24 and then fly on to Northern California.
