<FIRST>r w AM-US-MiddleEast 1stLd-Writethru a0667 04-13 0901</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Middle East, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0667,920</SECOND>
<HEAD>Baker Says U.S. Will Continue Dialogue with PLO</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Updates with senators' letter to Baker, subbing 4 grafs for
14th graf pvs, Meanwhile Israel</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State James A. Baker III said
Thursday that the United States will continue its dialogue with the
Palestine Liberation Organization despite statements by some PLO
elements which appear to challenge Israel's right to exist.
   He also told a Senate Appropriations subcommittee that the
willingness of Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir to consider
holding elections in occupied Palestinian territories, followed by
negotiations leading to a permanent settlement, is a new and
hopeful idea which should be fully explored.
   Sen. Warren Rudman, R-N.H., read several recent statements by
PLO officials which he said seemed to suggest they remain committed
to the creation of a Palestinian state and the destruction of
Israel.
   ``Statements such as those are clearly not helpful,'' Baker
said. ``We do look at statements such as that very carefully
because we want to continue the dialogue with the PLO under the
conditions under which they were started.''
   But he said that the PLO is composed of ``many dissident
elements, some of which are opposed to any dialogue with the United
States and some which have not renounced terrorism.''
   ``To date we are satisfied that the PLO is committed to what it
has told us, that it recognizes Israel's right to exist and that it
has renounced terrorism in all of its forms,'' Baker said.
   Baker said Shamir's willingness to hold elections in the
occupied West Bank and Gaza to choose representatives to open
negotiations with Israel is ``new, different and significant.''
   He also noted that Shamir said all options would be considered
in the structure of transitional and permanent arrangements.
   ``We think this is progress,'' Baker said. ``It is a useful
first step. It should be explored. It should not be rejected
categorically out of hand.''
   He said the United States will encourage Shamir, Egyptian
President Hosni Mubarak and Jordan's King Hussein to preserve
flexibility ``so that the options may be explored and if possible
capitalized upon.''
   ``Elections are an important political act that can launch a
process leading to negotiations on both transitional and final
status issues,'' Baker said.
   Responding to questions, Baker said it would be difficult to
conduct elections if the violence associated with the Palestinian
uprising in the occupied territories continues.
   ``Surely there has to be a greater degree of calm or tranquility
before you get to elections,'' he said.
   Meanwhile, 38 senators told Baker in a letter that they would
seriously consider withholding U.S. financial support for the
United Nations if the PLO were recogized as a ``member-state'' by
the world body.
   The senators told Baker they viewed such a move with alarm and
that it `'sets the stage for continued stalemate'' on the
Arab-Israeli issue.
   The group, led by Sen. Robert W. Kasten Jr., R-Wis., urged Baker
to ``use every means at your disposal'' to discourage the drive.
   Elsewhere Thursday, Israel and the PLO jockeyed for position,
with Shamir refusing to follow Palestinian official Nabil Shaath in
appearances before a meeting of American newspaper editors. So,
organizers changed the schedule, with Shamir speaking first, and
Shaath's appearance was delayed.
   Shaath, political adviser to PLO chairman Yasser Arafat, told
the editors he did not mind appearing after Shamir.
   Shaath said the U.S.-PLO dialogue demonstrated ``close
proximity'' in their positions. Shaath said the PLO has accepted
that a Palestinian state would consist only of the West Bank and
Gaza, adding that ``it's a bitter pill for us'' but a concession
that Israel should accept.
   As for Shamir's proposal for elections, Shaath called it ``an
exhilirating idea'' for Palestinians but he rejected any elections
which would bar PLO participation and be held under Israeli
occupation.
   Shamir, asked whether he would allow international supervision
of such elections and would let PLO members hold office if elected,
said such issues would have to be worked out by a ministerial
committee he sted the PLO had not relinquished a dream of
eventually setting up a state that would include Israel itself,
saying Shaath and other PLO leaders were conciliatory and moderate
when dealing with Westerners but take a hard line when speaking to
the Arab world. ``Maybe they want peace, but not with us,'' he said.
   Baker's chief deputy, meantime, told a Jewish audience the PLO
may be sincere in its declaration that it no longer seeks to
destroy Israel.
   ``The evidence is mixed,'' Deputy Secretary of State Lawrence
Eagleburger told leaders of the United Jewish Appeal.
   ``Historically there can be no issue that was the object of the
PLO,'' he said.
   ``At the moment the jury is out,'' Eagleburger said, when asked
at a luncheon whether he believed statements by Arafat in December
that the organization supported Israel's right to exist.
   ``There are questions that need to be answered, it is no longer
clear in either direction,'' said Eagleburger, traditionally a
strong supporter of Israel.
   Eagleburger also said the United States was ``not trying to
mediate between the PLO and Israel.'' Discussions with the PLO, he
said, are an attempt to encourage Arafat's organization ``to take
constructive steps to allow a process between Israel and
Palestinians on the West Bank and in Gaza to develop.''
   ``We will get a better fix'' on the PLO's intentions, he said.
</TEXT>
