<FILEID>AP-NR-04-13-89 1822EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-NorthernIreland     04-13 0434</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Northern Ireland,0445</SECOND>
<HEAD>IRA Man Extradited by Helicopter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who escaped from the Maze
prison in a 1983 IRA breakout was extradited from the Irish
Republic to Northern Ireland by helicopter Thursday to avoid an
anti-extradition protest at the border.
   An Irish Republican Army statement took responsibility for a car
bomb that exploded next to a police station this week, killing a
woman, and said the explosion may have been premature.
   Paul Kane, 34, was only the fifth man extradited from the
republic to Northern Ireland since the IRA began fighting in August
1969 to unite the predominantly Protestant British province with
the republic, which is overwhelmingly Roman Catholic.
   He was driven in a police convoy from top-security Portlaoise
prison, 50 miles from Dublin, to the Irish Army's Curragh camp and
taken by army helicopter to within a mile of the border. He was
quickly transferred to a Northern Ireland police helicopter, which
flew him to Belfast.
   Kane was charged Thursday night in Belfast Crown Court with
escaping from the Maze and other crimes.
   The helicopter transfer enabled police to avoid 200
anti-extradition campaigners who waited at the border for more than
24 hours to protest. Members of Sinn Fein, the legal wing of the
outlawed IRA, demonstrated at Portlaoise as Kane was driven away.
   He was arrested in the republic in November 1987 and had
resisted British attempts at extradition. Kane was serving 18 years
for IRA activities after conviction on the evidence of an informer,
Christopher Black.
   When the convictions resulting from Black's testimony were
quashed after the Maze breakout, Kane claimed he had been wrongly
imprisoned but he still faced the escape charge.
   He was one of 38 men who fled the Maze on Sept. 25, 1983. A
guard was stabbed to death and another was shot and seriously
wounded.
   In its claim of responsibility for the Wednesday bombing, the
IRA offered ``sincere apologies'' to the family of 20-year-old
Joanne Reilly, a Roman Catholic killed by the explosion in
Warrenpoint, less than a mile from the border.
   Miss Reilly worked in a hardware store next to the police
station and was hit with the full force of the bomb, which wounded
31 civilians and nine police officers. Police said they believe it
contained 1,500 pounds of explosives.
   Officials said more than 2OO homes were damaged.
   The IRA killed 18 British army soldiers in an ambush outside
Warrenpoint on Aug. 27, 1979. That same day, an IRA bomb on his
yacht killed Lord Louis Mountbatten, India's last viceroy and a
cousin of Queen Elizabeth II.
</TEXT>
