<FILEID>AP-NR-04-13-89 2144EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Bush 1stLd-Writethru a0668 04-13 0795</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0668,790</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Urges ``Partial Deregulation of Education''</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Adds 3 grafs at end with background on plan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNION, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush proposed a ``partial
deregulation of education'' Thursday, saying schools in poorer
communities would be given more flexibility in how they may spend
government money.
   Aides said Bush's proposal, an expansion of the package he
announced last week, would result in the elimination of burdensome
federal regulations.
   Bush, speaking at an education conference at Union High School,
sought to build public support for his education package while
renewing his argument that more money from the government will not
necessarily improve educational performance.
   ``We need to rely less on the collective wallet and more on our
collective will,'' he said.
   Bush, who campaigned on a theme of wanting to be the ``education
president,'' last week proposed $441 million in new spending for
school programs _ but without spelling out where the money would
come from.
   Overall, Bush's budget would freeze federal spending on many
education programs. It calls for total education spending of $21.9
billion _ the same level sought by former President Reagan in his
fiscal 1990 budget.
   Bush's proposals include awards and grants to outstanding
schools and teachers, an expanded program of magnet schools that
focus on curriculum specialties, and more funds for historically
black colleges. The plan has been criticzed as inadequate by
congressional Democrats.
   Bush told his audience, ``We want to help those most in need,
targeting federal resources where they can do the most good.''
   ``We want to waive some regulations for poorer communities,
allowing them to pool state and federal funds in exchange for
higher accountability and performance _ a kind of
performance-driven, partial deregulation of education, if you
will.''
   ``We'll give you the flexibility, you show us the results,''
Bush told a cheering audience of educators and students.
   Education Secretary Lauro F. Cavazos told reporters on Air Force
One that the administration would seek to relax regulations ``to
get funds to local schools without a lot of paperwork and a lot of
bureaucracy.''
   ``In essence, it is a type of deregulation,'' Cavazos said. He
said, however, that it would not represent a return to block grants
to schools, abandoned during the Reagan administration.
   He also said that, while poor communities would be the first to
benefit from the relaxation in federal regulations, the flexibility
would eventually be extended to other communities as well.
   On his way to the speech, Bush's motorcade made an unannounced
stop at Hamilton School, where the president greeted Gina Marie
Sisco, a sixth-grade student who had written him a letter.
   She was among a group of flag-waving students clustered on the
curb outside the school.
   In the letter, a portion of which Bush later read during his
speech, the young correspondent said only students who had won an
academic fitness award had been invited to the president's speech.
   ``I am a resource room student for math and English. I have a
learning disability. There are many kids like me and we all have to
work harder than most kids,'' she wrote.
   Bush praised Miss Sisco, saying, ``It's excellence and it's hard
work.''
   Barbara Bush attended the speech and was given a rousing
applause when her husband introduced her.
   ``She got a good clean bill of health yesterday from Walter Reed
Army Hospital,'' Bush said. Mrs. Bush received a radioactive iodine
treatment at the hospital to deal with a thyroid problem.
   In his speech, Bush said of money and education, ``A nation that
worships money _ or sees money as a cure for all that ails it _ is
a society in peril.''
   ``More spending isn't the only right answer or even the best
answer,'' he said. ``What we need is better value for what we
spend. What we need ... is a shared determination on the part of
every American to get involved with our schools. ... We must
reestablish the value of teaching and learning in this country.''
   Bush's ``partial deregulation'' plan closely follows
recommendations that were made to him after the election by the
Rochester, N.Y.-based National Center on Education and the Economy
headed by Apple Computer chairman John Sculley.
   The group has proposed waiving red tape and regulations in favor
of innovative local plans approved by state and federal
governments. Freedom from the rules would continue as long as
students met the performance targets set in the plans. As
envisioned by the center, the experiments would be used later as
models to revamp federal programs.
   Sculley said last month that Bush had been ``extremely
interested in what we had to say'' at a meeting in December. Both
teacher unions have endorsed the concept, at least on an
experimental basis.
</TEXT>
