<FIRST>r w AM-NationalService     04-13 0332</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-National Service,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bill Introduced</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two members of Congress introduced legislation
Thursday urging creation of a voluntary community service program,
increasing G.I. bill benefits and calling on the Bush
administration to develop a mandatory national service plan.
   Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., and Rep. John Porter, R-Ill., said
that although eight other national service measures exist, their
bill addresses the true concept of national service.
   ``There are those of us, Congressman Porter and myself, who
believe all Americans should serve their country. That is the basic
linchpin of this legislation,'' McCain told a news conference.
   The main aspect of the bill is the mandatory service proposal
that includes part-time and full-time community service programs as
well as full-time service in the active, reserve or National Guard
elements of the armed forces, or service in the Coast Guard.
   ``I realize that will be roundly criticized in some sectors of
our society but I think the worse thing was the injustice
perpetrated during the Vietnam War,'' McCain said. ``We asked a
certain economic level of our society to serve and allowed another
economic level of our society to remain at home.''
   McCain fought in Vietnam and spent 5 1@2 years as a prisoner of
war.
   Under the part-time community service program, volunteers will
serve 24 hours per month and two weeks during the year. Service
will be two to four years.
   Current G.I. bill benefits would be raised from $10,800 to
$15,120 for active duty members, and could be used for education,
vocational training or toward the purchase of a first primary
residence.
   The program's costs, according to the legislation, must fall
within existing budgets. The initial cost of the community service
program is $250 million with states providing the full matching
funds. Increases in the G.I. bill will be part of the Defense
Department budget.
   Porter said the legislation would ``provide the groundwork for a
resurgence in national service by encouraging young Americans to
make a commitment to their country.''
</TEXT>
