<FIRST>u i AM-Soviet-Vietnam     04-13 0542</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Vietnam,0559</SECOND>
<UNK>Soviet Advisers Saw Combat in Vietnam, Military Newspaper Says</UNK>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet military advisers helped their North
Vietnamese allies shoot down American airplanes with missiles
during the Vietnam War, the Soviet Defense Ministry newspaper
reported Thursday.
   Red Star carried a series of reminiscences that were believed to
be the first direct admission that Soviet military advisers engaged
in combat in the war.
   The newspaper's disclosures were typical of the greater openness
by the Soviet military under President Mikhail S. Gorbachev. But
they sounded a jarring note at a time when improved superpower
relations have brought more sympathetic coverage of the United
States by state-run media.
   Red Star said it was printing the reminiscences in response to
requests from readers.
   ``With three missiles, we brought down four planes,'' said Sgt.
N. Kolesnik, recalling a July night in 1965 when the troops he was
advising set up an anti-aircraft battery near a ruined town that
American pilots used for target practice.
   ``All of us worked well,'' Kolesnik said, naming fellow Soviets
he called the targeting officer, the computation commander, the
operator and other soldiers at ``the firing stations.''
   Later, Kolesnik said, the Vietnamese the Soviets were training
set up wooden decoys of missiles. After bombing the decoys to no
avail, the departing American planes ran into the enemy field of
fire and three Skyhawks were downed, Kolesnik said.
   The Soviets began training Vietnamese rocket troops in spring of
1965, Gen. Maj. G. Belov told Red Star.
   The soldiers' recollections mainly concerned training Vietnamese
to work with Zenith missiles and the battle to keep technologically
ahead of the Americans.
   The U.S. forces changed their schedule of air sorties after the
Soviets arrived, according to excerpts from the diary of Col. G.
Lyubinetsky. Previously they had flown on a regular schedule with
breaks and predictable days off.
   But after the Soviet specialists arrived, ``They realized that
they had to take the rocket forces seriously,'' Lyubinetsky wrote.
   Col. V. Fyodorov recalled that in 1966, when a Vietnamese
division ``was running a battle independently, already without the
participation of our specialists,'' it brought down an American
plane and the captured pilot refused to believe that the Vietnamese
had acted on their own.
   ``I don't believe you,'' he said when he was assured the
Vietnamese were responsible. ``Something smells Russian here.''
   During an unspecified period of battle while the Soviet regiment
was in action, 43 missiles brought down 23 American planes,
Fyodorov said.
   Belov said Soviets died in Vietnam, but did not say how many.
   One officer recalled being personally thanked for Soviet aid by
North Vietnamese leader Ho Chi Minh, and another said he saw a
Soviet soldier throw himself on a bomb to save a young Vietnamese
girl.
   When two Soviet technicians were leaving for home, Vietnamese
officers and soldiers ``were practically crying'' and walked a long
way behind their departing car calling, ``Linso, Linso,'' the
Vietnamese word for Soviet, Maj. Gen. A Trombachev said.
   ``That's how friendly you can get in eight months,'' he said.
   A recent article in Red Star described Soviet missile
specialists' work in the Middle East, and an editor's note
accompanying Thursday's article said readers also had asked for
information on Soviet troops in Syria and North Korea.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
