<FIRST>r i AM-UN-Iran-Iraq     04-13 0345</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-UN-Iran-Iraq,0353</SECOND>
<HEAD>UN Says Iran-Iraq Peace Talks Resuming April 20 In Geneva</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Direct peace talks between the foreign
ministers of Iran and Iraq will resume April 20, eight months to
the day after a cease-fire took effect in the 8-year-old war, U.N.
officials said Thursday.
   Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar will mediate the talks
in Geneva between Ali Akbar Velayati of Iran and Tariq Aziz of
Iraq, U.N. spokesman Francois Giuliani said.
   He read a statement from Perez de Cuellar urging both nations to
show more flexibility in the talks, which have been stalled almost
since they began Aug. 25, five days after the truce.
   It suggested the secretary-general would press Iraq to withdraw
from the Iranian territory occupied in the last days of fighting
and urge Iran to cooperate in clearing the Shatt-al-Arab, Iraq's
only sea outlet. The border waterway, closed early in the war, is
clogged with sunken ships and silt.
   ``The secretary-general and his special representative have
emphasized the need for withdrawal without delay to the
internationally recognized boundaries, the release and repatriation
of the prisoners of war and the speedy beginning of the mediation
efforts'' for a peace agreement, said the statement read by
Giuliani.
   Iraq occupies at least 260 square miles of Iranian territory,
according to U.N. estimates. Iran has said withdrawal must be
accomplished before prisoners are repatriated or other issues are
discussed.
   ``Pragmatic arrangements, particularly with regard to the
economic life of the two countries, may well be needed to hasten
the return to normality,'' the statement said in apparent reference
to Iraq's demand that the Shatt be cleared.
   Perez de Cuellar will be in Geneva on April 19-25 as part of a
European tour. His special representative for the peace talks,
Swedish U.N. Ambassador Jan K. Eliasson, will accompany him to the
negotiations.
   Giuliani said the negotiations probably would last two days,
preceded by individual meetings with Velayati and Aziz. Separate
meetings with Iranian and Iraqi officials who visited New York led
to the resumption.
</TEXT>
