<DOCNO> AP890413-0201 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-13-89 2158EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-TelephoneDeregulation     04-13 0511</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Telephone Deregulation,510</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dingell Says Congress Should Be Overseeing Telephone Industry</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY ARNOLD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congress is ready to assume federal guidance
of the telephone industry with legislation that would spur new
technologies and make sure consumers don't foot the bill, Rep. John
Dingell said Thursday.
   The Michigan Democrat, in an address to an audience of telephone
company executives, said the industry won't like everything
Congress is going to do on telecommunications issues this year,
that lawmakers ``will not satisfy the corporate protagonists in
this debate.''
   ``It will include provisions that one side will say are
unnecessary, and the other will decry as insufficient,'' said
Dingell, who is chairman of the House Energy and Commerce Committee
that deals with telephone issues.
   But he said it was time Congress lifted current restrictions on
the Bell operating companies that ``limit their ability to grow and
their ability to bring new products and services to the American
marketplace.''
   Dingell said he wants to return to Congress the ability to
oversee the development of the telecommunications industry, end
restrictions that ``constrain technological development and deprive
users of access to products and services'' and protect residential
subscribers ``from paying for the competitive ventures of the
telephone companies.''
   He said existing telecommunications policy under Congress, the
courts and the Federal Communications Commission is ``ad hoc and
uncoordinated. It makes no sense.''
   U.S. District Court Judge Harold Greene, Dingell said, has been
faced with an impossible situation in his effort to oversee the
Modification of Final Judgment under which American Telephone &amp;
Telegraph Co. split off the regional phone companies in 1984.
   The regional companies were prohibited from entering the
long-distance, manufacturing or information services marketplaces.
   Greene's dilemma, Dingell said, is to watch out for possible
antitrust violations by the powerful telephone companies while at
the same time recognizing the impact of his decisions on
international trade, universal telephone service and U.S.
competitiveness in information technologies.
   ``The more the judge takes these factors into account, the more
he usurps the authorities of the Congress,'' Dingell said. ``He can
properly limit his purview to questions of antitrust and end up
with decisions that are not in the larger national interest.''
   Dingell cited a recent decision by Greene to allow one of the
seven regional Bell companies, Pacific Telesis, to participate in a
trans-Pacific telephone cable project.
   He said the judge's ``decision repeatedly addresses the foreign
trade aspects of Pac Tel's participation and concludes that the
benefits outweigh any potential antitrust concerns.''
   Dingell said Congress, or an agency overseen by Congress, should
be making such decisions.
   ``It is not my purpose to criticize the judge for that decision.
My purpose is simply to point out that he is in an impossible
position,'' Dingell said.
   ``It is time for Congress to legislate the structure of the
American telecommunications industry and permit Judge Green to
return to his other duties and obligations.''
   Dingell said Reps. Al Swift, D-Wash., and Tom Tauke, R-Iowa,
were putting final touches on such legislation and it would be
introduced next week.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
