<FIRST>r w AM-ASNE-Clash     04-13 0382</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-ASNE-Clash,380</SECOND>
<HEAD>Israeli Ambassador, ASNE Clash</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israel's ambassador to the United States
clashed Thursday with the American Society of Newspaper Editors in
an incident reflecting the intractability of the Arab-Israeli
conflict.
   Ambassador Moshe Arad accused James Squires, editor of the
Chicago Tribune and one of the organizers of the annual ASNE
meeting, of seeking to embarrass Israel by inviting a PLO
representative to address the convention along with Prime Minister
Yitzhak Shamir.
   Shamir spoke to the group earlier Thursday and was followed less
than two hours later by Nabil Shaath, the political adviser to
Palestine Liberation Organization leader Yasser Arafat.
   Originally, Shamir was scheduled to make a back-to-back
appearance after Shaath, but organizers rescheduled at the last
minute to accomodate the Israelis' desire that Shamir and Shaath
not bump into each other, Squires said in an interview.
   Squires said he was ``quite astonished to hear'' from Arad that
Shamir could not appear on the same day as Shaath, but he
nonethless assured the ambassador he would do all he could to
prevent any meeting between the two men or their security details.
   He conceded he had told Arad he might be able to move Shaath's
appearance to the following day although he did not know if the
Palestinian's schedule would permit such a change.
   Arad said Squires had promised to try and schedule any PLO
speaker for the following day and ``I am deeply dismayed by this
breach of commitment on your behalf.''
   Arad said Squires had failed to inform him until this week of
the invitation extended to the PLO ``and an attempt to put them on
the same platform in direct sequence to each other reflected an
attempt to embarrass us.''
   Arad said he ``could not imagine'' that Squires had not known
Shaath would appear so closely following Shamir and ``still you
preferred to withhold this information. I find the entire handling
of the invitation most inappropriate and unethical.''
   Squires insisted that Arad ``was given no misleading
information'' about the speaking engagements, saying ``it's
ridiculous for them to dictate to us how we run our meeting.
   ``It's none of Mr. Arad's business who we choose to invite to
the ASNE meeting,'' Squires said. ``It's exactly the kind of
absurdity that this Middle East conflict is producing.''
</TEXT>
