<SECOND>AM-Diana, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0718,0305</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Lunges at Princess Diana</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with man's identity, quotes. No pickup</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CRAMLINGTON, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 57-year-old man who grabbed
Olympic sprinter Florence Griffith-Joyner in a passionate embrace
last August lunged at Princess Diana when she visited this town
northern town Thursday.
   Edward Adcock, a carpenter, said he meant no harm to the
27-year-old princess when he jumped over railings as she spoke to a
crowd outside a workshop for the mentally handicapped.
   ``I am sorry if I caused her any upset because I have always
admired her enormously,'' he said. ``I might have been in the
process of trying to give her a hug. She is attractive and I fancy
her, but I didn't realize it would finish up this way.
   ``I may appear calm on the surface, but inside me there is
turmoil. I have had some trouble in past years and now it has come
up again. But there is no way I would be violent or harm anyone.''
   Television pictures show the princess was startled. She stepped
backward as three burly detectives hurled themselves between her
and Adcock, but quickly regained her composure and continued
chatting with people in the crowd.
   A Northumbria police spokesman said further inquiries would be
made and no charges had yet been filed.
   In August, Adcock grabbed the American sprinter from behind as
she peeled off her track suit after winning a race in Gateshead. He
was not charged.
   Adcock wonders how his workmates at a building site will regard
his latest caper. ``They pulled my leg a lot over the Flo-Jo
business,'' he said.
   One person clearly was not pleased.
   Hetty Adcock, the carpenter's 85-year-old mother, broke into
tears when she heard the news and cried: ``Oh no! Not again!''
</TEXT>
