<FILEID>AP-NR-04-13-89 2210EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Trade-WorkerRights     04-13 0498</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Trade-Worker Rights,480</SECOND>
<HEAD>Buma and CAR Dropped</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government on Thursday announced that
Burma and the Central African Republic, because of violations of
worker rights, are being dropped from a program offering developing
nations duty-free entry of goods into the United States.
   At the same time, U.S. Trade Representative Carla Hills said her
office had rejected requests that Israel and Malaysia be denied the
benefits of the Generalized System of Preferences program because
of allegations about similar violations.
   In Israel's case, the government investigated complaints from
the American Arab Anti-Discrimination Committee that Arabs from the
West Bank and Gaza who travel to work in Israel are denied certain
rights and receive less wages and benefits than do other Israeli
workers.
   The USTR declined to revoke Israel's trade benefits, saying the
country was ``taking steps to afford internationally recognized
worker rights.''
   The government also refused to investigate the American Arab
group's allegations that Palestinians working inside the occupied
territories are being discriminated against, saying the West Bank
and Gaza are not legally considered part of Israel.
   Faris Bouhafa, a spokesman for the American Arab group, said his
organization was pleased that steps apparently are being taken to
correct violations within Israel and with the finding that the
territories are not part of Israel. However, he said his group
would have preferred that duty-free trade benefits be denied to
Israel ``until conditions were cleared up in their entirety.''
   The Generalized System of Preferences program was begun in 1976
to promote the economic growth of developing countries and help
them compete with industrialized countries in the U.S. market. It
provides preferential duty-free entry to about 4,100 products from
136 countries and territories.
   In 1984, the program was amended to require that countries'
benefits under the program be suspended if they are not working to
provide internationally recognized worker rights.
   Benefits for Burma and the Central African Republic had been
challenged by the AFL-CIO because of restrictions on the right to
organize independent unions and other alleged violations of rights.
The AFL-CIO also had filed complaints alleging violations of worker
rights in Haiti, Syria and Malaysia.
   A complaint against Liberia had been filed by the Lawyers
Committee on Human Rights, which alleged that the Liberian
government restricts workers' rights to organize unions and bargain
collectively.
   Venezuela's trade benefits had been challenged by Occidental
Petroleum, based on its claim that the company's assets were
expropriated without compensation by Venezuela's government-owned
oil company in 1975.
   The USTR said Haiti, Liberia, Syria and Venezuela will continue
to be part of the duty-free trade program while the complaints
remain under review for up to a year.
   AFL-CIO spokeswoman Lorrie McHugh said the organization was
``extremely disappointed'' with the government's failure to act on
its petitions against Haiti, Syria and Malaysia.
   ``We feel that the other three countries should have been
removed because workers are being seriously exploited and denied
very basic rights,'' she said.
   The changes announced Thursday take effect July 1.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
