<FIRST>r i AM-Britain-Czar     04-13 0272</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Czar,0279</SECOND>
<HEAD>Queen Should Attend Burial Of Czar Nicholas, Expert Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Queen Elizabeth II should be invited to a proper
Christian burial of the remains of the last Russian czar, which
were reported this week to have been found in the Soviet Union,
Burke's Peerage said Thursday.
   ``Not only the imperial family's relatives but others who wish
to show their sorrow for the fate of the last of the Romanovs
should be able to attend,'' said Harold Brooks-Baker, publishing
director of the bluebloods' guide.
   He said the queen should not accept President Mikail S.
Gorbachev's invitation to visit the Soviet Union until she is given
details of the fate of Czar Nicholas II and his family. Gorbachev
extended the invitation last Friday over lunch with the queen at
Windsor Castle at the end of a two-day visit here.
   The czar, a cousin of the queen's grandfather, King George V,
was shot with members of his family at Ekaterinburg by Bolshevik
revolutionaries in 1918.
   The Soviet weekly Moscow News reported Wednesday that a former
police officer-turned-screenwriter, Geli Ryabov, claimed to have
found the remains 10 years ago in a field near the execution site
but kept silent because times had not been right for publication.
   Ekaterinburg, about 900 miles east of Moscow, was renamed
Sverdlovsk after the revolution.
   Brooks-Baker said the question still to be answered was, ``Who
killed them?''
   ``It was either on orders right from the top or from a local
official in charge of the family, who panicked when anti-Red forces
_ probably the Czech Legion then in the area _ approached the
town,'' Brooks-Baker said.
</TEXT>
