<FIRST>r a AM-Hoffman-Quotes     04-13 0904</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hoffman-Quotes,0941</SECOND>
<HEAD>Steal These Quotations: Abbie Hoffman In His Own Words</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Hoffman Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   On the stand in Chicago Seven Trial:
   ``My name is Abbie. ... I'm an orphan of America.
   ``I live in Woodstock Nation. A state of mind for young people.
   ``I'm a child of the 60's. My present occupation is a cultural
revolutionary. But I'm really a defendant full-time.
   ``I never heard of a law against sexual intercourse in New York
City.''
   When asked if he had written a statement about his thoughts
during the 1968 Democratic convention week, Hoffman asked, ``Do you
mean `Did I write that I had these thoughts or did I actually have
them?' There's a difference, you know.''
   Prosecutor: ``There's a difference when it's convenient for
you.''
   H: ``Well, I don't know. I've never been on trial for my
thoughts before.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   ``I had a great urge to confess during this trial because I
heard the prosecution say I am an enemy of the state and I am. I'm
an outlaw. I always knew free speech wasn't allowed in present-day
America. You are allowed to believe in free speech but you can't
practice it.'' _ Part of statement at sentencing in Chicago Seven
trial, Feb. 20, 1970.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   ``(Drug) dealing, although dangerous, is a tax-free way of
surviving even though it borders on work.'' _ from ``Steal this
Book.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   ``George Washington grew hemp. He was probably a pothead. Ben
Franklin had 17 illegitimate kids.'' _ Statement comparing Chicago
Seven to the founding fathers at sentencing Feb. 20, 1970.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   ``They're going to have to cut off a lot more than our hair.
They're going to have to cut off our heads to stop the revolution.
The modern Philistines are going to feel the revenge of the seven
Samsons.'' _ Statement Feb. 28, 1970 after appeals court freed
Chicago Seven on bond _ they had hair cut by authorities when they
were jailed.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   ``Yippies believe in the violation of every law, including the
law of gravity.'' _ Speech at Columbia rally, March 14, 1970.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   ``We learned something in that trial at Chicago. We learned how
to wreck the whole court system, just like we wrecked the political
system on the streets of Chicago in 1968. All you got to do is
stand up to the judge and yell `How come?''' _ April 12, 1970 rally.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   ``The little people are going to whip the big people every time
the little people are right and keep a-coming. We are all outlaws
in the eyes of America, but we are proud outlaws, and we are going
to fight. We are going to put ourselves in the places the rulers of
America now hold. The youth of this nation is going to replace the
government and we are going to keep it.'' _ April 12, 1970 rally.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   ``I have not made a move in 20 years that hasn't had a political
motivation or been connected with a cause. ... My life has not been
about being a con artist out to make a quick buck.'' _ In interview
after surrendering in 1980 after six years as a fugitive,
responding to charges that he turned himself in to promote his new
book.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   ``I'm some one who says people can change their destinies. ...
You can do it, ... you can fight City Hall, and in that sense, I'm
a threat.
   ``I'm antiterrorist because they have no sense of humor and you
can't convince people of your point of view through the use of
terror.'' _ In interview after surrendering in 1980 after six years
as a fugitive.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   ``There were too many people of the 60's turned sour in the 70's
turned rich in the 80's. ... I am well aware that I am entering an
age of cynicism. I want to change that.'' _ In interview upon
re-emergence in 1980 to face cocaine charges.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   ``We can live very well for much less than we are led to believe
and still manage time to battle social or environmental
injustices.'' _ 1980 writing.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   ``Listen, the 60's were a fluke _ even I know that. What you see
here is student life as it's been since time immemorial. Most of
these kids don't want to make waves. All they want is to graduate,
get a good job and participate in the plasticity of the rat race.''
_ In 1985 interview before taking the stage in Yippie vs. Yuppie
debate with Jerry Rubin.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   ``You are talking to a leftist. I believe in the redistribution
of wealth and power in the world. I believe in universal hospital
care for everyone. I believe that we should not have a single
homeless person in the richest country in the world. And I believe
that we should not have a CIA that goes around overthrowing
governments and assassinating political leaders, working for tight
oligarchies around the world to protect the tight oligarchy here at
home.'' _ in 1987 interview with the New York Times.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   ``I grew up with the idea that democracy is not something you
believe in, or a place to hang your hat, but it's something you do.
You participate. If you stop doing it, democracy crumbles and falls
apart.'' _ From Hoffman's closing argument April 15, 1987 in
University of Massachusetts-CIA trespassing trial with Amy Carter.
The defendants were acquitted.
</TEXT>
