<FIRST>r w AM-Mexico-Narcotics     04-13 0222</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mexico-Narcotics,230</SECOND>
<HEAD>Reject Mexico Criticism</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate Foreign Relations Committee voted
14-3 on Thursday to reject an attempt to brand the government of
Mexico as uncooperative in the U.S. war against narcotics after
Secretary of State James A. Baker III declared such an accusation
is undeserved.
   The attempt was made by Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C., who contended
that President Bush's certification of Mexico as cooperative in
narcotics-control efforts was unjustified.
   The committee acted after Chairman Claiborne Pell, D-R.I., read
a letter in which Baker said Mexican President Carlos Salinas ``has
repeatedly pledged to make the fight against narcotics traficking a
national priority.''
   Baker added: ``He has backed up his tough rhetoric against drugs
and corruption with concrete actions. I remain thoroughly convinced
that the best way to reduce the flow of drugs through and from
Mexico is by improving our bilateral anti-narcotics cooperation.''
   Had the Helms inititive prevailed, the United States would have
had to end any economic assistance to Mexico and vote against that
country in international financial institutions.
   Bush could have prevented that course of action by declaring
that certification of Mexico was in U.S. national security
interests, even though Congress had found it was not cooperating in
anti-nartcotics efforts.
   Only Sens. Larry Pressler, R-S.D., and Connie Mack, R-Fla.,
joined Helms in voting for the proposal.
</TEXT>
