<FILEID>AP-NR-04-13-89 1920EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-VietnameseParade     04-13 0409</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Vietnamese Parade,0418</SECOND>
<HEAD>Councilman Stirs Anger With Remark to Vietnamese Immigrants</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WESTMINSTER, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A city councilman conceded Thursday
that he may have misspoken when he told Vietnamese immigrants, ``If
you want to be South Vietnamese, go back to South Vietnam.''
   Councilman Frank Fry stopped short of apologizing for the
remark, which he said was intended to suggest that immigrants need
to make more of an effort to assimilate into American society.
   Some Vietnamese immigrants in this suburban Orange County
community said they would try to recall Fry over the remark,
delivered Tuesday night before the council voted down a request for
a parade to honor Vietnam War dead.
   ``We're trying to promote harmony in the city,'' said Tien
Nguyen, a member of the organizing committee for South Vietnamese
Armed Forces Day. ``We are observing the American way, as well as
our heritage.''
   Parade committee spokesman Arthur Suchesk called Fry's comments
``nothing more than a bigoted, racial slur against the Vietnamese.
... It's like telling the Irish to go back to Ireland if they want
to celebrate St. Patrick's Day or Mexicans that they can't
celebrate Cinco de Mayo. He ought to be impeached.''
   Fry was among four of five councilmembers who voted against
closing a street in the city's Little Saigon area for a June 18
parade to honor South Vietnamese and Americans killed in the
Vietnam War.
   Three of the four councilmembers who voted down the two-hour
parade said the parade organizing committee should time its event
to conform with a U.S. holiday, such as Memorial Day.
   ``It's my opinion that you're all Americans and you'd better be
Americans. If you want to be South Vietnamese, go back to South
Vietnam,'' Fry told the parade organizers. ``That may be unfair,
but that's my opinion and I'm sure that is the opinion of a lot of
people around here.''
   Fry, a World War II veteran, said Thursday he had received about
five calls from Vietnamese immigrants supporting his statement,
because they believe the immigrants should assimilate. But he said
it may have been ``a little harsh'' to tell the immigrants to go
back to their homeland.
   Fry said he meant only to counsel the immigrants to ``try to
change and become an American, learn English, it is your new
language. Join in with the populace and learn your new ways.''
   ``I don't mind being recalled,'' he added, ``but the
polarization that would cause would be horrendous.''
</TEXT>
