<FIRST>r a AM-PeoriaFire     04-13 0584</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Peoria Fire,0600</SECOND>
<HEAD>Vagrant Charged In Fatal Fire Known as `Trouble'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT LEE ZIMMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PEORIA, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   He was a small man known as ``Trash Can
Joe,'' a vagrant who lived mostly at a mission. But he could turn
violent, and when he was thrown out of an apartment house he
returned to set it on fire, killing seven children and two young
mothers, authorities say.
   Joe Pickens, 34, held Thursday on a $2 million bond, is charged
with first-degree murder and arson in Tuesday's fire. Authorities
said the victims died in their sleep as the second floor of their
ramshackle frame house filled with smoke and flames.
   ``Joe was a small guy _ he couldn't whip a flea,'' said Jim
Garner, who lives across the street from the burned-out house. ``He
didn't even have the mind of a teenager. I just don't know what to
think.''
   Richard Brienen, superintendent at the Peoria Rescue Mission,
Pickens' most frequent address, said Pickens could be mean and
vengeful when drunk and once threw bricks at the mission after
being ejected for breaking its rules.
   ``My nickname for him was Trouble,'' Brienen told reporters.
``The guys used to call him Trash Can Joe. Sometimes when he'd get
kicked out of here he would just go crawl out in the trash cans to
sleep.''
   Pickens had numerous run-ins with the law, police said. On March
31, he ignored a judge's order to begin serving a 30-day sentence
for resisting arrest, the Peoria Journal Star reported. It was his
22nd misdemeanor conviction since 1983.
   The missed jail date was included on the jail's list of
violations to be brought to the attention of Peoria County State's
Attorney Kevin Lyons _ an action the jail says takes about two
weeks.
   ``I don't fault the sheriff or the jail,'' Lyons said. ``The
impression (that the fire could have been avoided) is not unusual
in any tragedy.
   ``It's like if one of (the victims) had been just visiting, and
the mother says `If only I had kept them home.'''
   Neighbors were not sure when Pickens, a native of York, Ala.,
first appeared in Peoria, or why.
   Garner said Pickens, whom he has known about two years, could
not read or write and had the mind of a 10-year-old.
   Fire Chief G. John Parker said Pickens apparently stayed in the
apartment house he set afire but was ordered out Monday night,
though Parker did not know why.
   On Wednesday, Pickens admitted to police that he had set the
fire in a rollaway bed in a vacant first-floor apartment early
Tuesday morning.
   ``He was an easy-going guy until he got into the booze,'' Garner
said. ``I guess he wanted to scare them because they put him out,
but that's a terrible way to scare somebody.''
   Garner's wife Claudie said Pickens was a friend of Joyce Barnes,
one of two residents of the house to survive the blaze.
   ``She'd ask him to leave sometimes but he'd usually come back,''
said Mrs. Garner. ``I'm angry and hurt and surprised he'd do
something like that to those folks. They were nice and never did
anything to hurt anyone.''
   Killed in the fire were Terry Davis, 27, and her three children:
Karlissa, 2, Arnisha, 7, and Tanoa, 10; Davis' sister, Wanda Hobbs,
20, and her children: Ashley, 1, Felicia, 4, and Eugene Roberts
Jr., two months; and Jacolby Thomas, 2, daughter of Ms. Barnes.
   Ms. Barnes and Eric Davis, 14, were hospitalized.
</TEXT>
