<FIRST>r i AM-Venezuela     04-13 0170</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Venezuela,0178</SECOND>
<HEAD>Protesters Burn Trucks And Throw Bombs To Protest Economic Measures</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 100 hooded students protesting
government economic policies took over the grounds of the Central
University campus Thursday and threw homemade bombs at police,
authorities said.
   The protesters hijacked at least three trucks at entrances to
the university, dragging the drivers out and setting the vehicles
on fire.
   The protesters, their faces covered with T-shirts, crouched
behind barricades and threw homemade Molotov cocktails at police
stationed at intersections around the university.
   Under Venezuelan law, police are banned from entering the campus
of the university, an autonomous institution.
   Police occasionally fired tear gas in the direction of the
protesters.
   There were no reports of injuries.
   New economic measures designed to move Venezuela toward a
free-market economy have led to drastic price increases in consumer
goods and public services.
   Riots over the measures in late February left at least 276 dead
by government count, although other estimates put the number at
between 300 and 500.
