<FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     04-13 0489</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0502</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rain in Texas, New England and Plains; Mostly Fair and Mild Elsewhere</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Rain fell in Texas, New England and the northern Plains on
Thursday, and mild weather elsewhere in the nation brought water in
another form: flooding snowmelt.
   Southeasterly winds spread moisture from the Gulf of Mexico
across much of central and eastern Texas, where intense downpours
fell in some places. Golfball size hail was reported at Braunig
Lake, Texas.
   A cold front pushed into western New England, bringing scattered
rainshowers. Snowshowers fell from parts of western Pennsylvania
into south-central New York state. Bradford, Pa., received an inch
of snow.
   Rainshowers fell across eastern North Dakota and northwest
Minnesota ahead of a cold front that was slowly sagging into the
region.
   Mild temperatures were reported across much of the nation _ bad
news for people living along swollen rivers.
   The Red River continued to flood in eastern North Dakota and
western Minnesota as melting snow raised its level to as high as 15
feet above flood stage.
   Minor lowland flooding also was reported along the Pearl River
in southeast Louisiana and along the lower Ohio River.
   Heavier rainfall during the six hours ending at 2 p.m. EDT
included .56 inch at Dyess Air Force Base in Texas and about a
third of an inch at Kingsville, Mineral Wells and Abilene, Texas.
   Temperatures were in the 50s or 60s across much of the nation,
but in the 40s across much of the Great Lakes and New England and
in the 70s and 80s in parts of the South and Southwest.
   A few cities recorded record low temperatures. The lows included
28 degrees in Asheville, N.C., 36 in Huntsville, Ala., and 20 in
Madison, Wis.
   The low in the nation Thursday morning was 12 degrees at
Gunnison, Colo., and Marquette, Mich.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 34
degrees at Buffalo, N.Y., to 95 degrees at Palm Springs, Calif.
   The National Weather Service forecast for Friday called for
scattered rain from the Great Lakes through the middle Mississippi
Valley, with widespread rainshowers and thunderstorms from the
eastern parts of the southern Plains through the lower Mississippi
Valley and the central Gulf Coast.
   Scattered rain also was expected across the northern half of
Maine. The remainder of the nation was expected to have pleasant,
mild weather.
   High temperatures were expected to be in the 60s or 70s across
much of the nation. Highs were forecast in the 50s from the
northern High Plains through the northern Plains and the lower
Great Lakes into much of New England; in the 40s from the upper
Mississippi Valley into the northern Great Lakes and across
northern and coastal parts of New England; in the 80s across the
southern half of Florida and the southern tip of Texas; and into
the 80s and 90s from Oregon through much of California into the
desert Southwest.
</TEXT>
