<FIRST>r a AM-ConfederateHome     04-13 0351</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Confederate Home,0361</SECOND>
<HEAD>Residents of Home For Confederate Women Ready About Move</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KAREN HAYWOOD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   There were some smiles and a few tears
Thursday when officials told a handful of daughters of Confederate
soldiers they would be moved permanently from their home in the
former capital of the Confederacy.
   ``I think it will be best to move. It seems like it will be so
much better, but I love everyone here,'' said 89-year-old Osa Lee
Yates, her voice cracking. She has lived in the Home For
Confederate Women for two decades.
   ``We went up there (to the new home) and looked through it,''
said Miss Yates. ``It was great.
   Beginning May 15, the eight residents will be moved to
Brandermill Woods Active Retirement Center, about 20 miles outside
of Richmond, said Janet Burhans, president and chairman of the
Confederate home's board of managers, which unanimously approved
the move Thursday.
   The 58-year-old home, which is owned by the board but sits on
state land, will go to the state along with much of the furnishings
in exchange for the women's care at the new nursing home.
   Caring for them there will save $160,000 to $170,000 a year,
according to board member Carter Pollard. Mrs. Pollard said the
board had been dipping into its trust fund for $200,000 to $300,000
a year and the fund would have been gone in about five years.
   Bertha Moore, 88, said she enjoys the activities at the home but
added, ``All my friends are going'' to the new facility.
   ``We fold napkins once in a while when they need them,'' she
said. ``We have church on Sunday mornings. On Tuesday, we have
Reverend Graham. He comes and he stays an hour. It's just Bible
study.''
   As visitors milled around, Mary Lynn, 87, sat down at the piano
in the home's memorial room where portraits hang of Mrs. Andrew
Jackson Montague, who raised money for the home, and Confederate
General Robert E. Lee.
   A trace of a smile was on her lips as she played a spirited
rendition of ``Dixie.''
</TEXT>
