<FIRST>r i AM-Peru     04-13 0303</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Peru,0311</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rebel Insurgency Claims 59 Lives This Week</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AYACUCHO, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leftist guerrillas killed 11 peasants in
raids on two mountain hamlets and one policemen in a separate
attack, officials said Thursday. That bought the insurgency death
toll this week to 59 nationwide.
   More than 690 people were killed in the first three months of
1989, making it one of the bloodiest periods in Lima's nine-year
insurgency, Sen. Enrique Bernales, head of the Senate commission on
violence, told Congress Wednesday night.
   In Lima, police on Thursday reported 305 people were arrested
this week in El Agustino slum in anti-insurgency sweeps. Officials
said most of those arrested had no identification papers and were
held briefly until they could prove their identities.
   The violence fueled opposition charges that President Alan
Garcia's center-left government is losing ground to the rebels and
its anti-insurgency policy is in disarray.
   More than 14,000 people have died in the violent campaign by the
Mao-inspired Shining Path movement to impose Marxist rule. The
uprising began in the impoverished countryside around Ayacucho, 235
miles southeast of Lima.
   Most of the dead have been highland peasants, but thousands of
others _ non-combatants, rebels, police and soldiers _ have also
been slain.
   In the latest violence, a Shining Path column attacked a police
post near Andahuaylas, 72 miles southeast of Ayacucho, around
midnight Wednesday, killing one policeman and wounding three,
police said.
   Shining Path attacks killed 11 peasants Monday in Tantarpata and
Jotapuquio, tiny hamlets located near each other about 60 miles
northeast of Ayacucho, police said.
   Report of the attack was delayed due to the area's remoteness,
they said.
   Also on Monday, troops killed 34 Shining Path guerrillas in
jungle clashes, and on Wednesday rebels killed 12 peasants at
Chongos Alto and a political leader in Huancayo in the highlands.
</TEXT>
