<FILEID>AP-NR-04-13-89 2323EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Fusion-Washington     04-13 0476</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Fusion-Washington,0494</SECOND>
<HEAD>Washington Researchers Conduct Cold Fusion Experiment</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Fusion-Profits, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two graduate students said Thursday they had
detected indications of cold fusion in an experiment conducted with
heavy water, but they could not get the same results using ordinary
water.
   Van L. Eden and Wei Liu, physics students at the University of
Washington, said they did not duplicate exactly the highly
publicized experiment by University of Utah chemist B. Stanley Pons
and Martin Fleischmann of England's University of Southampton.
   Pons and Fleischmann said they apparently produced nuclear
fusion in a tabletop experiment using ordinary lab equipment.
   But Eden, 28, and Liu, 27, said they did get indications that
fusion may have taken place in their experiment last week.
   In the experiment, a mass spectrometer detected a possible
indicator of tritium, a radioactive isotope of hydrogen commonly
produced in fusion reactions.
   The indicator was found when the experiment was run using
deuterium, a hydrogen isotope and component of deuterium oxide or
``heavy water.'' Eden said the indicator was not detected when the
test was repeated with ordinary water.
   The students' results, if confirmed, could help answer a
question raised about the Utah experiment by Harold Furth, director
of plasma physics at Princeton University.
   Furth, at a meeting Wednesday of the American Chemical Society
in Dallas, said that some experts believe the energy detected in
the Utah experiment is actually a chemical reaction that is not
understood.
   But he said if the experiment worked using deuterium oxide but
not ordinary water, it would suggest the reaction actually did
involve some sort of deuterium fusion.
   The students said, however, that they did not detect the
substantial quantities of neutrons expected from a fusion reaction,
although they were not using a particularly sensitive detector for
them.
   For their experiment, the pair used a test tube containing
deuterium oxide in which a palladium electrode and gold wire were
placed and connected to a power source. The palladium electrode was
connected to a vacuum chamber, which in turn was connected to the
mass spectrometer, which detects nuclear particles.
   Pons and Fleischman used a platinum wire instead of gold, and
observed the amount of excess heat produced, rather than observing
tritium particles.
   Eden and Liu cautioned that their results were preliminary and
needed review by other scientists. They also said they had not
ruled out other explanations for what was observed.
   Researchers at Brigham Young University, Texas A&amp;M, Georgia Tech
and Moscow University in the Soviet Union also have found possible
indications of cold fusion, but said their findings need further
testing.
   Fusion, the energy process that powers the sun and the hydrogen
bomb, has been touted as the ultimate energy source if a means
could be found to produce it economically.
   The two students said their major out-of-pocket expense was for
``about three pizzas'' bought by Liu.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890413-0222 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-13-89 2034EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-WrightProbe 4thLd-Writethru a0793 04-13 1212</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Wright Probe, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0793,1200</SECOND>
<HEAD>Embattled Wright Mounts Emotional Defense of Ethics Charges</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts new graf after 4th graf pvs, And a, report completed;
2 grafs after 12th graf pvs, Sources familiar, with votes on various issues</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With his position as the nation's highest
elected Democrat in jeopardy, House Speaker Jim Wright mounted an
emotional defense Thursday against serious ethics charges and
declared he would ``fight to the last ounce of conviction and
energy that I possess.''
   In a carefully scripted 30-minute counteroffensive delivered to
reporters and television cameras, Wright sought to rebut point by
point the charges being lodged against him by the House ethics
committee, which was writing its final report after a 10-month,
$1.5 million investigation of his finances.
   Wright's supporters called the appearance persuasive, but other
Democrats were agonizing over the prospect that their most visible
official might become a political liability and have to be deposed.
   And a member of the ethics panel, Rep. John T. Myers, R-Ind.,
said the speech would have no effect on the committee's
conclusions. ``We have a task to do, and I don't think we'll be
influenced at this point,'' he said.
   The committee completed work on its report late Thursday and
scheduled a news conference Monday morning to release it. The
report will include a statement alleging that Wright violated House
rules in several dozen instances, said a source familiar with the
investigation.
   Flanked by members of his leadership team and Texas colleagues,
Wright's voice choked with emotion as he defended his wife, Betty,
against the charge that her $18,000-a-year salary from a Fort Worth
business partner amounts to an improper gift.
   He said his wife was ``a good decent, caring, thoroughly
honorable person'' and he would ``damn well fight to protect her
honor and integrity from any challenge from any source whatever the
cost.''
   ``Whether I'm speaker of the house, which is the greatest honor
I've ever had, is not important,'' Wright said. ``What is important
is that Congress move swiftly _ and I'm prepared to move very
swiftly _ to get distractive matters of this kind behind us so that
we can concentrate on the really important things that affect this
country of ours.''
   He said his reputation ``is the most important thing and the
only really important thing. For my good name, which is the legacy
I intend to leave my children and my grandchildren, I will fight to
the last ounce of conviction and energy that I possess.''
   Wright declined to field questions after his statement. After
his impassioned public defense, Wright returned to the business of
the House, appearing in the chamber to push for a vote on a $49.7
million Contra aid package.
   Rep. Charles Wilson, who was among the three dozen or so of the
260 House Democrats to attend Wright's speech, said the event
``serves to brace everybody up for a good, hard tough fight.'' But
he added, ``We haven't hit bottom yet.''
   Sources familiar with the deliberations said all crucial votes
already had been taken and had gone against Wright on the two most
serious charges: that he violated House rules by accepting gifts
from a business partner with an interest in legislation, and that
he evaded limits on collecting speaking fees through bulk sales of
his book, ``Reflections of a Public Man.''
   One source said the 12-member panel _ evenly divided between
Democrats and Republicans _ had been unanimous in its decision that
Wright's acceptance of use of a car and condominium constituted
unreported gifts, and voted 10-2 to place Mrs. Wright's salary in
that category. The vote also was 10-2 to hold that Wright sought to
evade outside income limits through bulk book sales.
   But on the most potentially serious issue for Wright, whether
Mallick had an interest in legislation, the committee split 8 to 4,
with Democrats Chet Atkins of Massacusetts and Bernard Dwyer of New
Jersey siding with the six Republicans on the panel.
   The committee decisions essentially closed the $1.5 million
investigation and sent the case into a new, more open and more
political phase which could lead to a disciplinary hearing and a
range of punishments.
   The investigation not only jeopardizes Wright's leadership post,
but some lawmakers feared the action also pointed toward a new and
unrealistic standard for congressional conduct. One member of the
ethics committee predicted the decisions would add urgency to a
revamping of House ethics rules now in its early stages.
   Wright began his day Wednesday with a 10-minute, highly personal
speech to his strongest supporters at a closed-door leadership
meeting, and was given a standing ovation, according to
participants. They said his eyes misted as he lamented that his
wife had been drawn into the ethics case. ``I thought his
performance was touching,'' said Rep. David Obey, D-Wis.
   Later, the Texas Democrat told reporters: ``There are some
things worth fighting for, and one of them is personal honor and
reputation earned over 66 years of living and giving. And that's
far more precious to me than any public office.''
   Alluding to charges that his wife had done little work for a
salary she was paid by a Fort Worth business partner, Wright added:
``My wife's reputation is very precious to me. And I'm damn well,
darn well, not going to let that be sacrificed.''
   The mood among Democrats was somber. The report is certain to
force difficult political decisions on whether to uphold their
party's most visible official in the face of certain Republican
efforts to capitalize on the alleged ethical shortcomings of the
man who stands behind Vice President Dan Quayle in line of
succession to the White House. No speaker has ever been chased from
office by ethics violations.
   Rep. Dale Kildee, D-Mich., said members wanted to be fair to
both Wright and the House of Representatives. ``I think there's a
deep concern both as to the person of the speaker and the Congress
itself,'' he said. ``There's a lot of agony.''
   During three weeks of deliberations, debate and votes, sources
said the committee decided:
   _That upwards of $100,000 worth of benefits Wright and his wife,
Betty, received from Fort Worth real estate developer George
Mallick amounted to unreported ``gifts.'' The benefits included
Mrs. Wright's $18,000-a-year salary from 1980 through 1984 and free
use of a condominium and a 1979 Cadillac. House rules require
reporting of any gift over $100.
   _That because of his extensive investments in real estate and
oil and gas enterprises, Mallick had ``a direct interest in
legislation before Congress.'' That meant any gifts worth more than
$100 accepted by the Wrights would violate House rules.
   _That on several occasions Wright sold bulk quantities of his
book to organizations to which he had made speeches in lieu of
accepting honoraria. Speaking fees are limited by the rules, while
book royalties are not.
   The next step in the ethics process is for the committee to
issue a formal statement of the allegations against Wright. The
speaker then would have 21 days to present rebuttals and
counter-arguments before the committee determines whether to call
for a disciplinary hearing to decide whether sanctions are
warranted. Sanctions can range from a simple reprimand to expulsion
from the House.
</TEXT>
