<HEAD>Bush to Visit Lockerbie, Site of Pan Am Crash</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Adds 4 grafs of reaction at end</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Flight 103</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush will visit Lockerbie, Scotland,
where a Pan Am jumbo jetliner crashed after being blown apart by a
terrorist bomb, an administration source said Thursday.
   Bush plans to stop in Lockerbie on the way back from a NATO
summit in Brussels, Belgium and visits to Italy, England and West
Germany. He is scheduled to leave Washington on May 26 and return
June 1 or 2.
   A White House official said Bush wants to thank the people of
Lockerbie for their help in searching for victims, cleaning up
afterwards and helping relatives after the tragedy.
   The official, declining to be identified, said Bush is
considering the visit but ``it isn't a done deal.'' However,
another source, also speaking anonymously, said Bush would make the
stop.
   A White House survey team already has visited Lockerbie and an
advance team is expected to stop there within the next week for
further planning.
   The bombing of Pan American Wprld Airways Flight 103 last Dec.
21 killed 259 people aboard the plane and 11 on the ground in
Lockerbie.
   Bush recently met at the White House with a delegation of
relatives of victims of the Pan Am flight.
   Lockerbie citizens expressed pleasure at Bush's decision to
visit the town.
   Francis Park, convener of Annandale district council which
includes Lockerbie, said: ``As a former flier himself, I'm sure he
will have a close affinity with everyone involved in the disaster.''
   The local Church of Scotland minister the Rev. Rev James Annand,
who took part in the public memorial service for the victims of the
bombing, said Bush's visit would be an historic occasion for
Lockerbie and for Scotland.
   ``I can understand why he would want to visit the town. I have
been told by Americans that the crash created the biggest shock in
their country since the shooting of President Kennedy,'' Annand
said.
