<TEXT>
   President Bush has selected Lt. Gen. Ronald L.
Watts to become the next inspector general of the Army, the
Pentagon announced Thursday.
   Assuming Senate confirmation, Watts will succeed Lt. Gen. Henry
Doctor Jr., whom the Pentagon said would retire on Aug. 1 after
more than 35 years of active duty service.
   In the post of inspector general, Watts will oversee the staff
that handles internal audits and investigations of Army programs to
ensure they are conducted properly.
   Watts, 54, is a native of Seneca, Mo., who is currently serving
as the commander of VII Corps, U.S. Army Europe and the Seventh
Army. Doctor, 56, is a native of Oakley, S.C., who has held the
inspector general post since July 1986.
