<FIRST>r a AM-RobinsonFuneral     04-13 0203</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Robinson Funeral,0210</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sugar Ray Felled by Heart Disease, Coroner Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Heart disease killed champion prizefighter
Sugar Ray Robinson, a spokesman for the county coroner's office
said Thursday.
   Robinson, whose all-around boxing strength and skill led many
ring experts to consider him the world's greatest boxer
pound-for-pound, died Wednesday at the age of 67.
   The Rev. Jesse Jackson will preside over Robinson's funeral
service, set for 11 a.m. Wednesday at West Angeles Church of God
and Christ in Los Angeles, said Reve Gibson, Robinson's niece.
   A post-mortem examination showed Robinson died of
arteriosclerotic cardiovascular disease, which coroner's spokesman
Bob Dambacher interpreted as gradual weakening and hardening of the
arteries.
   The five-time middleweight champion also suffered Alzheimer's
disease and diabetes, Dambacher said.
   A public viewing of Robinson's body is scheduled for Monday
evening and Tuesday at the Angeles Funeral Home, Gibson said.
   Robinson, who dominated the ring for a quarter century until his
retirement in 1965, compiled a record of 175-19-6, including 110
knockouts.
   Besides his wife, Millie, Robinson is survived by a son from an
earlier marriage, Ray Jr., two stepchildren _ Ramona Lewis and
Butch Robinson _ four grandchildren and a sister, Evelyn Nelson of
New York.
</TEXT>
