<FILEID>AP-NR-04-13-89 2359EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-MuseumFire     04-13 0214</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Museum Fire,0220</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fire Chases Hundreds of Patrons from Museum</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A smoky fire chased hundreds of patrons from
the county Museum of Art on Thursday, but apparently did little
damage and spared a traveling exhibit of works by American painter
Georgia O'Keefe.
   The fire, reported at 12:56 p.m., was confined to a basement
hallway in the three-year-old Robert O. Anderson Building, one of
the museum's five halls, said city Assistant Fire Chief Jim Young.
   Smoke permeated the five-story building, and museum experts were
trying to assess possible damage to artworks after the flames were
doused at 1:19 p.m., he said. One firefighter suffered minor burns.
   The display of 120 O'Keefe paintings was in an adjoining
building and was untouched by smoke, authorities said. The popular
exhibit has been turning away patrons every day since it opened on
March 30th.
   The fire gutted a basement hallway used to store files and other
material, but the flames didn't reach galleries in the Anderson
building housing modern art, Young said.
   Patrons were evacuated by museum staff, Young said, adding that
120 were counted leaving the Anderson building and similar numbers
were assumed to have fled the other galleries. People were allowed
to return to all but the Anderson building about 3:15 p.m.
</TEXT>
