<FIRST>r a AM-Marcos-Transfer     04-13 0229</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Marcos-Transfer,0237</SECOND>
<HEAD>Marcos To Transferred From Intensive Care Unit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Philippine President Ferdinand Marcos was
transferred Wednesday from St. Francis Medical Center's intensive
care unit to its telemetry unit, which monitors heart patients, a
hospital spokeswoman said.
   Marcos, 71, was listed in guarded condition early Wednesday,
hospital spokeswoman Norma Kop said. He has been hospitalized since
Jan. 15 for treatment of heart and respiratory ailments.
   ``His condition hasn't really changed, but we're trying to free
up a room in ICU for a patient who may need it more,'' she said.
   The telemetry unit provides for monitoring heart patients, but
less acute care than the intensive care unit.
   Marcos and his wife, Imelda, 59, are under indictment on federal
racketeering charges accusing them of stealing more than $100
million from their homeland and stashing it in the United States.
   U.S. prosecutors have conceded that Marcos is too ill to stand
trial and have temporarily severed him from the case, but the
government is proceeding with the case against Mrs. Marcos.
   The ousted leader has more than $250,000 in unpaid bills at the
hospital. Mrs. Marcos claims the U.S. government should pay the
bills and that she is financially unable to do so.
   The Marcoses came here in February 1986 after their ouster in a
popular revolt that catapulted Corazon Aquino to power, ending
Marcos' 20-year rule.
</TEXT>
