<DOCNO> AP890413-0230 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-13-89 2205EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-TankerSpill 3rdLd-Writethru a0798 04-13 1130</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tanker Spill, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0798,1161</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cleanup Continues: Oil Near Cook Inlet, But No Farther</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 29th graf, `The National ..., to make it $15 million, sted
$1.5 million.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FRED BAYLES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP National Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VALDEZ, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The tedious task of scrubbing clean the
coastline and corraling remaining Exxon Valdez oil blotches
continued Thursday as a light sheen splashed islands at the
entrance to giant Cook Inlet.
   ``It'll probably splatter them, but we're not expecting too much
damage,'' said Hal Alabaster, spokesman for the National Oceanic
and Atmospheric Administration. ``We're having trouble estimating
what's going on out there because the currents are so tricky.''
   The leading edge of the spill, sighted west of Gore Point on the
Kenai Peninsula, continues to break up, said Coast Guard spokesman
Roy Compton. Gore Point is about 25 miles from the entrance to the
Cook Inlet, which leads to fishing towns such as Kodiak and Homer,
and even to Anchorage.
   The oil has not been seen in Cook Inlet, Alabaster said.
   In Prince William Sound, crews of workers continued to clean
islands, where tides have begun to wash from light sheen off the
beaches.
   ``That's favorable,'' Compton said. ``It gives them more of a
chance to recover the oil.''
   The shoreline was covered in oil following the March 24
grounding of the Exxon tanker, which sent 10.1 million gallons of
oil into the sound. More than 840,000 gallons has been recovered,
about 8 percent of the spilled oil.
   Coast Guard Commandant Paul Yost arrived in Valdez to take
charge of the cleanup effort.
   After flying over the area, Yost said he could see a marked
improvement since he visited to assess the spill for President Bush
two weeks ago.
   ``Things are getting better, and we're going to do everything we
can to expedite the cleanup,'' said Yost. ``It is important not to
forget that we have a long-term cleanup _ not days or weeks, but
probably for months.''
   Yost said he has given Exxon until Saturday to come up with a
plan for beach cleanup, including the number of personnel and
logistical support.
   ``I'm not in a happy relationship with Exxon,'' Yost said. ``I'm
here to oversee what they're doing, and I have some marching orders
from the president of the United States.''
   The National Transportation Safety Board announced it will hold
four days of public hearings beginning May 16 in Anchorage.
   ``The board's investigation will center on determining the
probable cause of the accident,'' said board member Lee Dickinson.
``While we will be examining initial emergency response efforts, we
will not be assessing the environmental issues raised by the
accident.''
   Spokeswoman Drucella Andersen said the agency expects to call
about 20 witnesses to talk about the nation's worst oil spill.
   Winds were generally out of the northeast Thursday, meaning they
could help push oil away from land, but the forecast called for a
wind shift to the southeast, increasing to 35 knots with a gale
warning, the Coast Guard said. Seas were forecast to increase to 9
feet in the Gulf of Alaska by Friday.
   Exxon-paid cleanup workers have filled hundreds of bags a day
with thick crude oil and gravel on Naked Island. About 100 workers
in oil-splattered yellow slickers were on the shoreline, mostly
scraping the crud off rocks with their hands.
   They call it rock waxing.
   ``I've been working with another fellow and we've packed at
least 100 gallons of the oil on this beach. For scooping it out of
the rocks that's pretty good. It makes a difference, out of 10
million,'' said Dean Carl, a wood boat refinisher from Valdez.
   ``This is a priority affair. We're doing good enough that every
day it's harder to find oil to pick up. That means something.''
   Workers are on the boats in Valdez at 6 a.m., ride for three
hours to the island and get back on the boat at about 4 p.m. after
seven hours of work. When converted cruise ships and sleeping
barges _ dubbed ``floatels'' _ are in place, the workday will be 12
to 14 hours because travel time to the islands will be eliminated.
   The state has identified 3,000 pieces of shoreline it hopes to
clean by the rainy season in late August. Only 44 are ready for
clean-up, said Department of Environmental Conservation
Commissioner Dennis Kelso.
   ``We have a fairly short opportunity to finish this before the
weather changes,'' Kelso said.
   At the Kenai Fjords National Park, light oil sheen has
splattered some outer islands, and tar balls have reached some
shoreline, but no significant damage is reported.
   ``The tips of the peninsula have been slimed for the past couple
of days, but the worst that could have happened hasn't happened
yet,'' said Jon Erickson, a park spokesman.
   Fishing towns along the coast have spent four tense days waiting
for the oil to hit land. Officials said that until all oil has
broken up and swept to sea, changes in the weather could still
throw crude ashore.
   Aerial surveys earlier showed significantly less oil on the
water, the result of earlier high wind and rough seas.
   The National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration announced
Thursday that Exxon made a $15 million down payment for the cost of
assessing the spill's long-term impact on Alaska's natural
resources.
   Administrator William Evans said the money would go toward costs
incurred by his agency, and for years of research into the effects
of the oil on sealife and animals in the region.
   ``NOAA's going to have a team here for a very long time,'' Evans
said.
   He said the focus of the research would be on what steps will be
necessary to restore or replace the fisheries and other natural
resoucres affected by the spill.
   The announcement came one day after Interior Secretary Manuel
Lujan complained in Washington that Exxon was dragging its feet in
providing ``up-front money'' for the planning process.
   Holland America-Westours Inc., the state's largest cruise
operator, announced it was contributing $100,000 to volunteer
efforts to save wildlife and will spend $1 million in television
commercials to reassure tourists that most of Alaska was not
affected by the spill.
   Thousands of sea birds and otters have died as result of the oil
slick, which coats fur and feathers with a poisonous goop that
prevents the animals from staying warm and bouyant.
   Biologists have recovered 150 dead otters. Fifty-four of 113
others being treated at a rescue center have died. So far, 1,242
dead birds have been found along the coast, 227 birds have been
rescued for treatment; 87 of those have died and nine have been
released.
   The herring fishery season set for this weekend in the Kodiak
area will go on as scheduled, officials said, but fish will be
tested for contamination.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890413-0231 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-13-89 0147EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Romania     04-13 0410</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Romania,0424</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ceasescu Says All Romanian Foreign Debt Repaid</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Nicolae Ceausescu announced
Wednesday that as of March 31 communist Romania had repaid all its
foreign debt, the Romanian state news agency Agerpres reported.
   In 1981, Romania's foreign debt totaled about $11 billion, but
the Bucharest government stopped almost all imports of Western
machinery and stepped up food exports for hard currency at the
expense of serious food shortages at home.
   By the end of 1988, Romania's foreign debt had dropped to about
$2 billion.
   There have been no indications, however, that authorities will
raise living standards by importing badly needed consumer goods.
   Hard currency earnings are badly need to buy Western machinery
and equipment to modernize mostly outdated industrial
installations. Most available resources probably will be used for
that purpose.
   Ceasescu runs the most repressive nation in the Soviet bloc, and
his efforts to rid it of foreign debt left Romania financially
strapped, with food and power shortages further reducing a poor
standard of living.
   The president's announcement came at the opening of a three-day
session of the Romanian Communist Party's policy-setting Central
Committee.
   ``I wish to inform the plenary meeting, the entire party and our
entire people that at the end of March Romania fully paid back its
foreign debt,'' Agerpress quoted Ceausescu as saying.
   ``This is the outstanding result of our people's work devoted to
the country's socio-economic development. It proves the might of
the Romanian socialist economy and opens wonderful prospects for
implementation of the party program of building the multilaterally
developed socialist society and Romania's advance to communism.''
   Agerpres said Ceausescu on Wednesday received a group of U.S.
business people representing over 50 companies that have trade
relations with Romania.
   Romania was deprived of Most Favored Nation trading status on
the U.S. market last year because of its record on human rights.
   If accorded the privilege, Romania would get the same terms as
those granted now or in the future to any other nation.
   Ceasescu referred to the issue in his meeting with the
Americans, saying ``There is only one problem awaiting an
appropriate solution, that is to apply the 1975 economic accord
which also provides for the mutual granting of the Most Favored
Nation clause unconditionally on either side.''
   Ceausescu said he would like to see two-way trade between the
United States and Romania reach the $2 billion mark annually,
Agerpres reported. He did not give the current figure.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
