<DOCNO> AP890413-0232 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-13-89 0151EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Hunthausen     04-13 0483</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hunthausen,0497</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rome Formally Ends Review Of Hunthausen's Ministry</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 5{-year Vatican review of Seattle's archbishop
who has come under fire from conservative Roman Catholics has
ended, the pope's U.S. representative announced Tuesday.
   A special three-member oversight commission that looked at
Archbishop Raymond Hunthausen's ministry ``is completed and its
mandate terminated,'' said Archbishop Pio Laghi, Pope John Paul
II's delegate to the United States.
   In a two-paragraph statement issued in Washington, D.C., Laghi
said Hunthausen ``has indicated that he, along with Coadjutor
Archbishop Thomas J. Murphy, will continue to address the issues
which have been of concern to the Church.''
   Hunthausen responded: ``I am grateful for the announcement by
Archbishop Laghi of the closure of the work of the apostolic
commission.
   ``Both Archbishop Murphy and I acknowledge the trial the church
here has faced over the past several years, yet we are also able to
view the whole experience as a time of grace, a grace which, with
the Lord's help, will enable us to offer our leadership to the
church in Western Washington in the years ahead.''
   Hunthausen, 67, said after a trip to Rome earlier this year that
he had been assured the review of his work in the Seattle Roman
Catholic Archdiocese had been completed, and that the apostolic
commission, chaired by Cardinal Joseph Bernardin of Chicago, would
be dissolved.
   The commission, which also included Cardinal John O'Connor of
New York and Archbishop John Quinn of San Francisco, was set up in
January 1987 to review Hunthausen's ministry. The Vatican has kept
close watch on Hunthausen since November 1983 after some
conservative Catholics criticized the archbishop.
   In a move that outraged many U.S. Catholics, the Vatican in 1985
removed Hunthausen's authority in five areas, including ministry to
homosexuals, some liturgical matters and the tribunal that decides
marriage annulments.
   Hunthausen had been criticized for being lax in those areas and
an auxiliary bishop, Donald Wuerl, was appointed to take over those
duties.
   When that situation proved unworkable, Hunthausen's authority
was restored in early 1987, Wuerl was transferred, and Murphy, a
bishop in Montana, was named coadjutor. The commission was also
named to advise Hunthausen.
   The commission met with Hunthausen five times, most recently in
October.
   Tuesday's announcement was praised by Sister Kathleen Pruitt, an
outspoken supporter of Hunthausen, and the director of mission and
outreach for the Sisters of St. Joseph of Peace.
   She said Hunthausen has not significantly changed his leadership
since the Vatican investigation.
   ``I'm sure some things have changed, not major things,'' said
Margaret Hoffman, director of the Sons of St. Peter Coalition, a
conservative group critical of the archbishop's leadership.
   Ms. Hoffman said liturgical abuses still occur in the
archdiocese and cited Hunthausen washing a woman's feet last month
in a Holy Week ritual. She said church teachings forbid washing a
woman's feet in the manner reminiscent of Jesus washing his
disciples' feet.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
