<FILEID>AP-NR-04-13-89 0000EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s w BC-Abortion-Bush Adv16   04-13 0914</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Abortion-Bush, Adv 16,0937</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv16</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, April 16, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Bush Acknowledges Evolving Position on Abortion</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush freely admits he has varied his
position on abortion over the years, leading up to his outright
call for repeal of the landmark Supreme Court decision legalizing
the procedure.
   But even in the steadily ``evolving'' position that Bush
describes, the president would still permit three exceptions to a
ban, allowing an abortion to save a mother's life and in cases of
rape and incest.
   As the Supreme Court prepares to hear arguments April 26 in a
Missouri case that could lead to the reversal _ or substantial
weakening _ of the 1973 Roe vs. Wade decision, Bush's position is
clear. He wants the decision reversed, thinks the issue ought to be
returned to the states and favors a pro-life constitutional
amendment.
   His position wasn't always so clear.
   In the 1980 presidential campaign, Bush said he would accept
abortion to save the mother's life and in cases of rape and incest.
But when Ronald Reagan picked him as a running mate, Bush sought to
minimize the differences they had on the issue. Reagan has
steadfastly opposed abortion except to save the life of the mother.
   ``Please do not keep reminding me of the differences we had,''
he told reporters at a news conference he and Reagan had after
accepting the nomination.
   Seven years later, when he started campaigning for the 1988
Republican presidential nomination, Bush talked anew of the three
instances in which he would accept abortion.
   Asked at a town meeting in Iowa to state his position, Bush said
succinctly: ``Oppose abortion. Oppose federal funding for abortion.
Want to see Roe vs. Wade changed so it won't legalize abortion.''
   During the general election campaign, he seldom broached the
volatile issue, and when asked about it, Bush often would say
tersely, ``I'm for adoption, not abortion.''
   But he got caught up in the issue again during a debate last
September with Democratic opponent Michael Dukakis at Wake Forest
University.
   Asked by a panelist what penalties he would propose for those
who continued to have abortions in a post-Roe-vs.-Wade scenario,
Bush advocated criminal penalties for women who terminate a
pregnancy.
   Then-campaign director James A. Baker III, now the secretary of
state, called reporters the next morning to tell them that Bush had
thought through the issue further.
   What Bush meant to say, Baker explained, was that women who have
abortions are ``additional victims'' and that any sanctions ought
to be brought against those who perform abortions.
   Bush has acknowledged that his position on the issue has been
``evolving'' over the years. He is known to have been deeply
affected, for instance, when his son Marvin and Marvin's wife,
Margaret, adopted a little girl. ``I thank God that her parents
chose life,'' Bush has said of his granddaughter.
   Three days after his inauguration, Bush told an anti-abortion
rally via a telephone hookup that abortion is ``our national
tragedy,'' and he spoke forcefully in favor of ending abortion on
demand.
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater was asked to explain how
Bush could reconcile his acceptance of three circumstances for
abortion with his support for reversing the landmark Supreme Court
decision.
   Asked what relief Bush would suggest for a woman whose case fit
one of the three categories but who lived in a state that outlawed
all abortions in a post-Roe-vs.-Wade world, Fitzwater replied,
``Well, he believes that Roe vs. Wade should be reversed and that
the states have responsibilities or rights to pass their own laws
regarding this matter.
   ``And he simply makes his views known on the issues, and the
states are free to follow that or not,'' the press secretary said.
   Nancy Broff, legislative director of the National Abortion
Rights Action League, said Bush's position is tantamount to letting
women fend for themselves.
   ``What would he say to the women who are on Medicaid, who are
brutalized by rape or incest, who currently can't get funding to
pay for abortions?'' she asked. ``I think what he's saying is that
if he were the one making the rules, he'd allow abortions under
three circumstances. But what he's saying is that he'd rather allow
7,416 state legislators to make this decision for women.''
   David O'Steen, executive director of the National Right to Life
Committee, said he's ``comfortable'' with Bush's position, even if
Bush has changed his statements over the years.
   ``Neither I as a person nor the Right to Life Committee as an
organization feels there has been any wavering in his position,''
O'Steen said. ``After all, about 98 percent of abortions are not
performed to save the life of the mother or for rape or incest.''
   O'Steen acknowledged, however, that his organization's ``ideal''
abortion premise is one that more closely matches former President
Reagan's position _ permitting the procedure only to save the life
of a mother.
   Diane Wood, a University of Chicago Law School professor, said
one of the complications of the Missouri case before the Supreme
Court is that ``overruling Roe vs. Wade could rest on a
constitutional theory that there is nothing in the Constitution
which expressly permits it,'' so therefore it should be left to the
states.
   ``One position the president might want to take is to urge the
states to enact legislation (in a post-Roe-vs.-Wade situation)
recognizing the three exceptions that he would allow,'' she said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sun April 16</NOTE>
</DOC>
