<FILEID>AP-NR-04-13-89 0226EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights     04-13 0755</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Highlights,0790</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Peter V. Ueberroth's proposed $464 million
purchase of strikebound Eastern Airlines collapsed over an impasse
with its unions and parent Texas Air Corp., the former baseball
commissioner said.
   His announcement Wednesday squelched a stunning but short-lived
effort to buy one of the nation's most strife-ridden airlines,
which has been mired in an emotional strike and bankruptcy
proceedings for more than a month.
   Eastern President Phil Bakes said the Miami-based airline's
strategy now was to reorganize as a smaller carrier serving roughly
50 percent to 60 percent of its pre-strike schedule of 1,040
flights a day and employing some 15,000 to 18,000 people, compared
with 31,000 before the strike.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   SmithKline Beckman Corp. and Britain's
Beecham Group PLC announced they would merge and form the world's
second-largest pharmaceutical company, but a Wall Street analyst
warned that either firm could find itself a takeover target before
the transaction is completed.
   SmithKline and Beecham, which confirmed earlier this month they
were negotiating on a merger, said Wednesday they would exchange
stock and establish a pharmaceutical and health care giant with
estimated sales of $6.7 billion.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ivan F. Boesky asked a federal judge to end his
three-year prison term but prosecutors refused to take a stand on
releasing the formr speculator at the center of Wall Street's
insider trading scandals.
   Boesky, who has served one year in prison, claimed Wednesday
that his help led to a record plea bargain deal by Drexel Burnham
Lambert Inc. and the subsequent indictment of its chief junk bond
financier, Michael Milken, and others on racketeering and
securities fraud charges.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PALO ALTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hewlett-Packard Co. moved to seize
leadership in the $4 billion computer workstation market,
announcing an agreement to buy Apollo Computer Inc. for $476
million in cash.
   Hewlett-Packard's surprise announcement Wednesday stole some
thunder from rival Sun Microsystems Inc., which announced what it
called the most significant new products in its history.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SHANNON, Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   GPA Group Ltd., one of the world's
largest aircraft leasing companies, said it will announce the
largest aircraft order in history next week, saying it plans to
order airplanes and engines worth $11 billion to $20 billion.
   The Ireland-based company's chief operating officer, James M.
King, said Wednesday he is ordering a mix of airplane models
manufactured by Boeing Co., McDonnell Douglas Corp. and Airbus
Industrie, the European joint venture aircraft maker.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Carlyle Group continued its pursuit of
Fairchild Industries Inc., sweetening its offer for the aerospace
electronics company to $243.7 million.
   Wednesday's move was the second time Carlyle has raised its
offer for Fairchild, which has rejected the investment
partnership's previous bids.
   Fairchild Secretary John Jackson said the bid was being
evaluated.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cable television executives faced a buzz saw
from congressional, broadcast and consumer critics who said cable
companies are reaping billions of dollars in profits at public
expense.
   Sen. Howard Metzenbaum, D-Ohio, led the attack Wednesday at a
congressional hearing, saying cable rates have risen an average of
32 percent nationally since Congress lifted virtually all
regulations on cable operators in 1984.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Communications Commission said it
would consider whether there is enough competition in the
long-distance market to give the American Telephone &amp; Telegraph Co.
more latitude in pricing.
   A decision to unleash AT&amp;T, if it came, would be a major change
in federal regulation of the telephone industry. The FCC statement
came Wednesday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mexico's latest $3.65 billion loan from the
International Monetary Fund will likely improve its standing in
upcoming debt restructuring talks with commercial bank creditors,
bank executives said.
   The executives comments on Wednesday came as negotiations
between the country and a 13-member bank committee are set to begin
April 19 in New York. The Mexican agreement with the IMF was
announced Tuesday.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market rose again Wednesday, as the Dow Jones average
of 30 industrials rose 8.07 to 2,319.65, adding to its 9.71-point
gain on Tuesday.
   Government and corporate bond prices finished little changed to
slightly lower in sluggish dealings, while municipal bond prices
edged up.
   The dollar ended mixed against major currencies in U.S. trading
after increasing slightly abroad.
   Palladium futures prices surged and other precious-metal futures
prices advanced; cocoa futures plunged; gasoline prices rose but
other energy futures were mixed; grains and soybeans were mostly
higher; and livestock and meat futures were mixed.
</TEXT>
