<FILEID>AP-NR-04-13-89 0343EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Woolworth     04-13 0470</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Woolworth,0488</SECOND>
<HEAD>Retailer's Board Approves New Holding Company</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   F.W. Woolworth Co.'s board of directors has
approved a new corporate structure that the giant retailer said was
aimed at making itself more responsive to business opportunities.
   Under the plan, which must be approved by stockholders,
Woolworth would become a wholly owned subsidiary of a new holding
entity called Woolworth Corp.
   ``The company believes the new holding company arrangement would
more accurately reflect the company's current management
structure,'' Woolworth said Wednesday in a statement.
   ``Additionally, it would increase organizational, operational
and financial flexibility, and allow Woolworth Corp. to more
effectively take advantage of future business opportunities,'' the
company stated.
   The company did not elaborate on why the board took the action
or what future business opportunities might be contemplated.
Woolworth spokeman J.F. Carroll said the company would confine its
comments to the written announcement.
   The plan, to be presented to stockholders at an annual meeting
in Universal City, Calif., on June 22, calls for outstanding shares
of Woolworth's common and series A preferred stock to be
automatically exchanged for equal holdings of the new Woolworth
Corp., which would be based in New York.
   Retail industry analysts said they were unable to determine the
significance of Woolworth's move given that the new arrangement
apparently would not alter the company's ownership in any
meaningful way.
   Woolworth's shares closed at $51.50 in New York Stock Exchange
consolidated trading, up $1.50.
   Woolworth said that if the plan is approved, each share in
Woolworth Corp. would ``represent the same interest in the same
business and assets, operated under the same management, as did a
share of the company immediately prior to the share exchange.''
   To bolster their abilities to defend themselves against unwanted
takeover attempts, numerous companies have realigned their
corporate structures, some adopting employee stock owernship plans
(ESOPs) to place a bigger portion of their shares in friendly hands.
   Last year, Woolworth attracted the interest of the corporate
raiding Haft family.
   A partnership controlled by Dart Group Corp.'s Chairman Herbert
Haft last spring disclosed plans to acquire $15 million or more of
the retailer's stock.
   Haft and his son Robert have become known as corporate raiders
because on repeated occasions they have purchased stakes in
companies, made unsuccessful takeover bids and then profited by
selling their stock when the companies have repurchased the shares
or gone private in buyouts.
   Several analysts said they were unaware of any renewed takeover
interest in Woolworth lately nor have they heard speculation about
what Woolworth might be intending to do, if anything.
   Woolworth's, which started as an owner of five-and-dime stores
and has expanded into specialty areas such as sportswear, had
revenue of more than $8 billion in 1988 and operated more than
7,700 stores in the United States, Canada, West Germany and
Australia.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890413-0246 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-13-89 0331EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Texaco Bjt   04-13 0633</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Texaco, Bjt,0654</SECOND>
<HEAD>Texaco Optimistic Of Its Prospects A Year After Leaving Bankruptcy
Court</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JULIA C. MARTINEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Whether Texaco Inc. can keep its promises to
become a more competitive, more profitable company remains to be
seen, but the oil giant is definitely headed in the right
direction, industry analysts say.
   Since last April, the nation's third-largest oil company reduced
its debt dramatically, raised $7 billion in cash from asset sales
and set a new business course that President James W. Kinnear hopes
will make Texaco ``one of the industry's most admired, competitive
and profitable companies.''
   At a meeting with industry analysts today, Texaco, which is
rivaled in size only by Exxon Corp. and Mobil Corp., is expected to
present itself as a proudly reorganized, more profitable company
ready to meet the competition of the 1990s.
   ``The story is an attractive one to see,'' said Michael Young,
an analyst with Smith Barney, Harris Upham &amp; Co.
   Analysts say management should take the credit for the company's
turnaround.
   ``They've done a remarkably good job when you look at the events
that have transpired,'' said Young.
   Frank P. Knuettel, an analyst with Prudential-Bache Securities
Inc., said last year's skeptics have become this year's believers
after watching Texaco exceed its initial asset sale plans.
   ``Now they're thinking, `Maybe this management does have this
situation in grasp.' And I believe it does,'' Knuettel said.
   But the company, which has shifted its primary focus from
refining oil to exploration and production, still must make a big
oil find and continue to prepare for crude price volatility.
   ``The tests of its promises are still coming up,'' said Stephen
Smith of Bear Stearns &amp; Co. ``It won't be decided in a year.''
   In April 1987, Texaco filed for protection from creditors under
Chapter 11 of the federal bankruptcy laws to avoid having to post a
potentially ruinous multibillion-dollar security bond in its fight
with Pennzoil Co.
   Pennzoil had sued Texaco, claiming Texaco's 1984 acquisition of
Getty Oil Co. interfered with Pennzoil's prior contract to buy part
of reserve-rich Getty. In 1985, a Houston jury awarded Pennzoil a
$10.3 billion judgment. Texaco appealed the judgment but eventually
settled with Pennzoil for $3 billion amid heavy shareholder
pressure to do so.
   Carl C. Icahn, Texaco's largest shareholder, began pressuring
the company into boosting its stock value largely through the sale
of assets after Texaco's board rejected his proposal to buy Texaco
for $60 a share. Last year, Icahn narrowly lost a proxy fight for
control of Texaco's board.
   Even before the bankruptcy, Texaco had begun a major
restructuring. But Icahn's overtures led to Texaco selling $7
billion in assets, including its lucrative Canadian subsidiary,
Texas Canada Inc., rather than the $5 billion originally planned.
   Texaco also agreed to pay two special dividends consisting of
cash and preferred stock with a total value of $8 per share, or
approximately $1.95 billion. In addition, the company plans to buy
back $500 million in common stock before August 1990.
   Icahn, who owns 17 percent of Texaco, agreed in return not to
buy any more Texaco stock for seven years.
   Many analysts say Texaco's stock price, which has hovered in the
$53 range, reflects its full value, but that could change if Icahn
decides to sell his share.
   Last year, Texaco turned a profit of $1.3 billion, or $5.35 a
share, compared with a 1987 loss of $4.14 billion, but that could
dramatically improve in 1989.
   Texaco still plans to sell about $300 million more in what it
considers marginal properties.
   Last week, it further reduced refining interests by announcing a
joint venture with Sweden's OK Petroleum AB that included the sale
of its 43 percent interest in a Swedish refinery along with its
depots and marketing interests.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
