<HEAD>Eastern Frequent Flier Asking Court to Block Shuttle Sale</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Eastern, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Atlanta attorney Moreton Rolleston Jr., a
frequent passenger on embattled Eastern Airlines, filed a petition
with the U.S. Bankruptcy Court that was used as the basis for the
judge's order in the case Wednesday.
   Referring to Rolleston's petition, U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Burton
R. Lifland ordered the parties involved in Eastern's Chapter 11
reorganization to show why he should not throw the airline open to
all biddersw _ and include ith it certain assets parent Texas Air
Corp. has bought or transferred from Eastern since acquiring it in
1986.
   Among other things, Rolleston's petition seeks to block the sale
of Eastern's Northeast shuttle for $365 million to developer Donald
Trump.
   Rolleston, 71, who handles litigation in cases involving real
estate and other areas, is a member of Eastern's frequent flier
program who says he has flown 600,000 miles on the airline since
1955.
   ``Nobody so far has taken any interest in what the public needs
except the judge (Lifland),'' Rolleston said late Wednesday in a
telephone interview from his home. ``I think something ought to be
done as soon as possible to get that airline flying.''
   Lifland has said on several occasions that it is in the public's
interest to return Eastern to a full schedule of flights quickly.
