<FIRST>r f PM-Eastern-DiamondDealer     04-13 0520</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Eastern-Diamond Dealer,0538</SECOND>
<HEAD>Diamond Dealer Says He's Readying Bid for Eastern</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Eastern, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Manhattan diamond dealer says he has formed a
partnership with an unidentified foreign airline that he said could
raise more than $250 million by the end of the week for a bid for
Eastern Airlines.
   Willy Censor, 62, said Wednesday he had met with officials from
Eastern and U.S. Bankruptcy Court to discuss his proposal for
buying the strikebound carrier. Eastern attorney David Boies
confirmed he met with Censor but declined to say whether the
airline was taking the bid seriously.
   A $464 million proposal from a group headed by former baseball
commissioner Peter V. Ueberroth collapsed Wednesday over a reported
union demand that an interim trustee run the airline during
bankruptcy proceedings.
   Censor owns O. Censor and Co., founded by his father in Antwerp,
Belgium, in 1917 and now located in Manhattan's diamond district.
He said he has owned stock in airlines.
   ``I am interested in airlines, in any business that can make
money,'' Censor said in an interview in U.S. Bankruptcy Court.
   He declined to name the overseas airline with which he said he
had formed a a partnership, but said, ``They have all the expertise
I need.''
   ``He told me he's been dreaming about owning an airline since he
came to America in 1946,'' said Judah Dick, Censor's attorney.
   ``All I can tell you is he has some connection with some
overseas airline that has apparently taken an interest in buying
out Eastern,'' Dick said. ``He's going to finance it because the
airline doesn't have the wherewithal to finance it.''
   Censor said he met with U.S. Trustee Harold Jones on Friday to
discuss the bid. He said Jones told him to submit a proposal to
David Shapiro, the court-appointed examiner overseeing part of
Eastern's bankruptcy proceedings. Jones and Shapiro were
unavailable for comment.
   Censor said he sent a telegram on Friday to Shapiro outlining
his interest in the deal and unsuccessfully tried to contact
Ueberroth and Frank Lorenzo, chairman of Eastern parent Texas Air.
Corp.
   ``My group is now in a position to obtain within one week from
today commitments from appropriate banks and from my own resources
of in excess of $250 million for the purchase of control of Eastern
Airlines,'' the cable read.
   ``Moreover, I can provide such further financing thereafter as
would be required to assure the airline's viability without
recourse to the Eastern shuttle.
   ``I am confident that retaining the Eastern shuttle will assure
more success with the Machinists than Mr. Ueberroth will have
because as they well know, the shuttle is at the heart of any
profitability which Eastern may have and is the key to its future
viability.''
   Eastern sought federal bankruptcy court protection from
creditors on March 9, five days after its Machinists union went on
strike and was joined by its pilots and flight attendants,
virtually shutting the carrier down.
   Eastern has agreed to sell its prized Northeast shuttle to
developer Donald Trump for $365 million, a deal pending approval in
bankruptcy court.
</TEXT>
