<FILEID>AP-NR-04-13-89 0359EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Mexico-Debt Bjt   04-13 0658</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mexico-Debt, Bjt,0680</SECOND>
<HEAD>IMF Deal Done, Mexico Faces Tough Bank Talks on Debt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ANDERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mexico will be ``firm but very cautious'' in
debt talks next week with its commercial bank creditors now that it
has in hand a $3.65 billion loan from the International Monetary
Fund, top Mexican officials said Wednesday.
   U.S. Treasury Secretary Nicholas Brady's Third World debt
reduction plan speeded negotiation of the loan, the officials told
reporters at a background briefing.
   ``We got what we wanted,'' said one of the officials, speaking
on condition of anonymity.
   Mexico also will ask banks to reschedule about $2 billion in
amortization of principal that come due this year, they said.
   President Carlos Salinas de Gortari wants to reduce the burden
of Mexico's $107 billion foreign debt and keep more money inside
the country for economic investment. Mexico is the developing
world's second-largest debtor behind Brazil, which owes $121
billion.
   Mexicans have seen their standard of living decline by half over
the last seven years, and Salinas is under political and social
pressure to reverse that course and renew growth.
   The three-year agreement reached Tuesday with the IMF is the
first since Brady outlined a plan last month that he hoped would
help ease payment terms on the Third World's $1.32 trillion foreign
debt.
   Getting creditor governments, banks, the IMF and the World Bank
to coordinate will take time, one Mexican official warned. But
Brady brought together proposals by leaders of industrialized and
developing nations and pushed the plan.
   ``In this sense the Brady Plan has speeded up the process,'' he
said, adding it took just 11 days of direct talks to hammer out the
IMF loan.
   The $3.65 billion loan will be used to bolster Mexico's foreign
exchange reserves and spur economic development. About one-third of
loan proceeds will be used to support Mexico's debt-reduction
proposals to the banks, the official said.
   Together with other short-term credits Mexico is seeking from
the IMF, the World Bank and other sources, Mexico will devote about
$500 million annually to debt reduction, he said.
   Treasury Secretary Pedro Aspe said Tuesday that Mexico will
offer banks the option of exchanging old debt for Mexican bonds
that discount debt principal and reduce interest rates.
   Mexico may choose to use loan proceeds to buy U.S. Treasury
bonds as collateral that the Mexican bonds will be paid, one
official said Wednesday.
   The banks need an inducement to buy the bonds, ``and this costs
money. We have to go into debt to get out of debt,'' he said.
   Issuing bonds to banks that retire part of their Mexican debt is
an attractive option to Mexico, with each dollar's worth of bond
capable of saving Mexico up to $12 in loan service costs over a
30-year period, the official said.
   Other options for bank creditors are being explored to meet
Mexico's goal of reducing its net outflow of resources to pay debt
from 6 percent to 2 percent of annual gross national product, the
officials said.
   ``We don't yet know'' how the restructuring talks will work out,
one said. ``We'll put before the banks option A, option B and
option C and use what they take.''
   Mexico also will ask banks whose Mexico amortizations come due
this year to reschedule payment, the officials said. They estimated
the amount at $2 billion, but did not say how much time they were
seeking.
   They added that implementing the Brady plan with such ideas as
creating a multinational pool of funds to support debt writeoffs
``still lack details,'' but that creditor banks are well aware of
Mexico's urgency in reaching a restructuring agreement.
   ``We have to be firm but very cautious,'' one official said.
``The urgency is obvious, but we must not allow ourselves to fall
into it. The banks are aware of this urgency.''
   Negotiations with a 13-member bank committee are set to begin
April 19 in New York.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890413-0250 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-13-89 0133EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f BC-Northwest     04-13 0407</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Northwest,0423</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report: Company Founded By Former Treasury Secretary Simon May Bid
On NWA</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY R. SANDOK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ST. PAUL (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wesray Capital Corp., a New York investment
company founded by former U.S. Treasury Secretary William Simon,
has approached a Northwest Airlines' union about a takeover bid for
the airline, according to a published report.
   Northwest union leader Bruce Retrum was quoted in Thursday's St.
Paul Pioneer Press Dispatch saying that Saunders Miller, a
Minneapolis financial consultant, contacted him within the last
week to try to set up a meeting with him, leaders of other
Northwest unions and a Wesray representative to discuss a leveraged
buyout.
   ``There were no specifics, but my assumption was that he wanted
to talk about an ESOP (employee stock ownership plan) or some
employee stock ownership,'' said Retrum, secretary-treasurer of
Teamsters Local 2747, which represents some of the airline's 6,500
flight attendants.
   The meeting was scheduled for Thursday but then postponed by
Miller, Retrum said.
   Miller declined comment, telling the newspaper, ``There is
nothing going on today that I'm aware of.''
   Wesray has participated in a number of buyouts, including the
employee purchase of Avis, but last week a spokesman for Simon said
he wasn't interested in buying Northwest.
   Meanwhile, the failure of Los Angeles billionaire Marvin Davis
to release details Wednesday of a plan to finance his proposed
$2.62 billion takeover of Northwest was viewed as a hopeful sign by
Gov. Rudy Perpich, who is fighting to keep the airline independent.
   Perpich said Davis had been expected to release details of his
plan Wednesday.
   NWA Inc. stock closed Wednesday on the New York Stock Exchange
at $90.50, up $1.50, surpassing Davis' offer of $90 a share.
   Davis, an oil mogul with interests in real estate and
entertainment, says he plans a shareholder proxy fight to win
control of the airline's board at NWA's May 15 shareholders meeting.
   Last Friday, NWA's board of directors rejected Davis' offer,
calling it inadequate. The board also reaffirmed its intention to
maintain the nation's fourth-largest airline as an independent
entity.
   Northwest, based in suburban Eagan, has asked a federal judge to
prevent Davis from negotiating with its unions, while Davis has
filed a separate lawsuit seeking to invalidate Northwest's ``poison
pill'' anti-takeover plan.
   Shortly before Davis announced his bid March 30, the airline
disclosed that another investor, whom it would not identify, holds
a 4.9 percent stake in NWA stock.
</TEXT>
