<DOCNO> AP890413-0251 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-13-89 0416EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Apollo-HewlettPackard Bjt   04-13 0662</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Apollo-Hewlett Packard, Bjt,0683</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hewlett-Packard To Buy Apollo In Move To Seize Workstation Leadership</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANTHONY MARQUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PALO ALTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hewlett-Packard Co. surpassed its
rivals in the thriving computer workstation market when it
announced a surprise agreement to buy Apollo Computer Inc.,
analysts say.
   Hewlett-Packard's $476 million cash purchase offer for Apollo, a
pioneer in the engineering workstation market, also stole some
limelight from principal rival Sun Microsystems Inc., which picked
Wednesday to unveil an entire overhaul of its high-powered
workstations line.
   ``We're pretty sure they won't be too delighted to hear this,''
said Richard Watts, director of marketing in Hewlett-Packard's
computer products sector, speculating on Sun's reaction to the
acquisition.
   The announcement Wednesday moved Hewlett-Packard into the
leadership position in the $4 billion computer workstation market.
Apollo and Hewlett-Packard together would have 30.4 percent of the
workstation market, taking the lead from Sun, which has 28.3
percent, according to Dataquest Inc., a San Jose-based research
firm.
   The workstation market is expected to grow at a 30 percent clip
through 1993, according to Alea Fairchild, an analyst with
Dataquest.
   Workstations are single-user computers that resemble personal
computers but are usually quicker, more powerful and with larger
screens and better graphics. They were originally used mostly by
scientists and engineers but are being increasingly targeted for
everyday personal and business use.
   ``It signals a real major commitment on our part to the
workstation portion of our business,'' said Watts.
   Hewlett-Packard, based in Palo Alto, said it will offer $13.12
per share for Apollo's estimated 36 million shares of common stock
outstanding and will begin its tender offer within five business
days.
   Apollo shares shot up $4.62{ to close at $12.75 in heavy
over-the-counter trading of 10 million shares. Hewlett-Packard fell
75 cents a share to $53.50 in consolidated New York Stock Exchange
trading.
   The deal requires regulatory approval and the tender of at least
51 percent of Apollo stock by shareholders. The deal should take 90
days to complete, said Watts.
   Apollo, a Fortune 500 company founded in 1980 and based in
Chelmsford, Mass., has suffered recent setbacks in the race with
Sun and lost money in two consecutive quarters last year. It
squeezed out a profit of $2.1 million for the year as a whole on
sales of $654 million.
   But Apollo Chairman and CEO Thomas A. Vanderslice said Wednesday
that the company's earnings due out next week would show ``very
strong'' results.
   Apollo will likely operate as a division within
Hewlett-Packard's workstation group once the acquisition is
completed, which should be in 90 days, said Watts.
   Vanderslice termed the transaction a ``win-win'' situation for
both companies and said he did not foresee major layoffs resulting
from the purchase.
   Hewlett-Packard said it will benefit from Apollo's strength in
computer networking and its large customer base and motivated work
force.
   Hewlett-Packard will bring its strength in the graphics area to
Apollo, which could use the help, as well as financial resources
that include $9.8 billion in revenues last year.
   ``The Hewlett-Apollo thing was pretty astonishing,'' said
Michael Murphy, a senior analyst and editor of San Francisco-based
California Technology Stock Letter. ``What Hewlett I think is doing
here is building a lot of customer relationships that they are then
going to migrate over into the Unix world.''
   Workstations run on Unix, an operating system that excels in
communications and the ability to carry out multiple tasks
simultaneously.
   The announcement came as Sun Microsystems rolled out a line of
computers that boast sophisticated new graphics and digital sound,
plus higher speeds and a circuit board that allows full-motion
video on a computer screen, useful for teleconferencing. It also
launched a family of Sun-3 workstations.
   ``I think that maybe is purely coincidental but it is
interesting timing,'' said Barry F. Bosak, an analyst with New
York-based Smith Barney, Harris Upham &amp; Co.
   Hewlett-Packard had 16.9 percent of the 1987-88 market share for
workstations and Apollo had 13.5 percent, Dataquest said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
