<FIRST>r f BC-USXProfit-Sharing     04-13 0275</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-USX Profit-Sharing,0285</SECOND>
<HEAD>USX To Hand Out Profit-Sharing Checks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   USX Corp., which more than tripled its
earnings in 1988 largely because of the strong performance of its
steel division, will distribute $71 million in profit-sharing to
20,500 steelworkers this week.
   The average payment will be $3,500 and must be mailed by April
15 under the company's contract with the United Steelworkers of
America. Payments equal 10.6 percent of employees' 1988 earnings,
or $1.70 for every hour worked.
   ``Not bad,'' said Charles J. Grese, president of USW Local 1557
at USX's Clairton Works, who noted that the payment still is less
than 1988 concessions valued at $2.12 per hour by the union.
   Steel contributed an operating profit of $501 million to the
corporation in 1988, helping Pittsburgh-based USX earn a total of
$756 million, or $2.62 a share, on revenues of $16.9 billion.
   This year's payment is the second for the company's USW workers.
Last year, they received $28 million, or 90 cents an hour, for
1987. That equaled about $1,700 for each worker.
   About 18,000 LTV Steel Co. workers will share $100 million in
profit-sharing checks also are due to be mailed this week, company
spokesman Mark Tomasch said.
   LTV workers will receive about $1.80 for every hour worked in
1988, or $3,744 based on a normal work year of 2,080 hours
excluding overtime, plus stock valued at 70 cents an hour.
   Bethlehem Steel Corp. distributed profit-sharing payments on
March 31 averaging $3,500 for each of 24,000 salaried and hourly
employees represented by the steelworkers and other unions.
   National Steel Corp., based in Pittsburgh, issued profit-sharing
checks last month averaging $1,835.
</TEXT>
