<FIRST>u f PM-Dollar-Gold     04-13 0372</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold,0387</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Down, Gold Little Changed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar fell in active European trading late
this morning. Gold prices were little changed.
   Currency dealers attributed the drop to rumors of the
appointment of a new West German finance minister who reportedly
wants to reduce or even eliminate a controversial 10 percent
withholding tax on interest income.
   They said that while the dollar is losing ground against most
major currencies, active buying of Deutsche marks is moving the
market.
   The dealers were referring to media speculation that West German
Chancellor Helmut Kohl will name Theo Waigel, head of the
conservative Christian Social Union, to replace Finance Minister
Gerhard Stoltenberg.
   They said Waigel has made the repeal or modification of the
withholding tax on interest income a condition for taking the post.
The tax, instituted Jan. 1, has led to a large outflow of capital
from West Germany since and has weakened the mark's exchange rate.
   ``Most people I talked to think (the rumors of the tax repeal)
are nonsense, but you can't exclude anything,'' said one dealer at
a large West German bank in Frankfurt. ``There is nothing going on,
so people jump on small things like that.''
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day
begins, the dollar slipped 0.05 yen to a closing 132.80. Later, in
London, it was quoted at 132.55 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Wednesday's
prices, included: 1.8702 West German marks, down from 1.88575;
1.6565 Swiss francs, down from 1.6645; 6.3330 French francs, down
from 6.3690; 2.1110 Dutch guilders, down from 2.1270; 1,374.80
Italian lire, down from 1,381.00; and 1.1880 Canadian dollars, down
from 1.18875.
   In London, one British pound cost $1.6994, slightly more
expensive for buyers than late Wednesday's $1.6925.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $387.75 a troy ounce, up
from $387.25 bid late Wednesday. At midmorning, the city's five
major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $387.80.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $387.65, up from $387.30 bid late
Wednesday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose $2.09 to close at a bid $388.46.
   Silver was quoted in London at a bid price of $5.88 a troy
ounce, little changed from Wednesday's $5.89.
</TEXT>
