<FIRST>u f PM-Japan-Markets     04-13 0290</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0303</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Edges Up Against Yen, Share Prices Rise A Bit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar edged up today against the Japanese
yen for the third consecutive day, while share prices on the Tokyo
Stock Exchange gained marginally.
   The dollar closed at 132.85 yen, up 0.23 yen from Tuesday's
132.62-yen closing. It opened at 132.68 yen and ranged from 132.60
yen to 132.88 yen. The dollar now has gained 0.77 yen in three
trading days.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average,
a 250.56-point gainer the previous day, inched up another 6.87
points, or 0.02 percent, closing at 33,256.45.
   Selling to take profits in the afternoon erased most of the
Nikkei's gain in morning trading, dealers said.
   ``The index started to weaken at midmorning, mainly because
there was no market-affecting news to encourage buying today,''
said Satoru Nagayoshi of New Japan Securities Co.
   He said investors were hesitant to buy certain shares until
after they have seen major U.S. economic indicators, including the
nation's trade figures for February, due to be announced Friday in
Washington.
   Volume traded on the first section was estimated at 1 billion
shares, down from Tuesday's 1.1 billion. Among the gainers were
machinery and construction issues.
   In currency dealings, participants also generally remained on
the sidelines awaiting Friday's U.S. trade and wholesale price
index figures, said Ichiro Ikeda of Chemical Bank in Tokyo.
   The U.S. currency edged up shortly before the end of trading due
to position adjustments, he added.
   ``Also, yen-selling to buy West German marks contributed to the
dollar's rise against the yen,'' Ikeda said.
   ``But investors' dollar-buying incentives won't be strong enough
to push the currency beyond the 133-yen level before the weekend at
least,'' he said.
</TEXT>
