<FIRST>r f PM-EasternRebuilding     04-13 0637</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Eastern Rebuilding,0656</SECOND>
<HEAD>Management Employees To Work Out Plans For New Eastern</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Eastern Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastern Airlines' skeleton management staff can now
put aside, at least temporarily, worries about a change in
ownership and focus on rebuilding the faltering airline, says a
company spokesman.
   Officials announced Wednesday that a proposed $464 million offer
to buy the carrier from a group led by Peter V. Ueberroth had
fallen through.
   ``It's really been a roller coaster,'' spokesman Robin Matell
said Wednesday. ``It's really been impossible to concentrate on a
plan as such.''
   Eastern President Phil Bakes, in announcing the end of the
buyout effort by former baseball commissioner Ueberroth, said the
company envisions a gradual rebuilding to an efficient carrier with
about 18,000 employees and 130 to 150 jetliners flying to 60 to 80
cities.
   ``We are going to continue to bring in new recruits and continue
to build our system,'' Bakes said in New York. ``We are hopeful we
will be afforded the opportunity to accelerate and work on that
task.''
   Matell said it was premature to discuss how Eastern, flying only
10 percent of its schedule since its unions walked out March 4,
will get back to 50 to 60 percent of its old schedule of 1,040
flights daily.
   Eastern employed 40,000 people when Texas Air Corp. Chairman
Frank Lorenzo bought the company in 1986, a number that dwindled to
30,000 before the strike.
   Union leaders, however, doubt that Eastern's management can
overcome negative publicity, some $2.5 billion in debt, a recent
history of steady losses and the need to find qualified workers to
replace strikers.
   ``The airlines is in a spin. It's almost hit the ground and
they're still telling people they can pull it out,'' said Eastern
pilot Ed Potter, who scoffed at Bakes' promise to rebuild the
airline.
   Spokesman James Ashlock said Eastern has been quietly calling
non-union workers back, to a work force now at 4,500 from a low of
1,000 the first week of the strike. The company had 12,000
non-union employees when the strike began, and officials said they
don't know how many will be willing to return.
   Ashlock said employees who have stayed on the job had had a lot
of concerns about the Ueberroth deal, which would have given the
unions 30 percent ownership in exchange for pay and wage
concessions.
   ``It looks like we move on to another phase,'' said Ashlock. ``I
do think there is a certain release of anxiety here at the base,
where a great many people, particularly the non-contract people,
were increasingly concerned at the way the situation had been
building.''
   Eastern now has 115 or 116 flights daily after resuming service
on Bahamas and Atlanta routes this week, Ashlock said. The company
has concentrated on its most profitable routes, mainly its
Northeastern shuttle service and Latin American service, in its
strike schedule.
   Since the strike began, Eastern competitors, particularly
American Airlines, have expanded service to capitalize on Eastern's
woes, and the company acknowledges it must overcome consumer
skepticism. Discounted tickets and other lures are likely, the
company has said.
   But Eastern needs more pilots. Only 200 of 3,600 pilots have
flown since their union joined the Machinists strike.
   The company still hopes to gain a federal appellate court order
sending the pilots back to work, even though U.S. District Judge
Edward B. Davis on Wednesday reported to a appeals court that there
was no evidence to support company claims the pilots are on an
illegal strike.
   Ashlock said 34 newly recruited pilots are in the third week of
a six-week training course, 34 more are in the second week, and a
third class will begin next week.
   So far, Eastern hasn't needed to hire any new mechanics to
replace striking Machinists, Ashlock said.
</TEXT>
