<FILEID>AP-NR-04-13-89 1000EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Japan-Trade     04-13 0474</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Japan-Trade,0493</SECOND>
<HEAD>Trade Surplus Dips in March for First Time in 7 Months</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japan's trade surplus fell in March to $6.74
billion, its first decline in seven months from year-earlier
levels, the Finance Ministry announced Thursday.
   Japanese exports had exceeded imports by $7.46 billion in March
1988, and by $7.24 billion in February 1989.
   The March figure brought Japan's trade surplus for fiscal 1988,
which ended March 31, to $79.01 billion, up from $75.99 billion the
previous year and the first increase in two years.
   Exports in fiscal 1988 increased 14.7 percent to $272.94
billion, while imports rose 19.7 percent to $193.92 billion, the
ministry said.
   Ministry officials said strong overseas demand for Japanese
products throughout the fiscal year had boosted exports, especially
of semiconductors, computers, cars and business machines.
   They said imports remained brisk because of strong Japanese
domestic demand, and included increased flows of foreign
manufactured goods.
   The ministry officials said the fiscal 1988 surplus rose mainly
because of lower prices for oil, Japan's largest import commodity.
   In March, exports climbed 16.9 percent from a year earlier to
$26.55 billion, while imports surged 29.8 percent to $19.81
billion, the ministry said.
   After seasonal adjustments, the March surplus came to $5.57
billion, a sharp drop from $8.86 billion in February, the ministry
said.
   The officials said imports surged in March as companies began
importing in earnest after several months of restrained consumption
due to Emperor Hirohito's death on Jan. 7 and funeral on Feb. 24.
Importers also stepped up transactions before the end of the
Japanese fiscal year, they said.
   The trade surplus with the United States in March ballooned to
$4.13 billion from $3.40 billion a year earlier, the ministry said.
Exports grew 21.6 percent to $8.75 billion, while imports rose 22
percent to $4.62 billion.
   For the fiscal year, the trade surplus with the United States
declined slightly to $49.10 billion from $50.84 billion in fiscal
1987. Exports to the United States rose 8.4 percent to $92.60
billion, while imports grew 25.7 percent to $43.50 billion, the
ministry said.
   Japan's trade surplus with the European Economic Community in
March fell to $1.67 billion from $1.93 billion a year earlier, it
said.
   For the fiscal year, Japanese exports to the EEC exceeded
imports by $22.32 billion, up from $20.11 billion the previous
year. Exports rose 20.3 percent to $47.80 billion, while imports
expanded by 29.9 percent to $25.48 billion.
   The surplus in trade with Southeast Asia in March grew to $2.34
billion from $2.03 billion in March 1988.
   Japan's trade surplus with the region for the fiscal year rose
to $20.37 billion from $14.82 billion the previous year. Exports
rose 23.9 percent to $69.86 billion, while imports grew 19.1
percent to $49.50 billion.
   Japan includes freight and insurance costs in its import
figures, but not in its exports.
</TEXT>
