<FILEID>AP-NR-04-13-89 1028EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-WallStreet10am     04-13 0291</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wall Street 10am,0308</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market gave ground today as traders
warily awaited the latest reading on inflation.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials dropped 7.88 to 2,311.77
in the first half hour of trading.
   Losers outnumbered gainers by about 7 to 4 in nationwide trading
of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 325 up, 584 down and
563 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 21.24 million shares as of 10
a.m. on Wall Street.
   The government is due to report Friday on the producer price
index of finished goods for March, along with several other
economic statistics.
   Analysts expect the price index to show an increase of about 0.5
percent, down from 1.0 percent in both January and February.
   That would provide at least a tentative bit of evidence that a
slowing economy was reducing upward pressure on inflation and
interest rates.
   In a new bit of evidence that business activity is indeed
slackening, the Commerce Department reported that retail sales
increased a scant 0.1 percent last month, following a
downwnward-revised 0.6 percent decline in February.
   Losers among the blue chips included International Business
Machines, down | at 110{; Philip Morris, down \ at 119|; DuPont,
down { at 104[, and American Telephone &amp; Telegraph, down [ at 31[.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks fell
.39 to 167.43. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index slipped .15 to 334.08.
   On Wednesday the Dow Jones industrial average rose 8.07 to
2,319.65.
   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners nearly 4 to 3 on the
NYSE, with 804 issues up, 615 down and 539 unchanged.
   Big Board volume totaled 165.20 million shares, against 146.83
million in the previous session.
