<HEAD>Crop Futures Open Mixed In Lackluster Trading</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices were narrowly
mixed today in light, choppy trading on the Chicago Board of Trade.
   Soybean futures opened lower in reaction to Wednesday's
6-to-10-day National Weather Service forecast for normal
precipitation next week in the Midwest, then turned slightly higher
in a modest technical rebound.
   Corn futures were mixed with support stemming from signs that
the Soviet Union is seeking to buy some U.S. corn.
   Talk of Soviet buying interest also lent early support to the
wheat market, but a forecast for above-average precipitation next
week in the central and northern Great Plains limited the early
gains.
   In early trading, wheat was 1 cent lower to 1 cent higher with
the contract for delivery in May at $4.02{ a bushel; corn was {
cent lower to \ cent higher with May at $2.67} a bushel; oats were
1 cent lower to 1 cent higher with May at $1.79{ a bushel; soybeans
were 1{ cents lower to 2 cents higher with May at $7.26{ a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were mixed in early trading on the
Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were unchanged to .33 cent higher with June at 71.12
cents a pound; feeder cattle were .25 cent lower to .43 cent higher
with May at 76.15 cents a pound; hogs were .10 cent lower to .08
cent higher with June at 45.85 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies
were .40 cent lower to .10 cent higher with May at 33.25 cents a
pound.
   Cattle futures settled mostly lower on Wednesday while most pork
futures advanced.
