<FILEID>AP-NR-04-13-89 1153EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-S&amp;Ls 1stLd-Writethru   04-13 0717</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-S&amp;Ls, 1st Ld-Writethru,0737</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Bailout Plan Goes to Senate Virtually Intact</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Top 8 grafs new to UPDATE with House panel voting to allow banks
to take over S&amp;Ls immediately. Editing throughout to shorten.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A House banking subcommittee today amended
President Bush's savings and loan bailout plan to allow banks to
immediately begin buying up both insolvent and healthy thrift
institutions.
   In deference to small banks and the thrift industry, Bush had
proposed allowing banks to buy only ailing S&amp;Ls for the next two
years and healthy ones as well after that.
   But Reps. Stan Parris, R-Va., and Mary Rose Oakar, D-Ohio,
claimed support from both the administration and the Federal
Reserve for their amendment, which was approved on a voice vote by
the 47-member House Banking Committee's financial institutions
subcommittee.
   ``The one question we are repeatedly asked is what are we doing
to bring more capital into a capital-deficit industry,'' said Rep.
Doug Barnard, D-Ga. ``This is the one thing we can do.''
   Opponents expressed fears that allowing wholesale bank takeovers
of S&amp;Ls will concentrate too much market power in the banks,
decrease the amount of money available for home loans and
ultimately raise the taxpayer share of the bailout's costs.
   Rep. John LaFalce, D-N.Y., predicted that banks will buy only
healthy S&amp;Ls, saying they should at least be required to take over
an insolvent thrift for each financially sound one that they
purchase.
   ``The government is going to be stuck with every unhealthy
thrift in existence and the public's going to be stuck with
additional millions'' of dollars in paying off their depositors,
said the subcommittee's chairman, Rep. Frank Annunzio, D-Ill., who
opposed the amendment.
   While the House panel continued altering Bush's $90 billion
bailout package, the Senate Banking Committee approved it Wednesday
night after bowing to the administration on virtually every major
dispute.
   All 21 members of the panel voted Wednesday to support the
package after its chairman, Sen. Donald W. Riegle Jr., D-Mich.,
lost an 11-10 vote that would have rejected the administration's
proposal for keeping $50 billion in S&amp;L spending out of the budget
deficit.
   Riegle had sought to include the spending in the budget and
borrow the money through the Treasury. He contended that would have
saved taxpayes $4.5 billion in interest payments over 30 years,
compared with Bush's proposal to borrow the money through a new,
quasi-government agency.
   The administration vigorously opposed Riegle's plan, contending
Congress would be tempted to use it to evade deficit limits for
many other programs. Treasury Secretary Nicholas F. Brady promised
to recommend a presidential veto if Riegle's plan was adopted.
   The full Senate is scheduled to begin debate on the legislation
Monday, with a vote expected by Wednesday.
   The Senate Banking Committee also passed most of the revisions
sought by Bush to accompany the bailout and prevent a repeat of the
financial crisis.
   The key, according to the administration, is a requirement that
S&amp;L owners back their lending with more of their own capital,
beginning in June 1991. The administration would like to forbid
growth by S&amp;Ls that do not meet the capital standard, but the
committee decided to permit those institutions to grow 5 percent to
7 percent a year through lending in home mortgages.
   ``Obviously we don't like growth for undercapitalized thrifts,''
said Assistant Treasury Secretary David W. Mullins, one of the
architects of the Bush plan. ``We've learned hard lessons from it
in the past.''
   But, overall, he said the Senate capital standard was ``a good
solid approach.''
   The Senate committee also restructured the regulatory
bureaucracy along the lines suggested by the administration,
placing a once-independent S&amp;L regulatory agency under the Treasury
Department.
   However, in an administration-approved compromise, it created a
separate independent agency to oversee the lending function of the
regional Federal Home Loan Banks, which borrow money at low,
government-backed rates and lend it to individual S&amp;Ls.
   The House subcommittee voted 27-16 Wednesday to approve an
amendment by Parris that permits S&amp;Ls to continue using deposits in
subsidiaries investing in risky areas such as commercial real
estate development, fast food franchises and junk bonds.
   The House panel also adopted a measure requiring the government
to offer some of the repossessed property from failed S&amp;Ls for
housing poor people.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
