<DOCNO> AP890413-0267 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-13-89 1204EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Japan-Koito     04-13 0351</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Japan-Koito,0365</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Reported Probing Pickens Purchase of Koito Shares</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japan's Finance Ministry is investigating a
possible new technical irregularity in the purchase of 32.4 million
shares of a Japanese auto lighting company by U.S. corporate
takeover specialist T. Boone Pickens Jr., news reports said
Thursday.
   The reports said the ministry had discovered that the Azabu Auto
Group, from which Pickens bought his 20.2 percent share in Koito
Manufacturing Co., originally did not report to authorities it had
bought more than a 10 percent interest in the lighting firm.
   Failure to make such a report could be a violation of Japan's
Securities and Exchange Law.
   The news reports said the problem was discovered through
documents furnished by the Azabu Group after the ministry began a
formal inquiry last week into the sale of the shares.
   An official in the Finance Ministry's securities market division
said, ``I can't comment. We are still in the midst of our
investigation.''
   Pickens' purchase of the stock, which makes him the largest
shareholder, has been widely described as a possible ``greenmail''
or takeover attempt.
   In greenmail, a hostile corporate suitor makes his profits when
his stock is purchased at a premium by the target company or
another shareholder friendly to the firm.
   The Azabu Group, which reportedly has targeted other Japanese
companies for greenmail in the past, bought 48 million shares of
Koito in 1988. A large block of those shares was registered under
the name of T. Boone Pickens as of March 31, 1989.
   The second-largest stockholder, Toyota Motor Corp., holds 19.1
percent of Koito's stock.
   Koito said Tuesday it had temporarily suspended the name
transfer registrations for certificates for stock bought by Boone
Co., a Pickens-controlled investment firm, due to another legal
problem.
   A Koito official said Pickens' designate may have filed an
inapproriate application with the Finance Ministry regarding the
purchase by failing to state that the company was involved in the
manufacture of defense-sensitive parts. Koito, officials said, is
engaged in military-related aircraft parts production.
   A Boone Co. spokesman has said its interest in Koito is not
hostile.
</TEXT>
