<DOCNO> AP890413-0268 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-13-89 1215EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a f BC-Savings Adv17   04-13 0749</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Savings, Adv 17,0781</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv17</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Monday, April 17</HEAD>
<HEAD>Taking Stock After Tax Day</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserGraphic in AP Access under IRA</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIVIAN MARINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tax deadline time always compels some Americans
to make financial resolutions aimed at saving more of their
hard-earned bucks for a new house or their children's education.
   Despite their intentions, Uncle Sam isn't coaxing them too much,
since many incentives disappeared when Congress revamped the tax
law three years ago.
   Wall Street firms and banks, seeking new sources of money, have
been lobbying to get those tax breaks back.
   ``The trade-off hasn't worked,'' said Jeffrey M. Schaeffer,
director of research for the Securities Industry Association, a
lobby group of brokerage companies. ``The government thought if you
lowered marginal rates that would create the incentive to save and
invest.
   ``It may well be we have to think that over.''
   The Tax Reform Act of 1986 lowered the maximum individual tax
bracket to 33 percent from 50 percent, but it also eliminated many
deductions and preferential items. The changes included
restrictions on Individual Retirement Accounts and ended the
favorable treatment on capital gains and losses.
   Groups such as the American Bankers Association want the
government to restore IRA benefits so anyone can deduct annual
contributions of up to $2,000. Individuals can still make
tax-deferred contributions but only those who aren't covered by
company pension plans can take the deductions under the revised tax
code.
   The SIA has been keeping busy lately. Its officers testified
before the House Ways and Means Committee this past week that
capital gains on stocks should be taxed differently from ordinary
income. Before tax revision the maximum rate on capital gains had
been 20 percent.
   The group also is pushing for changes in the way stock dividends
are taxed, arguing that the current system imposes what amounts to
a double levy. Not only do stockholders pay taxes on dividends, the
SIA says, but corporations also are taxed since they can't deduct
these payouts from their taxable income the way they can for the
interest on bonds they issue.
   Lobbying groups and others concede that it's doubtful the tax
changes they desire will happen soon.
   ``I don't look for the government to be giving anybody any
breaks in the near future,'' said Jay Goldinger, a principal with
the Beverly Hills, Calif., investment banking firm Capital Insight
Inc. ``It's a reactionary body, not one that anticipates a
problem.''
   Some financial analysts disagree on whether IRA deductions and
preferential capital gains treatment had encouraged non-wealthy
taxpayers to sock more money away in the first place.
   ``I think that the history of tax legislation aimed at spurring
savings has so far been fruitless,'' said Edward Yardeni, chief
economist for Prudential-Bache Securities Inc., who believes that
changing demographics, not government intervention, will prompt
Americans to save more.
   ``We've had the IRAs. We've reduced the tax rates. Even
inflation has come down thanks to government policies. Yet the
savings rate continued to fall through 1987.''
   The nation's personal savings rate, which pales in comparison
with those in industrial rivals such as Japan and West Germany, has
been declining over the past 20 years after rising during the 1950s
and early '60s.
   In 1987 it hit a 40-year low of 3.2 percent of after-tax income,
then bounced back to 4.2 percent last year.
   The downward trend reflects what economists called poor personal
planning for the future, and they say it could have serious
implications for the economy. The savings rate represents billions
of dollars that can be loaned for reinvestment and business growth.
   Some analysts say big changes have to be made to get people to
save or invest more, especially for things like new homes or a
college education. The government already provides incentives for
those saving for their retirement, offering tax deductions on
things such as employee-sponsored 401k savings plans and Keogh
programs for the self-employed.
   Some groups, though, say more needs to be done to take care of
current needs. The National Association of Home Builders, for
example, would like to see a housing equivalent of IRAs, or
something that would allow the interest on savings to be
tax-deferred if earmarked for the purchase of a house.
   William Schreyer, chairman of Merrill Lynch &amp; Co., has proposed
giving IRA savers the right to withdraw money from their accounts
for home ownership, medical care or education, without having to
pay taxes on the proceeds.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Monday, April 17</NOTE>
</DOC>
