<DOCNO> AP890413-0269 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-13-89 1218EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-Budget 1stLd-Writethru   04-13 0674</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Budget, 1st Ld-Writethru,0693</SECOND>
<HEAD>Budget Deal Announcement Expected Friday</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 2 new grafs for 2nd graf pvs, Bargainers planned, with
negotiations under way</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   All signs are pointing to a formal
announcement on Friday that White House and congressional
negotiators have agreed on a fiscal 1990 budget bearing a deficit
of about $100 billion.
   Bargainers resumed their private meetings in a Capitol office
today, with the two sides hoping to give final shape to a deal on
the $1.2 trillion spending plan.
   The ranking Republican on the House Budget Committee, Rep. Bill
Frenzel of Minnesota, said the plan was to complete work on the
pact today, ``if we have to go all night.''
   The talks broke off early Wednesday evening because some of the
participants had other appointments, but one source knowledgeable
about the sessions said a final agreement could probably have been
reached had the negotiations lasted another 30 minutes.
   Another source said that House leaders have been told to expect
to go to the White House on Friday for a public announcement of a
pact.
   ``I'm very hopeful, actually optimistic that we will have an
agreement this week,'' House Majority Leader Thomas Foley, D-Wash.,
said after Thursday's meeting.
   Asked if bargainers would go to the White House today for an
announcement of a deal, Senate Budget Committee Chairman James
Sasser, D-Tenn., said, ``I think we probably will go Friday.''
   The deficit for the current fiscal year, which ends Sept. 30, is
expected to surpass $170 billion. But due largely to optimistic
economic assumptions used by the White House _ and accepted by
Congress _ budget writers say they need to find only $28 billion in
savings to chop next year's red ink to $100 billion. The
Gramm-Rudman law would trigger automatic spending cuts if the
deficit surpasses that amount by more than $10 billion.
   Some lawmakers are already acknowledging that the talks will not
produce the profound budget reductions that some legislators,
economists and others say are necessary to take a meaningful bite
out of the government's fiscal problems.
   ``I don't think anybody's expectations ought to be driven to the
point of expecting a dramatic and breathtaking announcement,'' said
Foley.
   The deal would achieve half of its savings by reducing
anticipated spending, and half by raising revenues.
   Tentative revenue agreements include nearly $6 billion by
selling federal assets, $5.6 billion from new taxes and much of the
rest from raising fees for various government services.
   President Bush pledged during last fall's campaign not to raise
taxes, and battles between him and the Democratic-controlled
Congress can be expected over where the new taxes will come from.
   Bush has favored reducing the capital gains tax, which he says
would stimulate the economy and raise revenues next year by $4.8
billion. Democrats say the proposal is a money-losing boon to the
rich.
   In the spending area, more than $7 billion would come from
slowing the rate of growth in programs that automatically provide
benefits to recipients, such as a savings of more than $2.5 billion
in the Medicare program that provides health care for the elderly.
   Accounting gimmicks are expected to provide much of the
remaining savings, such as $2 billion in savings by moving the U.S.
Postal Service ``off-budget.''
   Defense spending would be about $300 billion, approximately the
same as Bush proposed in the budget he presented to Congress in
February.
   Once an agreement is announced, Congress would have to enact a
budget resolution containing the pact's language, a process
expected to take weeks. By law, that resolution _ which does not
need the president's signature _ is supposed to be completed by
April 15. The deadline is never achieved, and there is no legal
penalty for that failure.
   Even with a resolution in place, separate bills would have to be
passed to actually enact the spending and taxing decisions reached
this week. That work will take months, and probably will not be
finished until at least the Oct. 1 start of fiscal 1990.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890413-0270 </DOCNO>
