<SECOND>BC-Dollar-Gold,0279</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Lower In Europe, Gold Higher</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: AMs planned by 5:30 p.m. EST</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar fell against the major currencies
in lively European trading Thursday. Gold prices were higher.
   Foreign exchange dealers said a West German cabinet change and
Swiss interest rate rises boosted European currencies.
   The replacement of West German Finance Minister Gerhard
Stoltenberg by Theo Waigel spurred European currencies because
Waigel opposes the 10 percent withholding tax on interest income.
   The tax has seen investment money leaving the country since it
was imposed Jan. 1.
   After the Swiss National Bank raised interest rates, the Swiss
franc became more attractive to investors and it rose sharply
against the dollar.
   In London, one British pound cost $1.7010 late Thursday, more
expensive for buyers than Wednesday's late $1.6925.
   Other late rates for the dollar in Europe compared with
Wednesday's late rates: 1.8720 West German marks, down from 1.8857;
1.6422 Swiss francs, down from 1.6645; 6.3335 French francs, down
from 6.3690; 2.1080 Dutch guilders, down from 2.1270; 1,374.00
Italian lire, down from 1,381.00; 1.1875 Canadian dollars, down
from 1.1887.
   Earlier in Tokyo, the dollar slipped to 132.80 Japanese yen from
132.85 yen on Wednesday. In London late Thursday the dollar was
trading lower at 132.35.
   In London, gold traded late at a bid price of $388.75 a troy
ounce, up from $387.25 late Wednesday. The late Zurich bid price
was $389.15, up from $387.30.
   Earlier in Hong Kong gold closed at $387.75 bid, up from $384.15.
   Silver bullion traded late in London at a bid $5.87 a troy
ounce, down from $5.89.
</TEXT>
