<DOCNO> AP890413-0281 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-13-89 1450EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f BC-AutoSales     04-13 0441</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Auto Sales,0454</SECOND>
<HEAD>Big Three Sales Rise Sharply</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Auto Sales-Table</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: AMs version planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Big Three automaker sales shot up 26.5 percent in
early April, when incentives were in full force, compared with last
year when the deals had expired, the companies said Thursday.
   General Motors Corp., Ford Motor Co. and Chrysler Corp. said
cars and light trucks sold at an average daily rate of 34,931
during the April 1-10 period this year, compared with a rate of
27,621 last year.
   Car sales soared 27.6 percent and sales of light trucks were up
24.6 percent during the period.
   Late last month, Ford and GM announced new incentive packages
featuring 2.9 percent interest on two-year loans and increased
rebates. Chrysler got into the fray April 3, going one step further
to interest-free financing on two-year loans for all of its cars.
   While incentives surely contributed to some of the early April
sales boom, some of the increase is attributable to slow sales
during the period last year. Incentives in effect during the first
quarter of 1988 expired March 31, persuading consumers planning
spring or summer purchases to make them earlier.
   March and April typically are hot car-selling months as
Americans get ready for summer vacations. But March sales were
lower than expected, giving rise to the new incentive packages.
   Car and truck sales by the Big Three so far this year were
running 6.9 percent behind last year's pace, going to a daily rate
of 33,068 vehicles, compared with 35,535 between Jan. 1 and April
10 last year.
   Ford said its car sales rocketed to a daily rate of 7,896 during
early April, up 47 percent from 5,372 the same time last year. For
the year, Ford's car sales were running at a rate 0.4 percent below
last year's.
   Sales of Ford's light trucks rose 28.2 percent for the period
but fell 3.2 percent for the year.
   Early-April car sales at GM rose 20.8 percent to a daily rate of
10,764, compared with 8,911 last year. GM's car sales for the year
through April 10 were 12.1 percent behind last year's rate.
   GM's light trucks sold in early April at a rate 25.9 percent
above last year and were down 4.2 percent for the year.
   Chrysler said its early-April car sales rose 12.4 percent to a
daily rate of 3,180, compared with a 2,830 last year. Year-to-date
sales ran 19.1 percent behind last year's rate.
   On the truck side, Chrysler's sales in early April were running
17.2 percent ahead of last year's pace, and for the year were up
2.1 percent.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890413-0282 </DOCNO>
