<SECOND>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0242</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wheat Futures Gain On Talk Of Soviet Interest</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wheat futures prices closed moderately higher
Thursday on the Chicago Board of Trade amid persistent rumors that
the Soviet Union had purchased a large quantity of U.S. wheat for
near-term delivery.
   Oat futures advanced in a rebound from the previous session's
losses while other grain and soybean futures finished narrowly
mixed.
   Similar rumors of wheat-buying by the Soviets had swept through
the market on Wednesday, causing prices to rise. But prices slipped
in early trading Thursday following a National Weather Service
forecast for rain next week in some key winter-wheat growing areas
of the United States.
   Talk of a Soviet wheat purchase surfaced again Thursday
afternoon. Traders bid up the price of wheat for May delivery, but
the buying interest in contracts for later deliveries of wheat was
more restrained.
   The National Weather Service's prediction for normal
precipiation in most of the Midwest last week weighed on corn and
soybean prices.
   At the close, wheat was unchanged to 6 cents higher with the
contract for delivery in May at $4.09 a bushel; corn was 1} cents
lower to } cent higher with May at $2.68{ a bushel; oats were 2{
cents to 5 cents higher with May at $1.84 a bushel; soybeans were 2
cents lower to { cent higher with May at $7.27 a bushel.
