<DOCNO> AP890413-0287 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-13-89 1605EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Eastern-Rebuilding     04-13 0738</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eastern-Rebuilding,0766</SECOND>
<HEAD>Skepticism Greets Eastern Comeback Pledge Following Ueberroth Downfall</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Eastern Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastern Airlines management's claims that the
debt-ridden company can return from bankruptcy as a significant
carrier without a new owner or its striking unions met with
skepticism Thursday from labor leaders and some analysts.
   Company officials say their goal is to rebuild Eastern as a
smaller, more efficient carrier, but some analysts say that might
not satisfy the airline's creditors and a sale still might be the
only alternative.
   Eastern President Phil Bakes, announcing the collapse of a $464
million buyout proposal by former baseball commissioner Peter V.
Ueberroth, said Wednesday the company envisions gradually
rebuilding to a carrier with about 18,000 employees and 130 to 150
jetliners flying to 60 to 80 cities.
   That would be down from a pre-strike workforce of 30,000 flying
250 planes to 110 cities but larger than its present 4,500
employees and flight schedule amounting to 10 percent of pre-strike
operations.
   ``We are going to continue to bring in new recruits and continue
to build our system,'' said Bakes.
   A March 4 strike by Eastern's Machinists, joined by its pilots
and flight attendants, virtually grounded the airline and forced it
to seek bankruptcy court protection from creditors while it
attempts to resolve its problems.
   Union leaders scoffed at Bakes' statement that Eastern could
bring in enough recruits to replace its strikers.
   Analysts said negative publicity over the strike _ which already
has cost Eastern some future customers _ and proposed restructuring
plans may hinder Eastern's chances of climbing out from $2.5
billion in debts and a decade of nearly steady losses.
   A smaller airline couldn't generate enough revenues to satisfy
creditors, they said. Either new ownership or a liquidation sale of
Eastern's assets are more realistic, some analysts said.
   ``Creditors face reduced risk in a liquidation,'' said Robert
Decker, airline analyst at Duff &amp; Phelps. ``If Eastern is brought
back to life, creditors continue to face the risk of their
investment.''
   Wally Haber, a general chairman for the Machinists union,
claimed Thursday that a decline in passenger traffic last month at
Eastern's sister carrier, Houston-based Continental Airlines,
indicated consumer distrust of Frank Lorenzo, chairman of parent
Texas Air Corp.
   Although Continental added flights on Eastern routes during the
strike's first month, its revenue passenger miles fell 4.3 percent
from March 1988. Continental traffic was down 7.4 percent in the
first three months of this year compared to 1988.
   ``The people aren't flocking to Continental because of the
public image Mr. Lorenzo has made for himself,'' Haber contended.
   Lorenzo got Continental's union contracts abrogated in 1983 and
brought the carrier out of Chapter 11 reorganization as a major
carrier.
   But Haber said a rebuilding Eastern would face an industrywide
shortage of pilots and mechanics that didn't exist six years ago.
Eastern could subcontract Machinists' work and apparently has done
so with some foreign companies, Haber said.
   ``But I don't know where Mr. Bakes is going to get his pilots,''
Haber said.
   Eastern spokesman Robin Matell said it was ``very premature'' to
discuss rebuilding plans.
   Eastern says it has been recalling non-union workers and had
rebuilt its workforce to 4,500 from a low of 1,000 during the first
week of the strike. The company had 12,000 non-union employees when
the strike began and officials said they don't know how many will
be willing to return.
   Eastern has 115 or 116 flights daily after resuming service on
Bahamas and Atlanta routes this week, spokesman James Ashlock said.
The company has concentrated on its most profitable routes, mainly
its Northeastern shuttle service and Latin American service, in its
strike schedule.
   The airline has agreed to sell the shuttle to developer Donald
Trump for $365 million.
   Only 200 of 3,600 pilots have flown since their union joined the
Machinists strike.
   The company still hopes to gain a federal appellate court order
sending the pilots back to work, even though U.S. District Judge
Edward B. Davis on Wednesday reported to a appeals court that there
was no evidence to support company claims the pilots are on an
illegal strike.
   Ashlock said 34 newly recruited pilots are in the third week of
a six-week training course, 34 more are in the second week, and a
third class would begin next week.
   So far, Eastern hasn't had to hire any mechanics to replace
striking Machinists, Ashlock said.
</TEXT>
