<FIRST>u f AM-MoneyFunds     04-13 0366</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Money Funds,0377</SECOND>
<HEAD>Money Funds Rose $1.33 Billion in Latest Week</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Interest rate figures reported by Donoghue's Money Fund Report
are for week ended Tuesday. All other figures are for the week ended Wednesday.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Assets of the nation's 464 money market mutual
funds rose $1.33 billion in the latest week, the Investment Company
Institute said Thursday.
   The rise, to $302.51 billion in the seven-day period ended
Wednesday, followed a $1.16 billion increase in the funds' assets
the previous week, according to the Washington-based mutual fund
trade group.
   The increase, from the previous record of $301.2 billion set
last week, marked the 14th straight weekly all-time high for the
funds' assets and reflected the growing attraction of such
investments due to rising interest rates.
   The Investment Company Institute said that in the latest week,
assets of 231 general purpose funds rose $977.5 million to $99.60
billion, assets of 94 broker-dealer funds increased $464.5 million
to $129.86 billion, and assets of 139 institutional funds declined
$111.4 million to $73.06 billion.
   The seven-day average yield on money market mutual funds rose in
the week ended Tuesday to 9.14 percent from 9.08 percent the
previous week, according to Donoghue's Money Fund Report, a trade
journal based in Holliston, Mass.
   The 30-day average yield rose to 9.04 percent from 8.97 percent,
Donoghue's said.
   The average maturity of the portfolios held by money funds was
32 days, up from 31 days, Donoghue's said.
   Separately, the newsletter Bank Rate Monitor said its survey of
100 leading commercial banks, savings and loan assocations and
savings banks in the nation's 10 largest markets showed the
effective annual yield available on money market accounts was 6.61
percent as of Wednesday, unchanged from a week earlier.
   The North Palm Beach, Fla.-based newsletter said the effective
annual yield available on special savings accounts, called Super
NOW accounts, was unchanged at 5.14 percent.
   Bank Rate Monitor said the effective annual yield on six-month
certificates of deposit was 9.34 percent, up from 9.27 percent the
previous week. Yields were 9.50 percent on 1-year CDs, up from 9.45
percent; 9.32 percent on 2{-year CDs, up from 9.31 percent; and
9.21 percent on 5-year CDs, unchanged.
</TEXT>
