<FIRST>u f AM-Eastern-Deadlock     04-13 0626</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eastern-Deadlock,0647</SECOND>
<HEAD>Experts Say Sale Is Only Way To Break Eastern's Labor Impasse</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Eastern Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARIANN CAPRINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A sale of strike-torn Eastern Airlines
increasingly is seen as the only way to resolve its deadlocked
labor dispute, according to many experts who also cautioned
Thursday that employees will discover they may have lost the fight
no matter who ends up owning the carrier.
   Interested buyers following in the footsteps of Peter V.
Ueberroth are likely to demand at least the same $210 million in
labor concessions included in his aborted takeover plan.
   ``Concessions are just the starting point'' for any further
talks, said Paul Tiffany, a professor of management at the
University of Pennsylvania's Wharton School.
   Observers see a sale of the carrier as a face-saving device for
unions that have locked themselves in a seething battle they have
has focused almost entirely on the perceived evils of one man _
Frank Lorenzo, chairman of Eastern parent Texas Air Corp.
   ``Of recent labor disputes, I can't think of any that is so
personalized, and that one-dimensional perspective is wrong,''
Tiffany said.
   ``A sale will allow the employees to say they were fighting for
a principle,'' he said. A period of worker euphoria will follow any
sale of the carrier but once that fades, Tiffany predicted,
employees could realize they've lost economically.
   After the Ueberroth deal collapsed, Eastern reiterated a plan to
return to the skies as a scaled-down company roughly half its
pre-strike size. If a buyer emerges who will save even some of the
jobs Eastern would cut, ``it's a big gain'' for the unions, said
bankruptcy attorney Richard Lieb.
   But there is no guarantee a new owner would preserve a
significant number of jobs. Harvard Business School professor
Janice McCormick said the dispute ``is way past the point of
victory for anybody.''
   The Ueberroth deal collapsed due to an impasse over the union
demand that a court-appointed trustee replace Lorenzo in charge of
Eastern until the carrier's reorganization plan was approved _ a
demand experts said could prove to be the unions' biggest mistake.
   ``As the transaction was originally structured, it had so many
escape hatches ... that there was no assurance the airline would
end up back in hands of Lorenzo'' if Ueberroth backed out, said
pilots' attorney Bruce Simon.
   But appointing a trustee sends a more subtle message to those
versed in such legal maneuvers.
   Trustees, while very rarely appointed, typically are named when
there has been ``fraud, dishonesty, incompetence or gross
mismangement of a company'' or less frequently if it is in the
interest of creditors or stockholders, said James J. White, a
management professor at the University of Michigan in Ann Arbor.
   For example, in January 1988, a bankruptcy judge appointed a
trustee to run Sharon Steel Corp. because Chairman Victor Posner
failed to agree with creditors restaffing the board of directors.
   Posner had to repay Sharon $4.4 million which he had used to pay
legal fees in a tax evasion trial where he pleaded no contest.
   While White said he ``can't understand how the court could reach
the conclusion'' that there is fraud or dishonesty involved in
running Eastern, he noted the appointment of a trustee generally
casts a pall over management.
   If a successful buyer does not emerge, experts said, the unions
could be forced back into negotiations in time.
   ``After a long enough strike, everybody's views change,'' White
said, particularly as strikers face continued expenses and little
to no income.
   ``A fair number of (Eastern) employees are accustomed to a
fairly nice standard of living who are surely going to be in a
bind. Notwithstanding their dislike for Lorenzo, that will push
them'' to a settlement, White said.
</TEXT>
