<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     04-13 0542</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0561</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Falls; Gold Prices Rise</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede LONDON-BC</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar finished lower against major foreign
currencies in hectic trading Thursday, buffeted by a hike in
interest rates by a key European bank.
   Gold prices rose. Republic National Bank of New York quoted a
bid of $389.10 a troy ounce for gold, up $2.10 from Wednesday's
late bid.
   Dealers said a move by the Swiss National Bank to raise interest
rates got currency trading off to a chaotic start.
   ``The Swiss franc had been fairly weak against other currencies,
and this gave the signal that (the Swiss) didn't want it to
depreciate much further,'' said Bob Morrissey, a senior trader at
the Bank of Boston.
   Dealers sold dollars to buy the Swiss franc, which led the
downturn in the U.S. currency, Morrissey said.
   The gap between U.S. and European interest rates decreases when
rates rise overseas, decreasing the relative attractiveness of
dollar-denominated investments.
   Further rumors that the Bank of Japan might be next in line to
raise rates continued to pressure the dollar, said Stephen
Flanagan, a vice president at Manufacturers Hanover Trust Co.
   A West German cabinet change also helped boost the European
currencies. The replacement of West German Finance Minister Gerhard
Stoltenberg by Theo Waigel spurred European currencies because
Waigel opposes a 10 percent withholding tax on interest income. The
tax has prompted an outflow of investment money from West Germany
since it was imposed Jan. 1.
   Traders said U.S. activity quieted down later in the session in
anticipation of Friday's release of trade figures for February and
producer prices for March, a key inflation indicator.
   In Tokyo, the dollar slipped to 132.80 Japanese yen from 132.85
yen on Wednesday. In London late Thursday, the dollar was trading
at 132.35. In New York, the dollar finished at 132.05 yen, down
from 133.03 yen on Wednesday.
   In London, the British pound rose to $1.7010 late Thursday from
Wednesday's late $1.6925. In New York, sterling rose to $1.6982
from $1.6922 late Wednesday.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late
Wednesday's rates, included: 1.8723 West German marks, down from
1.8828; 1.6433 Swiss francs, down from 1.6648; 6.3395 French
francs, down from 6.3615; 1,374.13 Italian lire, down from
1,380.50, and 1.1870 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1896.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late
Wednesday's rates, included: 1.8720 West German marks, down from
1.8857; 1.6422 Swiss francs, down from 1.6645; 6.3335 French
francs, down from 6.3690; 2.1080 Dutch guilders, down from 2.1270;
1,374.00 Italian lire, down from 1,381.00; 1.1875 Canadian dollars,
down from 1.1887.
   Gold bullion prices strengthened in U.S. and foreign trading.
   In New York, gold for current delivery settled at $390.30 a troy
ounce on the Commodity Exchange, up from Wednesday's $388.20.
   In London, gold traded at a late bid of $388.75 a troy ounce, up
from $387.25 late Wednesday. The late bid in Zurich was $389.15 an
ounce, up from $387.30. Earlier in Hong Kong, gold closed at a bid
of $387.75, up from Wednesday's $384.15.
   Silver bullion traded late in London at a bid of $5.87 a troy
ounce, down from $5.89. Silver for current delivery on New York's
Comex settled at $5.867 a troy ounce, down from $5.868 on Wednesday.
</TEXT>
