<FIRST>u f AM-OilPrices     04-13 0236</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices,0245</SECOND>
<HEAD>Energy Futures Prices Fall</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Energy futures prices retreated Thursday, as
some traders decided to cash in their holdings to take advantage of
recent price rises.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the May contract for West
Texas Intermediate, the benchmark grade of U.S. crude, fell 35
cents to close the day at $20.29 a barrel. Other contract months
also fell.
   Among refined products, unleaded gasoline for May delivery fell
1.30 cents to 68.81 cents a gallon and heating oil for May delivery
lost 1.06 cents to 52.14 cents a gallon.
   William Byers, an oil analyst for Bear, Stearns &amp; Co., said the
decline was led by the gasoline contracts which have been rising on
a combination of seasonal demands and worries about the impact of
the Alaskan oil spill.
   ``Gasoline was the catalyst for the decline. There was some
profit-taking in the gasoline group and that depressed crude and
heating oil. It put some psychological pressure on the rest of the
energy group,'' he said.
   But Byers said trading was quiet and most of the price erosion
occurred in the afternoon.
   Peter Beutel, who follows oil prices for Elders Futures Inc.,
said the selling was motivated by technical conditions in the
energy market.
   ``It seems the overriding sentiment in the market is that prices
have gone as far as they can go on this particular runup,'' he said.
</TEXT>
