<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp     04-13 0691</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0714</SECOND>
<HEAD>Palladium Hits 8-Year High; Platinum Up Sharply</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Palladium futures prices soared to an 8-year high Thursday as
new reports on room-temperature nuclear fusion experiments
triggered a rally in platinum futures that drove that metal's price
to its highest level in four months.
   The explosive price gains occurred as scientists at the
University of Washington and in the Soviet Union said they had at
least partially duplicated a University of Utah experiment in which
researchers claim to have used a rod of palladium and coil of
platinum to harness for the first time the nuclear reaction that
fuels the stars.
   On other markets, gold futures rose while silver futures were
mixed; petroleum futures plunged; grains and soybeans were mixed;
and livestock and meat futures were mixed.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, platinum settled $24 to $25
higher with the most active contract, for delivery in July, at
$558.30 a troy ounce. Platinum for spot delivery finished at
$555.80, the highest settlement for a spot platinum contract since
Dec. 15.
   Palladium, a whitish metal produced as a byproduct of platinum
and nickel mining, settled $5.50 to $9.85 higher with the active
June contract at $179.65 a troy ounce and the spot April contract
at $184. Spot prices for palladium have not been above $180 since
late 1980.
   Palladium prices have risen steadily since late March, when
chemists B. Stanley Pons of the University of Utah and his research
partner Martin Fleischmann of the University of Southampton,
England, stunned the scientific world by announcing their
cold-fusion findings. At least four other groups of researchers
have since confirmed the results, at least partially.
   Market speculators are betting that if the process proves
commercially viable, demand for platinum and palladium will
increase sharply.
   Platinum prices have been slower to respond to the fusion news
than palladium, partly because platinum prices tend to shadow the
gold market, which has been in sluggish period.
   Despite its positive fundamentals, which include a long-term
outlook for extremely tight supplies, the platinum market was
unable to rally until the palladium market gave it a push, said
Richard Levine, vice president of precious-metal and
foreign-exchange trading with Elders Futures Inc. in New York.
   ``All this reflects is that you're in a good, solid bull market
in the platinum group,'' Levine said.
   On New York's Commodity Exchange, gold settled $2.10 to $2.20
higher with June at $394.20 a troy ounce; silver was 0.5 cent lower
to 0.5 cent higher with May at $5.89 a troy ounce.
   Petroleum futures fell sharply on the New York Merc as gasoline
traders took profits after four straight gains of strong gains.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 19 cents to 40 cents
lower with May at $20.29 a barrel; heating oil was .91 cent to 1.15
cents lower with May at 52.14 cents a gallon; unleaded gasoline was
.30 cent to 1.30 cents lower with May at 68.81 cents a gallon.
   Wheat for May delivery advanced moderately on the Chicago Board
of Trade amid persistent rumors that the Soviet Union had purchased
a large quantity of U.S. wheat for near-term delivery.
   The National Weather Service's prediction for normal
precipitation in most of the Midwest next week weighed on corn and
soybean prices.
   Wheat settled unchanged to 5} cents higher with May at $4.08} a
bushel; corn was 1} cents lower to 1 cent higher with May at $2.68}
a bushel; oats were 2{ cents to 5 cents higher with May at $1.84 a
bushel; soybeans were 2 cents lower to \ cent higher with May at
$7.27 a bushel.
   Cattle futures finished mostly lower while pork futures ended
narrowly mixed in lackluster trading on the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange.
   Live cattle were .48 cent lower to .15 cent higher with June at
70.95 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .15 cent to .75 cent lower
with May at 75.95 cents a pound; live hogs were .05 cent lower to
.20 cent higher with June at 40.12 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were .20 cent lower to .20 cent higher with May at 33.35
cents a pound.
</TEXT>
