<FIRST>r f BC-NewCigarette     04-13 0308</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-New Cigarette,0321</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lorillard Introduces Lemon-Tasting Cigarette in 3 Markets</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   This city proved to be an inhospitable test
market for Premier, R.J. Reynolds' gamble on a high-tech, smokeless
cigarette, but it's one of three cities chosen for test-marketing a
more conventional smoke.
   Lorillard Inc. on Thursday announced that its Spring Lemon
Lights would be sold in Phoenix, Milwaukee, and Hartford, Conn.,
before national introduction.
   Tucson, Phoenix and St. Louis were separate markets for Premier.
   Lorillard competitor R.J. Reynolds ended a five-month test of
Premier on March 1, saying that although consumer acceptance had
been poor, the idea might work in the future. Premier used a carbon
heat source to pull warm air over a flavor capsule containing dried
tobacco.
   Lorillard spokeswoman Sara R. Ridgway said the Premier failure
played no role in test-market selection.
   ``That was a different type of product. This is a standard old
cigarette. The difference is that it has a lemon taste,'' she said.
   Ms. Ridgway said Phoenix was considered a good test market
because of demographics and location. The desert metropolis is far
enough away from other cities to enable planners to analyze the
impact of advertising and response, she said.
   Roland D. Hammer, group brand manager for New York-based
Lorillard, said the new cigarettes would be available in menthol
and non-menthol, both in two sizes.
   He said they would be packaged in yellow, silver and red or
yellow, silver and green color schemes to convey the idea of a
lemon-flavored smoke.
   ``The `hint-of-lemon' taste is a light, refreshing sensation
that can easily be associated with springtime,'' Hammer said.
   The advertising campaign was created by Saatchi &amp; Saatchi,
featuring springtime themes and settings, Hammer said.
   Lorillard, which has manufacturing plants in Greensboro, N.C.,
and Danville, Va., also makes Kent, Triumph, Newport, True, Satin,
Old Gold and Max cigarette varieties.
</TEXT>
