<FIRST>r f AM-FreeportMcMoRan     04-13 0393</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Freeport McMoRan,0402</SECOND>
<HEAD>Natural Resources Company Announces Stock Repurchase</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JANET McCONNAUGHEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Freeport McMoRan Inc. offered up to $600
million Thursday for 15 million shares of its common stock _ or
about 21.8 percent of the shares outstanding.
   The natural resources company said it will buy the shares in
what is known as a Dutch auction, setting a single price between
$35 and $40 per share, based on the number and prices of shares
offered by stockholders.
   ``We felt that to spend ... between $525 million and $600
million for our own stock was an excellent investment,'' said Craig
Saporito, vice president and director of investor relations for
Freeport McMoRan.
   Companies often repurchase shares of stock to make the price
rise, discouraging unsolicited takeover offers. Freeport McMoRan
stock, $34.37{ Wednesday, closed at $37 Thursday on the New York
Stock Exchange.
   Stockholders who offered shares at or below the price set by
Freeport McMoRan will get that price in cash, said the company,
which owns majority interests of divisions which drill for oil, gas
and sulphur, mine gold, copper, diamonds and uranium, and work with
geothermal energy.
   ``Every time you put money in the ground, even though we've been
extremely successful of late, there's a risk,'' said Saporito. ``We
looked at a number of things and felt that that kind of investment
in our stock ... would benefit not only the company but the
shareholders who elected to tender and the shareholders who elected
to continue with us.''
   Even that was probably less than its worth, especially
considering Tuesday's announcements of major sulphur and copper
finds, said Terry H. Smith, vice president of the New Orleans-based
brokerage firm of Howard, Weill Inc.
   Tuesday, Freeport McMoRan announced that Freeport Egyptian
Sulphur Co. had found a 20 million ton sulphur deposit on a
concession in Egypt's North Sinai Desert. It also announced that
Freeport-McMoRan Copper Co. Inc. had increased the reserve estimate
for a mine in Irian Jaya, Indonesia, from 93 million metric tons to
118 million metric tons of ore yielding copper, gold and silver.
   ``Our appraised value for Freeport McMoRan prior to the
announced major discoveries of silver and copper was approximately
$40 per share. I am ... revising those numbers, and believe that
$40 may be low by as much as 50 percent,'' said Smith.
</TEXT>
