<FIRST>u f AM-Earns-Media 1stLd-Writethru f0284 04-13 0555</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Earns-Media, 1st Ld - Writethru, f0284,0570</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gannett Posts Profit Rise, Times Co. Down, Affiliated's Loss Narrows</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Recasts lead, ADDS 5 grafs to UPDATE with New York Times Co.
earnings. SUBS 2nd graf to CORRECT location of Gannett headquarters.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Gannett Co. Inc. said Thursday its first-quarter earnings edged
up 1.3 percent, the New York Times Co. said its first-quarter
profit declined and Affiliated Publications Inc. reported a smaller
first-quarter loss.
   Gannett, which is based in Arlington, Va., reported record
first-quarter earnings of $74.9 million, or 47 cents per share,
compared to $74 million, or 46 cents per share, during the same
period the previous year.
   The latest results reflected a pretax gain of $9 million on the
sale of two newspapers. The 1988 results included a $45 million
gain from the sale of Gannett's interest in Cowles Media.
   Operating revenues grew 8 percent to $817.9 million in the first
quarter, compared to $757.9 last year.
   Operating income rose 24 percent to $145.0 million from $117.0
million a year earlier.
   ``Operating income posted its strongest advance since the first
quarter of 1984, reflecting a stronger retail advertising
environment and favorable supply conditions for newsprint,'' John
J. Curley, Gannett chairman, president and chief executive officer,
said in a letter to stockholders.
   He said the gain in operating income resulted from stronger
local advertising demand and effective expense controls. Newspaper
advertising increased 7 percent during the quarter, and circulation
revenues increased 4 percent. Broadcasting revenues rose 10
percent, and outdoor revenues increased 27 percent.
   Gannett publishes 85 daily newspapers, including USA Today, 35
non-daily newspapers and USA Weekend, a newspaper magazine. The
company also operates 10 television stations, 16 radio stations,
Gannett News Services and the largest outdoor advertising company
in North America.
   Boston-based Affiliated said it lost $9.9 million in the first
quarter compared with a loss of $14.4 million in the same period a
year earlier.
   First-quarter revenue rose 2.9 percent to $130.4 million, up
from $126.7 million a year earlier.
   The latest results include charges of $18.9 million related to
Affiliated's equity investment in McCaw Cellular Communications
Inc. compared with charges of $25.3 million a year earlier.
   Affiliated owns The Boston Globe, which ``continues to
experience softness in advertising linage, particularly in
classified, which has negatively affected advertising revenues,''
said Affiliated Chairman William O. Taylor.
   Affiliated also owns Billboard Publications Inc., and Taylor
said he is pleased with the results from the specialty publishing
business.
   The New York Times Co. said its first-quarter profit dropped to
$33.5 million, or 42 cents a share, from $45.5 million, or 56 cents
a share, in the first quarter of 1988.
   Revenue for the 1989 period totaled $423.1 million, up from
$416.9 million a year earlier.
   ``As we had anticipated, first-quarter earnings were down
significantly,'' said Arthur Ochs Sulzberger, chairman and chief
executive. ``The business climate in New York remains uncertain;
However, we continue to believe that 1989 will be a satisfactory
year.''
   Operating profit dropped 15 percent in the company's newspaper
group, due principally to lower ad volume at the Times, the company
said. The group also inlcudes 35 regional newspapers and a
one-third interest in the International Herald Tribune.
   Operating profit also was off sharply at the company's magazine
group, to $700,000 from $7.3 million a year earlier, the company
said.
</TEXT>
