<FILEID>AP-NR-04-13-89 0146EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-CarsonPirie-Bergner     04-13 0358</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Carson Pirie-Bergner,0370</SECOND>
<HEAD>Carson Pirie Board Rejects Offer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Carson Pirie Scott &amp; Co. said Wednesday that its
board of directors rejected a $282 million offer from P.A. Bergner
&amp; Co. to merge the two Midwest department store chains.
   P.A. Bergner, a Swiss-owned chain with headquarters in
Milwaukee, sought to acquire Carson Pirie of Chicago for at least
$20 a share in cash or an unspecified combination of cash, stock
and notes.
   ``Carson's board of directors has unanimously determined that it
is not in the best interest of ... shareholders, employees,
customers, suppliers and other constituencies,'' Peter S. Willmott,
chairman, president and chief executive of the company, said in a
letter to P.A. Bergner.
   ``During the last two years, Carson Pirie ... has returned the
company to retailing as its core business and provided Carson's
shareholders with a cash payment of more than $30 a share,'' he
wrote. ``The best interests of Carson's shareholders will be served
by the company pursuing an independent course.''
   Alan R. Anderson, chairman and chief executive of P.A. Bergner,
said he was disappointed with the decision.
   ``Our offer, after all, represents a 52 percent premium over the
price at which Carson's stock has traded during 1989'' before the
offer was made.
   Carson Pirie's stock closed unchanged at $21.37{ a share
Wednesday on the New York Stock Exchange.
   ``We have stated our willingness to meet with Mr. Willmott and
his financial and legal advisors to negotiate a definite
acquisition agreement at a fair price that would benefit Carson
Pirie Scott's shareholders, employees and customers,'' Anderson
said.
   ``We can only wonder what alternatives the board can propose to
shareholders to maximize the worth of their investment in a way
that is comparable to the values contained in our proposed merger
proposal,'' Anderson said.
   Carson Pirie lost $38.8 million in the fiscal year ended Jan.
31., much of it from its catalog operations. It owns 33 department
stores in Illinois, Iowa, Indiana and Minnesota, as well as 388
County Seat specialty stores in Midwest and Sunbelt states and 23
Arcadia stores in Chicago.
   P.A. Bergner operates 31 department stores in Illinois and
Wisconsin.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
